<HEADLINE>
TEXAN IS HOPEFUL FOR OPEN SPOT ON U.S. CYCLING TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five past Olympians spice the U.S. roster, but the fate of
Frisco, Texas, resident Jeff Labauve remained in doubt as USA
Cycling announced its track roster last week.
</P>
<P>
   Medal winners Marty Nothstein of Trexlertown, Pa., and Erin
Hartwell of Indianapolis, Ind., head the list of former Olympians
to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   Nothstein won a silver medal in the match sprint event at the
1996 Atlanta Olympics, while Hartwell earned a bronze at the '92
Games and a silver in '96 in the kilometer time trial.
</P>
<P>
   The top performers at the U.S. Olympic Trials for Track Cycling
at the Frisco Superdrome in May were named to the U.S. Long Team
and competed in World Cup events during the past six weeks. The
final announcement of the Olympic team _ 11 men and three women _
came Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Making the women's team was two-time Olympic speed skating medal
winner Chris Witty of Park City, Utah. She will attempt to become
only the second U.S. athlete to medal in both the summer and winter
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Joining her on the women's team are Tanya Lindenmuth of
Trexlertown and Erin Veenstra-Mirabella of Colorado Springs, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The final men's sprint position remains open and will be
determined no later than Aug. 1. USA Cycling officials _ and
sprinter Labauve _ are awaiting the fate of veteran Johnny Bairos
of Redlands, Calif., who suffered a horrific crash at a World Cup
event three weeks ago in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Bairos was competing in a match sprint race and riding outside
of three other cyclists when he was forced up and over the track.
According to eyewitnesses, he fell more than 20 feet and landed
face-first, 30 feet away from the velodrome.
</P>
<P>
   Bairos, 22, fractured his jaw in two places, broke his right
kneecap, severely bruised his right thigh and suffered fractures in
his right and left sinus cavities. He has had to undergo two
surgeries since the accident.
</P>
<P>
   USA Cycling officials remain hopeful that Bairos can recover and
compete in the Sydney Games. If he can't, Labauve is expected to
replace him on the U.S. squad. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
