<SLUG> BC-BBO-MULHOLLAND-BRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULHOLLAND'S BEST OUTING FOLLOWS WORST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He came into Saturday's game ranked fifth in the National League
in fewest walks per nine innings (1.9), making Terry Mulholland his
own tough act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Mulholland exited, he had 1.9-upped himself, not
issuing a walk in eight innings in earning his second win against
the Red Sox this season.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from his last start.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday in Atlanta, he absorbed one of the worst
shellackings of a major league career that began 14 years ago in
San Francisco. The lefthander was touched for 10 hits and nine runs
by Montreal in a 17-1 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, though, he survived some early scares and he didn't
hurt himself with the free pass. All seven Boston base runners had
to earn their own way on against Mulholland, who finished with a
flourish, retiring the last eight batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a pitcher who started the game with a 6.06 ERA.
Opponents were batting .324 against him. He had given up a
career-high 13 hits three times this season and now he had to face
a team that had decimated Minnesota pitching earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I definitely went out and used my entire repertoire
today,'' said Mulholland, who improved his record to 9-8 while
lowering his ERA to 5.71. ``It's not an easy task to pitch to that
lineup over there and I was very effective in using both halves of
the plate. I was primarily going away with my sinker and then
working the guys in with cutters and curveballs down. It was a
matter of mixing it up enough to where they didn't get comfortable
looking for one pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was a moment in the Boston fourth when Mulholland was
bending and about ready to break.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Frye and Carl Everett had grounded singles to left and
Nomar Garciaparra, who had doubled off Mulholland in the second,
was up. Garciaparra went after the first pitch, sending a grounder
to third baseman Chipper Jones, who turned it into a 5-3 double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland got out of the inning by striking out Morgan
Burkhart. After Troy O'Leary singled to open the fifth, Mulholland
promptly picked him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The double play was very big and Chipper made a great play,''
he said. ``That was a big lift for me because there was a good
chance it was going to be a big inning for them and I may not have
been around after that.''
</P>
<P>
   The pickoff? ``When the ball came back to the infield, I was
walking back to the mound and (O'Leary) had already taken his lead
prior to me getting on the rubber, so I thought maybe I can catch
him a little flat-footed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That sequence helped hold the Red Sox at bay in what was to
become, according to Braves manager Bobby Cox, ``The best game
Terry's pitched all season.''
</P>
<P>
   But the manager also felt that his starter was ``gassed'' after
eight innings of work, so it was John Rocker time with the four-run
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have gone back out for the ninth,'' said Mulholland,
``but we needed to get a couple of guys right in the bullpen and it
was a good situation for Rock to come in and start the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   After Mulholland's 4 1/3 forgetful innings against Montreal,
pitching coach Leo Mazzone had a few things on his mind he didn't
want Mulholland to forget, specifically his tempo and pitch
selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry moves fast as it is,'' said Mazzone, ``but sometimes you
can move too fast and get ahead of yourself. Terry quieted
everything down today, from start to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   And quieted some Red Sox bats in the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
