<SLUG> BC-BBO-PAXTON-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAWFORD SENT BACK TO PAWTUCKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three days ago, Paxton Crawford gleefully flew out of Minnesota
with a prized trophy in his pocket: the game ball from his first
Red Sox victory.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Crawford was hauling a sadder payload _ all his
belongings back to Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   In a roster move certain to rile anxious Sox fans, manager Jimy
Williams informed the promising rookie it was time to go.
</P>
<P>
   Despite several shaky outings recently by Boston's regular
starters, there is no room for Crawford, who left town with an ERA
of 2.19 in his two starts since he was summoned from Pawtucket July
1 to replace the injured Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our roster,'' Williams said. ``He came up for Pedro,
and Pedro is coming off'' the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Martinez does not come off the disabled list until
Thursday. For a day, at least, Crawford's demotion could allow the
Red Sox to recall lefthanded reliever Sang-Hoon Lee, who struck out
the side for Pawtucket Friday in relief of former Boston starter
Brian Rose. The Sox temporarily depleted their bullpen by using two
lefthanded relievers in Saturday's 5-1 loss to the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   For at least one rotation after the All-Star break, Williams
indicated he will stick with his regular starters and said the
demotion will allow Crawford to start Thursday for Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, 22, the epitome of a hard-throwing, easygoing country
pitcher, took the news in stride. ``I'm not worried about it or mad
at anybody or nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's outing, Crawford clinched Boston's four-game sweep
of Minnesota by outdueling the Twins' $36 million ace Brad Radke,
allowing one run on six hits and no walks in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford pitched well enough to win his big-league debut July 1
against Chicago, yielding only two earned runs in 5 1/3 innings.
However, he took the loss amid a series of misplays by his former
Pawtucket teammate, Izzy Alcantara, which helped the White Sox
score four unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid did fine,'' Williams said of Crawford's two outings.
``But we only have so many players with options. We have these
other pitchers who are starting after the break and he has continue
to start, too,'' in Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a young kid,'' Crawford said, ``and they've got some
veterans on the team who deserve to pitch. They have worked so hard
and so long for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams seemed resigned to some criticism of Crawford's
demotion. ``We can only do things one step at a time, just one step
at a time,'' he said. ``You folks might have other ideas, but we
have to do things the way we think is the proper way to do them at
this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford received the news in a closed-door meeting with
Williams and pitching coach Joe Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if they were going to tell me I was staying or
going,'' he said. ``But I was ready either way. I don't think my
heart rate even went up a beat. I'm getting kind of used to this
all-of-a-sudden-something-happens stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated before his makeshift locker, Crawford said, ``I'm not
going to worry about the money or the bigger paycheck. It's nice,
but as long as I have a uniform on and as long as I pitch, I'm not
worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was the relocation to address. ``I've got to pack
up my stuff, throw it in my truck, and go again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the packing would be a cinch. ``I still have three plastic
trunks in my truck full of clothes,'' he said. ``I never really had
time to unpack here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
