u s BC-BBO-ONBALL-SECONDEFFO     07-09 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ONBALL-SECONDEFFORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND EFFORT IS SOX' PRIORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With only one game left before the All-Star break it comes down
to this: The Red Sox need to work harder than ever to remain a
contender in the American League East. They are slipping fast and
need to turn it around . . . or else.
</P>
<P>
   After a four-game sweep at Minnesota, the Sox have regressed.  &UR;  &LR; 
With Saturday's 5-1 loss to the Atlanta Braves at Fenway, their
second straight defeat, Boston is just a game over .500 (42-41) and
19-19 at home. Last year, the Sox were 13 games above .500 (47-34)
at the All-Star break and locked into second place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing we have to do is go out there and battle our way
through the tough times,'' said catcher Jason Varitek. ``Right now,
guys are struggling. We have to find a way to do some things, get
more into ballgames, create new pitches, and throw more pitches.
You can't sit back and wait for people. We have to find a way to
get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to put it all together for a long stretch. We haven't
been able to do that just yet. That time is going to come. But you
know, there are a lot of guys putting in a lot of work, trying to
better themselves and better the team.''
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of sad faces in the clubhouse, but none were
making excuses. Twelve players, including ace Pedro Martinez, are
on the disabled list, and that is understood. But it still hurts to
sweep Minnesota by scoring a ton of runs, and then get slammed by
the Braves, who are surviving their own pennant race against the
Mets and seem primed for a return to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we played in Minnesota was a nice way to play,'' said
Varitek. ``But not just because we scored a lot of runs. That was a
series in which we were able to go about our business. We have to
keep that attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems on the field have had a lot to do with the
injuries. Minus Trot Nixon and Darren Lewis, the outfield won't be
mistaken for a Gold Glove trio, not with Jeff Frye and Brian
Daubach plugging the holes. Ed Sprague has yet to pay dividends at
third base. Pedro may not be completely healthy for the rest of the
season, and Bret Saberhagen has yet to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   World Series talk has slowed since early May, the last time
Boston won a home series (White Sox, May 8-10). Interleague play
hasn't helped at all _ the Sox are just 3-8 against National League
foes after Saturday's setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's not from lack of effort,'' said manager Jimy
Williams. ``We just couldn't score (Saturday). We had some guys up
in the right situations and it just didn't work. (The Braves) made
some pitches when they had to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox try to salvage the series finale Sunday against Greg
Maddux. But even a win may not be enough to brighten the postseason
outlook. Jeff Fassero needs to recover from his dead arm. Somebody,
perhaps Bernard Gilkey, needs to fill Nixon's shoes if the right
fielder's absence is prolonged.
</P>
<P>
   One thing we do know is that the second half is going to hinge
on the Martinez brothers, and both seem more than up to the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half we should do better,'' said Ramon, who was
saddled with the loss Saturday despite allowing just two earned
runs in six innings. ``Like today, I knew that if I kept it close
we had a chance to score some runs and we didn't. That happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
