A7027 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-REDSOX-BRAVES-BOS     07-09 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REDSOX-BRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX DROP SECOND TO BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's probably not a problem Jimy Williams will point out to John
Harrington between the CEO's trips to City Hall and the State
House.
</P>
<P>
   By now, it is commonly understood that Williams is the type of
guy who would sooner chew off his own arm than complain to his boss
about anything.
</P>
<P>
   But this idea of playing the Atlanta Braves just before the
All-Star break has got to go.
</P>
<P>
   Things to do before taking a three-day vacation:
</P>
<P>
   1) Turn down the AC.
</P>
<P>
   2) Water the plants.
</P>
<P>
   3) Face Greg Maddux, the four-time Cy Young Award winner, after
having already lost back-to-back games at Fenway Park to lefthanded
starters (Tom Glavine and Terry Mulholland) for the first time
since April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we faced Maddux last year just before the break,
too,'' Sox catcher Jason Varitek said after the Sox fell, 5-1, to
the 37-year-old Mulholland and the defending National League champs
before 33,311 dismayed patrons on Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely. Mulholland's performance Saturday (8 innings, 1 run,
7 hits, 0 walks) came on the heels of Friday's 5-3 win by Glavine,
the local lad who showed no mercy on his former heroes. It also
foreshadows Sunday afternoon's scheduled performance by Maddux, who
will be attempting to send the Sox to their fourth series sweep
this season and third consecutive weekend of having their heads
handed to them.
</P>
<P>
   Last July in Atlanta, on the Sunday afternoon just before
baseball went on holiday, Maddux and the Braves whipped the Sox,
8-1, sending them to their fifth loss in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll get lucky and beat him this time,'' Varitek said
sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough the Sox may be stuck with the Braves as their
interleague partner in perpetuity. Except for those Boston Braves
diehards who still carry faded Sibby Sisti baseball cards in their
battered wallets, most folks in Boston would just as soon see Team
Turner beating up somebody else on cable than the Olde Towne Team
in the Fens.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves and Sox have met 17 times since interleague play
began in 1997. So far, it's Braves 12, Sox 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like playing against them,'' Varitek insisted. ``I enjoy
playing the good teams. There isn't anybody here who doesn't enjoy
playing the good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the innocence of youth. A more world-weary view was offered
by Sox lefthander Jeff Fassero, who came out of the bullpen for the
first time this season and had reason to wish he'd never popped his
head out. In the eighth, an inning after reliever Bryce Florie
walked Chipper Jones with the bases loaded to break a 1-1 tie,
Fassero gave up a two-run home run to Javy Lopez, the Braves
catcher who was swinging one-handed, to make it 4-1, then
surrendered Andruw Jones's 23d home run in the ninth for Atlanta's
final run.
</P>
<P>
   Both were Fenway Park specials, fly balls that carried over the
left-field wall, but that was of little consolation to Fassero, who
with Randy Johnson in Seattle in 1997 formed the last pair of
lefthanders to beat the Sox here in consecutive starts. It did
nothing for Ramon Martinez, either, whose record is now 6-5 even
though he held the Braves at bay for six innings-plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fastballs were outs, the two forkballs were home runs,''
Fassero said. ``The Green Monster giveth, and the Green Monster
taketh away. Take away a foot, and those balls are singles. In a
bigger ballpark, those are two fly balls.''
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that, Fassero observed, is this misguided notion that
the Sox and Braves were meant for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why we should have to play them six
times,'' Fassero said, dismissing the historical context as a
reason to manufacture a rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't Philadelphia be our rivals or Montreal our rivals?
The Braves have been the best team in the '90s. Why should we play
them? Playing a team three times or six times doesn't make a
rivalry. The teams in our division are our rivals.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, of course, Atlanta isn't the only team that has made
the Sox look overmatched. The Sox are 3-8 in interleague play, and
they're now a .500 team at home (19-19), where they haven't won a
series since taking two out of three from the White Sox May 8-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves came into the weekend with the worst earned run
average in the National League for the first week of July (5.81),
but recovered nicely against the Sox. Especially Mulholland, last
seen on the losing end of a 17-1 game against the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, hits allowed by a pitcher can be a misleading stat.
David Wells began play having allowed more hits than any pitcher in
the American League (140, a phat total by anyone's calculation),
but the Blue Jays' don't-call-me-portly lefthander leads the majors
in wins with 14.
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland, meanwhile, began play with a yield of 145 hits, most
by any pitcher in the majors. Yet, for the second time this season,
he proved unfathomable to Sox hitters, who three times had two hits
in an inning but scored only once.
</P>
<P>
   When Mulholland faced the Red Sox in Atlanta last June 10, he
threw five scoreless innings in a 6-0 romp in Turner Field before
coming out with a strained groin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a good cutter, and he hides the ball pretty well,''
Varitek said. ``And tonight, he got ahead of all the hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday afternoon, Maddux is likely to offer more of the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be here,'' Williams said. ``We'll definitely show up
tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
