u s BC-BBO-BRAVES-BREAK-BOS &LR;      07-09 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAVES-BREAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES EYE STRONG FINISH BEFORE BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Braves, no matter what they were doing, had only one eye on
their task. Those eating had the one eye on their food but the
other on the television. Those dressing had one eye on the sock on
their foot and the other on the Mets-Yankees game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we go, here we go, here we go . . . we got action!'' a
Brave shouted as the Mets' Mike Piazza was conked in the head by a
pitch from the Yankees' Roger Clemens. ``We got serious action!''
The Braves locker room at Fenway Park quickly grew louder.
</P>
<P>
   Braves catcher Javy Lopez also had one eye on the TV as he
explained how he had hit his home run off the Red Sox' Jeff Fassero
in the eighth inning more or less one-handed, adding insult to the
injury of Fassero's poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to finish strong before the All-Star break,'' Lopez
said just before Clemens threw the pitch that knocked out Piazza.
``Now is the time to do it because now the Yankees are doing the
job for us on the Mets. So I guess this is the opportunity for us
against the Red Sox to get ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Piazza went down, Lopez's eye had caught it all and his
reaction was instant. ``(Clemens) did it on purpose . . . Piazza
hit a home run twice off Clemens . . . that says it all.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves themselves had said it all with their second
consecutive comfortable win over the once-again hitless wonders
that are the Red Sox. The Braves have learned how to treat the
meek: beat them soundly.
</P>
<P>
   And Lopez was in the middle of it all, from calling the pitches
from Terry Mulholland that sent the Sox hitters back into their
pre-Minnesota funk, to his hit leading off the seventh that led to
the Braves' 2-1 lead, to his two-run homer on a 1-2 count in the
eighth that put the game far out of reach. John Rocker ended it all
with a 1-2-3 ninth that saw him go more to his curve ball than his
wild fast ball of Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been getting me with breaking pitches,'' Lopez said
when asked if he was surprised Boston pitchers keep throwing him
breaking balls when he twice beat the Red Sox last year off
breaking pitches. ``It all depends on what I'm looking for on that
particular pitch. Fassero threw me a split-finger and I hit it only
so-so . . . but good enough to hit it out of the ballpark. I ended
up with only one hand on the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Lopez had the one-handed homer and three hits, it was
Chipper Jones's at-bat with the bases loaded and two out in the
seventh of a tie game that quietly accomplished almost as much as
Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Sox reliever Bryce Florie had just struck out a flailing Andruw
Jones with one out, bringing up Jones. Jones came through a with a
``quality at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Florie from San Diego and he's a hard sinker-slider
guy,'' Jones said. ``He'd gotten me out (Friday night) on a slider
and his bread-and-butter is that hard sinker to get you to hit the
ball on the ground. I was thinking, `You got to make him get the
ball up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jones nearly cleared the bases on a first swing against Florie
when his drive down the left field line landed in that spacious 2
feet of foul territory between the line and the left field seats.
Florie got ahead of him, but Jones eventually worked the count to
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had put a real good swing on that first ball that I hit down
the left field line and it barely hit foul,'' said Jones. ``So I
felt like I was on it pretty good and, on that 3-2 pitch, he tried
to throw that sinker down. I had to make him get the ball up, and
he never did.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones took the pitch, saying ``you've got to take what God gives
you,'' and ``luckily that sinker fell low of the strike zone. It
was way down, no question.'' Jones walked to first, Lopez trotted
home from third with the go-ahead run and the Braves once again
were taking care of business against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the first two games of the series is not enough for
these Braves. ``(Sunday) is a big game for us because we don't want
to go into the break on a losing note,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Especially against the meek of the bat.
</P>
</TEXT>
