<HEADLINE>
ANGELS DEPEND ON POWER PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mike Scioscia didn't apologize exactly for
another home run blitz by the Anaheim Angels, but the manager sure
made it sound that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I keep saying we're more than just a home run team,
the more I'm proven wrong,'' Scioscia said Saturday after the
Angels hammered four more homers in beating Colorado 6-2 in an
interleague game before a crowd of 22,958 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Angels' third win in a row, jumping them five games
above .500 for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Colorado is going the other way. Monday the Rockies
were in first place in the National League West. Since then they've
dropped six in a row, including the last two to the Angels, and
fallen into third place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a powerful lineup,'' Scioscia said. ``We've been able
to shut them down two games, and that's big.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hill (5-5), who failed to make it out of the second inning
in his last start, this time pitched into the sixth inning, then
turned it over to a bullpen that blanked the Rockies on one hit in
the final 3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Mike Holtz pitched out of a mini-jam in the sixth,
Shigetoshi Hasegawa followed with two solid innings, then Troy
Percival hurled a 1-2-3 ninth, striking out two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a well-pitched, well-played game,'' said Mo Vaughn, who
slugged one of the Angels' four home runs, a two-run blow in the
first when Anaheim jumped on Colorado's Brian Bohanan (4-6), the
one-time Dodger, for three quick runs.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad slugged Bohanan's second pitch of the game into the
right- field seats for his 17th homer, then Vaughn followed a walk
to Benji Gil with his 23rd. Bengie Molina, appearing as a
designated hitter for the first time in his career - maybe his
grand slam the night before earned him the job - hit his
career-best 11th homer in the fourth when the Angels went on top
5-2. And Garret Anderson, who struck out in his first two at-bats,
hit his 25th in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ninth time this season the Angels have hit four or more
homers in a game, tying a club record. They've now hit 140,
third-most in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   At the rate they're going, they'll wind up with 261, or 69 more
than the club-record 192 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It's not something Scioscia says he's thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll feel much better about this club when we get back to
manufacturing runs,'' said ScioscialIw}:!Q
</P>
</TEXT>
