<HEADLINE>
ON SECOND THOUGHT, ANGELS LINEUP HAS BIG HOLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Finding just the right No. 2 hitter to
complement his power-packed lineup has proved to be a seasonlong
search for Anaheim Angels manager Mike Scioscia, one he concedes he
hasn't completed yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a key spot,'' Scioscia said. ``With Mo (Vaughn), (Tim)
Salmon and (Garret) Anderson coming up right behind, the No. 2 guy
has got to get on base.''
</P>
<P>
   So far Scioscia has employed a half-dozen players in the No. 2
position. For now, he said, he'll stick with Benji Gil against
left-handed pitching and Kevin Stocker against right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go with the matchups until someone steps up in that
spot,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Adam Kennedy was Scioscia's choice to bat second
early on, but it didn't pan out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a young player and, right now, he's better down in the
lineup,'' Scioscia said of Kennedy, who was in what is now his
customary No. 8 spot in the order Saturday. ``He's still got a ways
to go (to bat No. 2).''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was in the No. 2 spot for 49 games, when his average
took a nosedive. But in his past 33 games, mostly hitting eighth,
he's climbed back, from .257 to .284.
</P>
<P>
   Others who have tried the No. 2 spot are Orlando Palmeiro (13
games), Scott Spiezio (5), Keith Luuloa (1), Stocker (10) and Gil
(9), who was 1 for 3 with a walk and a run scored Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Latest streak: The Angels are on their longest winning streak of
the season. Three in a row. For the sixth time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep playing well, it'll work out,'' said Vaughn, when
asked about the Angels' latest momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weve got to keep getting solid starting pitching, not just Ken
(Hill), but all of them, and we've got to keep generating things
offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn: Larry Walker, a two-time National League
batting champion and a career .312 hitter, was the Colorado DH on
Saturday and went hitless in four at-bats. That made the Rockies a
dismal 1 for 16 in five games using the DH. ... The Rockies' Mike
Lansing, with two hits Saturday, has 1,000 in his career. ... The
Angels' remarkable Darin Erstad, with a homer and a single, has 46
multi-hit games, most in the majors, and 12 in his past 17 games.
He has 140 hits for the season, most in the majors. He's hit safely
in 72 of the 86 games he's played. ...
</P>
<P>
   Anderson tied teammate Troy Glaus and Leon Wagner (1962) for
most homers by an Angel before the All-Star break (25). ... Bengie
Molina leads all major-league rookies in average (.306) and home
runs (11). ... Kennedy's fourth-inning double snapped an 0-for-9
streak. ... The Rockies, for all their woes - a 17-30 road record,
a season-high six-game losing streak and a first-to-third plunge in
the NL West in less than a week - still are assured of a winning
record at the All-Star break for only the second time in franchise
history (1995 was the other).
</P>
</TEXT>
