<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-NELSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT OF OWNER, PLAYERS HAS MAVS COACH FEELING YOUNG AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For Don Nelson, the desire to return to coaching
paralleled a child's motivation to play with his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching the Dallas Mavericks, like riding bikes, was fun.
Again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really the biggest reason why I returned,'' Nelson
said. ``I'm having a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Prodded to return by new Mavericks billionaire owner Mark Cuban,
the team's star players and his own family Nelson, 60, ended his
39-day coaching retirement on May 28.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone could see that Nelson didn't look like a tired,
disinterested coach ready to ride his nest egg into retirement. The
clock suddenly turned back 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm 40 again,'' joked Nelson, who started his run
of seven consecutive division titles with the Milwaukee Bucks two
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's having fun,'' Cuban said. ``That's the message
I've tried to bring to everybody here. You can have fun in this
game. It's a business, but you enjoy going to work, you're going to
do a lot better. I think Nellie is starting to have fun. I can see
it in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Nelson, Don's son and his lead assistant coach, credits
Cuban with re-energizing his father, who he simply calls ``Coach.''
To say that Cuban has shaken things up since he bought the team
would be like saying, there's no money in the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing was just sort of perfect for (Cuban) to come in and
just inject us with that special element that we needed,'' Donnie
said. ``Since he's been here, Coach has been a different person.
Part of it is we do have the freedom now to really go and get
things done. We always had the knowledge. We always knew the
angles, but we didn't have the capability.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson took nearly all the blame for the Mavs' often-dismal play
over the past three seasons. The Mavericks were 35-81 in Nelson's
first two years as coach. (He took over for fired coach Jim
Cleamons 16 games into 1997-98 season.)
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks seemed handcuffed by both the bottom-line business
philosophy of the previous ownership and, in the opinion of many,
by Nelson's several questionable personnel moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few periods in time where it was real
touch-and-go and we didn't know if we were gonna make it,'' Donnie
said. ``That's when Mark came in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Mark was faithful to us in our lowest hour,
we'll never forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire lit under the organization by Cuban didn't burn Nelson
out of town, as was widely speculated. Instead, Nelson, who
appeared to be going through the motions on his way to retirement,
heated up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He appreciates the ideas I've been able to introduce and the
new concepts, and it takes some of the pressure off him,'' Cuban
said. ``For instance, I've been doing a lot of dealing with agents
instead of him and he likes that.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading the bring-back-Nellie charge, were the Mavs' two
cornerstone players, All-Star guard Michael Finely and forward Dirk
Nowitzki. Nelson drafted a virtually unknown Nowitzki ninth overall
in the 1998 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said I wanted him back,'' said Nowitzki, who finished
second in the voting for the league's Most Improved Player award
last season. ``He's supported me through my whole career and he was
great even when I didn't play that good my first year. He gave me a
lot of minutes, which wasn't normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love him, love his style. He always has something new
and it's just great to play for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs' record after a dismal start _ 31-19 over the final 50
games, including a 9-1 April _ not only gave fans reason to be
optimistic for the coming season, it acted as time warp into the
1980s for Nelson. Donnie likened his father's mood over the final
three months to his run of seven consecutive division titles with
the Milwaukee Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win, you have fun,'' Donnie said. ``Coaches are like
players. Winning basketball games is what really our existence is
about as coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the public support from his players and Cuban made
the decision to come back easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant the world to me,'' Nelson said. ``The players were
the No. 1 reason why I came back and Mark was second.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Free-agent hopeful Gheorghe Muresan made his minicamp debut
Saturday at the Tom Landry Center. Assistant coach Donnie Nelson
said the 7-foot-7 center ``looked like the (Muresan) of old. He was
moving pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Muresan, who has missed 102 games the past two seasons with N`
</P>
</TEXT>
