<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS CAN PROVE HIS GREATNESS TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems only right that Pete Sampras will have to vanquish
Australian Patrick Rafter to make tennis history on Centre Court at
Wimbledon on Sunday. Sampras grew up emulating the Aussie greats of
an earlier era and has spent recent years closing in on what
mightbe the game's most important record _ career Grand Slam titles
_ which he now shares with an Aussie.
</P>
<P>
   A victory against Rafter would give Sampras his seventh
Wimbledon title in as many finals and his 13th Grand Slam title,
moving him ahead of Roy Emerson. It would also spark a new
discussion about whether Sampras is the best player of all time. In
tennis circles the consensus pick is Rod Laver, who Sampras
idolizes, one of two players in the men's game (Don Budge was the
other) to win the Grand Slam _ Wimbledon, French Open, U.S. Open
and Australian Open _ in the same year. Laver did it twice, in 1962
and '69.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great achievement, but remember this: when Laver did it
the first time, tennis was an amateur sport. In '69, the game was
in its professional infancy. Now, the money is big, competition is
tougher and some of the best athletes in the world can be found on
a tennis court. That wasn't the case then.
</P>
<P>
   Also, don't forget that three of the four Slams in Laver's era
were played on grass, with the French on clay. Winning the Grand
Slam now means excelling on grass, clay, and two distinctly
different hard-court surfaces. All that and the fact there are more
specialists in the game _ usually making a living on clay. It's one
of the reasons Sampras hasn't been able to win the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras doesn't make excuses. He will not draw any
comparisons between himself and Laver or diminish what Laver
accomplished. Instead, Sampras points out that because Laver turned
professional in the early 1960s before the four Grand Slams allowed
pros to play, he probably cost himself a slew of Slam titles. And
Sampras would not be playing for the Slam record Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That's typical Sampras, but it doesn't make for good copy. In
today's world, athletes have to talk smack, to have an attitude to
match their game. Even the reserved British crowds that attend
Wimbledon find Sampras boring. During the past two weeks, Sampras'
bid for the record 13th Slam title has been thoroughly overshadowed
by the Williams sisters, as well as the exploits of Andre Agassi,
Mark Philippoussis, Tim Henman, and others.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not as if Sampras has just been sailing along. He is
suffering from tendinitis above his left ankle and almost had to
withdraw during the first week, the pain and disappointment clearly
visible in his expression. Until Saturday, he had not practiced or
warmed up before any of his matches. It couldn't be scripted any
better in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, some his fellow players have suggested that Sampras is
faking, using the injury as psychological warfare or a crutch. If
he says he is injured, it makes him the underdog and lessens the
pressure and expectations. This is not the first time he has done
this, they say. Remember, for instance, how he was doubled over in
pain during a quarterfinal match against Alex Corretja at the U.S.
Open? And inexplicably won?
</P>
<P>
   How about when he collapsed after his first singles match
because of dehydration during the Davis Cup final against Russia
(on clay, no less), and came back to win the doubles and decisive
singles match on the final day. And there was the memorable scene
at the Australian Open when Sampras wept openly during his match
against Jim Courier because his coach Tim Gullikson was sent home
suffering from a cancerous brain tumor. He won that match too.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who has been around Sampras knows how down-to-earth
and unaffected he is. He hates phonies. While he has maintained a
good relationship with Agassi, for example, he isn't a real big fan
of Agassi's Las Vegas schtSBbSy3u$-qJ3 &Cx1f; e}i &UR; f &UR; 'W4,8o1vU$(R}~`y
</P>
</TEXT>
