<SLUG> BC-BBA-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADING WETTELAND MIGHT LEAVE GAPING HOLE IN RANGERS' BULLPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ He has heard the rumors. He is well aware of
the enticing price that he might bring.
</P>
<P>
   But let me suggest that it's going to take more than a few weeks
of trade winds to blow over John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   Trade Wetteland?
</P>
<P>
   Don't be so quick to say yes.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, his nightly emergence out of the Texas Rangers' bullpen
sometimes resembles an outtake from an Indiana Jones movie. Yes,
Mr. Wetteland sometimes makes liberal use of the ballpark's warning
track.
</P>
<P>
   So what's your point?
</P>
<P>
   When last we checked, Wetteland stood second in the American
League in successful save opportunities (21). From May 12 to June
5, he was perfect, a club record 13 in a row.
</P>
<P>
   After a ghastly run in April, Wetteland has been the most
consistent arm in manager Johnny Oates' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Trade him? If the Rangers plan to take the 2001 season
seriously, a more inspired solution might be to re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin indicated yesterday that, contrary
to published suggestions, he is not ruling out the possibility that
Wetteland will be back with the Rangers in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   What does Wetteland think, officially?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I need to have an official stance,'' he said
Saturday night, after a deep sigh.
</P>
<P>
   He has a job to do, Wetteland reminded. And that job curtails
fretting about anything beyond the task at hand _ tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want for next month, for next year, is not important,''
was the way Wetteland put it.
</P>
<P>
   He is hard not to like. Yet he can be so perplexing to try to
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland is either the most grounded player in the Rangers
clubhouse _ or the biggest enigma. Much like with his ninth-inning
pitching, a visitor has to peer between the lines.
</P>
<P>
   He is devoutly Christian, and he walks _ and pitches _ the talk.
While Rangers fans squirm and mutter, Wetteland has been known to
stoically scythe his way out of a self-induced bases-loaded jam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I do the job?'' Wetteland asks.
</P>
<P>
   It's as close to a gimme-a-break complaint as you'll get from
Wetteland. His even keel has set an example for the tender young
minds in the Rangers bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of those tender minds, which one exactly do you
propose should take Wetteland's place, provided he is traded before
the July 31 deadline?
</P>
<P>
   Tim Crabtree? Young Francisco Cordero? Jeff Zimmerman?
</P>
<P>
   If Wetteland is dealt away, who's to say that the Rangers won't
head to spring training next February with finding a closer their
No. 1 priority?
</P>
<P>
   Is potential free agent Robb Nen any better? Maybe, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Melvin has some gnawing nights ahead. The
Rangers' recent spate of success might not have dented the Seattle
Mariners' lead as much as prolonged the season's bitter end.
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as it would be to deal away a .340-plus hitter such
as David Segui, Melvin might want to weigh every offer. Segui has
not been a run-producing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, if someone inquires about the fickle arms of Esteban
Loaiza and Darren Oliver, Melvin needs to take the call.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wetteland case is different. A veteran who has seen his
success, who has saved 21 of 25 chances this season, is not readily
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever fate awaits, don't expect Wetteland to campaign one way
or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to avoid being self-serving,'' he said. ``Where I am,
what I'm doing, I leave that to the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wetteland's wife Michele awaits the birth of their
third child. For the record, the baby is due July 30, the day
before the trade deadline. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
