<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-MARINERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS FOLD IN GAGNE'S LATEST COLLAPSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As the Los Angeles Dodgers head into the final game
before the All-Star break, they're playing like they need a break.
</P>
<P>
   Several players are sick with the flu. Saturday, the whole team
looked sick in suffering its most one-sided loss of the season,
11-0 to the Seattle Mariners before a sellout crowd of 45,248.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good thing the break's coming,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``We're short-handed as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, only Mark Grudzielanek, F.P. Santangelo and Eric
Karros have the flu, and Todd Hundley's bruised thumb prevents him
from batting right-handed. All but Grudzielanek played Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was the fifth time this season the Dodgers have been
shut out (June 11 against Oakland was the last) and it erases two
eight-run losses as their widest margin of defeat. Los Angeles
previously lost 15-7 at Arizona on May 8 and 11-3 at Montreal on
April 6.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Eric Gagne isn't sick, but one day after the
pitching held up in a tight 11-inning victory, Gagne (1-5) got
knocked around for eight runs and seven hits in 3 innings - the
shortest start of his young career.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud provided more than enough punch for Seattle with a
career-high-tying five RBI. He hit a three-run homer off Gagne as
part of a four-run third and doubled in two more off Jamie Arnold
in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gagne's performance that had everyone talking. He's the
one the Dodgers wanted to showcase after waiving Orel Hershiser.
Now, they hope the 24-year-old who has just 17 career starts will
recover and learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just getting too fast and starts reaching back for a lot
more when he should be thinking a little more,'' pitching coach
Claude Osteen said. ``It's not a criticism of him. It's a stage
where he's at. I love his aggressiveness. We all do. But a lot of
times it gets him in trouble because he overthrows.''
</P>
<P>
   Gagne was disappointed because he said he went over the game
plan and knew what to do but didn't execute.
</P>
<P>
   After a 1-2-3 first inning, Gagne was in trouble in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Oliver singled in Olerud for a 1-0 lead, then David Bell's
sacrifice fly in the third made it 2-0. Then Gagne let hang a
changeup that Olerud hit deep to center for a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I got a little (angry) at myself for hanging a
changeup,'' Gagne said. ``I don't know what it was. I didn't
execute the plan. ... Right now, I need to get some people out, and
that's the bottom line. When I get in the game, I try to do too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle chased Gagne in the fourth as it batted around and
scored four more in the fourth for a 9-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers offense, meanwhile, has averaged about five runs a
game this season, but you wouldn't know it from the past two games.
After getting just five hits Friday night, including one over the
final eight innings, the Dodgers had just three off Seattle starter
Aaron Sele (11-3) in seven innings and two in the ninth off Brett
Tomko.
</P>
<P>
   Sele has pitched just twice against the Dodgers, but he's 2-0
with a 1.29 ERA against them, a span of 14 innings. He last beat
them June 7, 1999 while with Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he walked four, struck out three, didn't give up a hit
until the third inning and pitched out of a jam in the seventh. He
walked Karros and Hundley with one out and gave up a single to
right to Jim Leyritz before getting Adrian Beltre to ground into an
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers hope one day Gagne can regularly pitch out of
similar jams and that Saturday was just a minor setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these things he's going through, he'll benefit from,''
Osteen said. ``I always say you learn more from adversity than when
you're ringing everyone's bell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
