<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD IS PUT ON HOLD BY SELIG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Gary Sheffield heard from his agent, who heard from
the players union that his suspension appeal would be heard in
Atlanta during the All-Star break. Los Angeles Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson and general manager Kevin Malone heard the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   As so often happens when you play ``Telephone,'' the message
changes along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sheffield's appeal won't be heard by commissioner Bud Selig
in Atlanta, and there's no date set. The Dodgers don't play in New
York (site of Selig's office) again this season. The closest they
come is July 28-30 in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration level mounts, but Johnson has passed the boiling
point. Not only does he fear Sheffield having to serve his
five-game suspension during August, he hasn't been told when the
suspensions for Carlos Perez, F.P. Santangelo and Mike Fetters are
supposed to start.
</P>
<P>
   It has been reported Perez will serve his five games starting
July 16, followed by Fetters for one game July 21 and Santangelo
for five games starting July 22. But no baseball official has told
Johnson, and he's finding it difficult to set up his rotation and
make roster moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like going in for detention, but 'I'll tell you when.'
That's hard,'' Johnson said. ``Are these suspension cut in stone? I
read it in the paper, but nobody's given me official notification
in the form of a letter or fax. ... I've got to try managing around
these suspensions, and not knowing isn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he has tried to reach officials in Atlanta, site of
Tuesday's All-Star Game, and felt the end of the ordeal is near.
Sheffield said he just wants the matter resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Familiarity: Shortstop Alex Cora knows Seattle shortstop Alex
Rodriguez from his days in Miami through a mutual friend. Cora said
Rodriguez is ``a nice guy and one of the boys.'' Plus, Cora's
brother, Joey, was Rodriguez's teammate from 1995-'98.
</P>
<P>
   So it was a little ironic when they collided at second base
Friday night. Rodriguez suffered a grade two concussion (grade
three is most severe) and a sprained knee. He didn't play Saturday,
won't play today and won't play in Tuesday's All-Star Game,
although he will attend. Carlos Guillen started in his place
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   For Cora, collisions are just part of the game, but it was hard
to see Rodriguez lying motionless near second base.
</P>
<P>
   Cora tried to call Providence Hospital - where Rodriguez stayed
Friday night - but was unsuccessful in reaching him. Rodriguez was
released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle team doctor Larry Pedegana said Rodriguez will be out
for a week because of the concussion, but it's not known how long
the knee might sideline him. Rodriguez's head injury took priority
at the hospital. Pedegana said no knee tests were done.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get a chance I'll talk to him,'' Cora said. ``It's not
about apologizing, I want to see how he feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumps and bruises: Mark Grudzielanek has the flu, and F.P.
Santangelo caught it, so he didn't start. Rookie Mike Metcalfe got
the start at second base. ...
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Todd Hundley bruised his right thumb in the 11th inning
of Friday's game. On the third-to-last pitch of the game, Jay
Buhner fouled a ball off Hundley's thumb, leaving it black and
blue.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley said he can grip a bat but can't grip a baseball, so he
started at designated hitter (Johnson said the switch-hitting
Hundley can bat only left-handed). With Chad Kreuter serving his
eight-game suspension, Jim Leyritz started behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Hundley won't catch today's game, either, and he's
looking for a right-handed DH to start against Seattle left-hander
Jamie Moyer. ...
</P>
<P>
   Closer Jeff Shaw threw Friday and could be reactivated for
Thursday's game against the Angels, which is his scheduled return
date. Johnson said Shaw threw ``the best stuff he had all year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
