<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-teacher finds joy helping a forest grow
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ever heard of snorkeling in North Georgia? Talk to
Brent Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Snorkeling on the Conasauga River in the state's northwest
corner is one of the joys the former history teacher counts in the
career change he made five years ago. ``Oh man,'' Martin exclaims,
``it's like being in an aquarium.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has come to love the annual ``insect walk'' along the
wild and scenic Chattooga River sponsored by Georgia Forest Watch,
the 750-member watchdog organization Martin heads. Two years ago
the organization won a National Wilderness Society award as a model
for groups springing up in the Southeast, where logging and roads
threaten forest ecology.
</P>
<P>
   The Conasauga River, which starts in the Cohutta wilderness and
makes a horseshoe loop into Tennessee before drifting back into
Georgia, is the only place on the planet where you can see the
Conasauga logperch, a tiny fish numbering fewer than 200. The
river, whose cool, crystal waters are a shock to city folks
accustomed to silt-laden streams, nourishes 92 species of fish,
including 13 on the federal threatened or endangered lists. Every
summer, Georgia Forest Watch sponsors three snorkeling events led
by expert biologists, each limited to 25 people.
</P>
<P>
   But mountain outings aren't Forest Watch's _ or Martin's _
mainstay. Preserving the 750,000-acre Chattahoochee National Forest
is. The organization, whose membership is split almost evenly
between Atlanta and mountain residents, was formed after the first
10-year forest management plan was completed in 1986, under a
federal law ushered in during Jimmy Carter's presidency. The plan
was appealed by environmentalists who thought it permitted too much
timber cutting. A settlement with the National Forest Service
called for a citizen watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a Kennesaw College history instructor with a century of
family roots near Ellijay, Ga., volunteered with the group from its
beginnings in 1988. A few years later, he threw in the towel on his
Ph.D. in modern British history at Georgia State University and
devoted his career to his true passion: the environment. He was
named the first full-time CEO of Forest Watch in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bob Kibler, retired chief of Emory University's neurosurgery
department, stepped down as Forest Watch president last fall. He
credits Martin with maintaining a strong hand in the forest plan
the Chattahoochee district is finalizing. It protects watersheds
and proposes additions to wilderness areas.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Layfield, a Forest Service planner, says he makes it a
habit to call Martin to talk over logging and conservation issues.
``We don't always agree,'' he said, ``but we can work through just
about anything now.'' Martin grew up in a working-class family in
rural Cobb County, where he spent his boyhood coon hunting,
camping, fishing and collecting arrowheads near Nickajack Creek.
``I guess I never got over watching the woods I grew up in (being)
destroyed,'' he said. When Highlands Industrial Park was built in
south Cobb, the forest of his boyhood disappeared. ``I'm still mad
about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During his graduate studies, Martin helped historians document
the environmental history of North Georgia, poring over archival
maps dating to the Cherokee Indians and to subsequent eras when
mining and agricultural interests clear-cut the forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to appreciate the incredible job the Forest Service did
in bringing Southern forests back to life over the past 75 years,
regenerating oaks and other hardwoods,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin is critical of management policies that have placed
too much emphasis on road building and logging. Forest Watch and
the Sierra Club were instrumental in organizing a coalition of
environmental groups that won a landmark federal lawsuit against
the Forest Service last year that requires the agency to conduct an
assessment of species that might be harmed by proposed timber
projects before approving them. (Chattahoochee forest officials are
trying to change their own rules to get around the requirement _ an
effort being challenged by the Southern Environmental Law Center.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Valuing the forests,'' Martin says, ``is about valuing
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
