<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zedillo a class act in face of PRI defeat
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Largely overlooked in the coverage of the
Mexican presidential election is the grace with which incumbent
President Ernesto Zedillo and losing candidate Francisco Labastida
accepted the results.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo and Labastida, ranking members of the Party of the
Institutional Revolution (PRI) were both class acts as the results
came in with surprising swiftness _ not to mention clarity _ July
2.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo deserves a lot of credit for quickly taking the
initiative and the airwaves to broadcast his congratulations to
winner Vicente Fox and promising to work with him on a transition.
</P>
<P>
   It was a message that the transition would be both peaceful and
respectful.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida acted commendably and responsibly as well. A career
PRI-ista, Labastida made a graceful exit from 30 years of public
life. He may be back, but it's highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   It could not have been easy for the ranking members of a party
that has been in control of Mexican politics to do that. In fact,
there was no blueprint for reaction because the PRI has not lost a
presidential election since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Mexican presidents have been autocrats, whose power
was limited only by money and imagination. The 1980s saw an
insurgence _ a peaceful one but insurgence nonetheless _ to which
the PRI steadily lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his administration, Zedillo had the courage to renounce
the old ways of doing business by declaring that he was not going
to handpick a successor and then by having the tenacity to make
that decision stick.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the outgoing president picked the PRI nominee and
whoever got the dedazo (the finger tap) was assured of victory,
whether he had the majority of votes or not.
</P>
<P>
   However, when history judges his successor, it ought to have
kind words for Zedillo, who made this peaceful transition possible.
</P>
<P>
   The election results brought to mind a conversation I had last
fall in Mexico City with a North American business woman. ``Zedillo
hasn't done much for the country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except bring democracy,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   THE THRILL OF VICTORY . . .
</P>
<P>
   After elections around here, a story emerges about this fellow
in Austin who walks up to the victor, embraces him or her warmly
and declares: ``Hey, we won!''
</P>
<P>
   It's urban legend, of course, one of those stories that crops up
when cocktail conversation turns to the light side of political
life. And like most humor what makes it funny is that it rings
true. Turns out it contains international truth as the reaction to
the Mexican presidential election shows.
</P>
<P>
   Only two weeks ago, many I approached and a few just volunteered
that the PRI would win. In the aftermath, comments _ delivered both
by e-mail and in person _ pretty much ran something like this: ``I
knew it all along.'' or ``This a great day for Mexico.'' ``The mood
here is one of joy.'' ``The system works.''
</P>
<P>
   Put another way: ``Ganamos.'' That means ``We won.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AGONY OF DEFEAT . . .
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the interests of full disclosure, I bet a friend of mine
that Labastida would win. The PRI, after all, had 71 years of
political domination going for it, as well as a tried-and-true
machine for delivering votes. Moreover, Mexicans are basically
conservative people who approach change as one would approach a
rattlesnake _ with great caution.
</P>
<P>
   I figured Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, who came in third, would deny Fox
enough opposition votes to enable the PRI-istas to hold onto the
presidency. I also had enough evidence to put money on Fox, but
just couldn't quite bring myself to do it.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine in Mexico City who is quite an avid follower of
politics and who converses frequently with those in the know
assured me solemnly that when all was said and done, Labastida
would pull 43 percent; 35 percent would go to Fox and Cardenas
would take 16 percent. The really minor candidates would pick up
the change. He was right, just had the Fox and Labastida numbers
transposed.
</P>
<P>
   I sent him a note last Monday suggesting that we should each
re-evaluate our futures as fortune tellers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
