<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON _WASHINGTON _ President Clinton goes to Camp
David Sunday forwhat's likely to be his last clean shot at a high
stakes foreign policy win to burnish a legacy stained by scandal.
While he'll continue for the rest of his term to juggle an armful
of international issues _ China trade, national missile defense,
Balkans peacekeeping among them _ no other initiative has consumed
so much of his time, so captured the imagination of the public or
is so ripe for completion as the quest to end half a century of
conflict between Israelis and Palestinians. Appropriate to the
stakes for himself and for history, Clinton has chosen a venue rich
in symbolism and resonant with hope. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ALZHEIMER'S _ WASHINGTON _ A study of twins supports previous
research indicating that education may protect against Alzheimer's
disease and other forms of dementia, scientists reported at a
meeting here of dementia researchers. Meeting is continue through
July 18. (Nesmith, Cox News Service)
</P>
