<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-EXAM (Beijing) _ This is ``Black July'' in China, time for
the long-anticipated exam that determines who goes to college in a
country where a degree is seen as a ticket to prosperity, and
failure can mean consignment to drudgery. 1200 words. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-RIGHTS (Cairo) _ The arrest last week of a prominent
sociologist on suspicion of defaming Egypt has alarmed human rights
advocates around the region who say it reflects a policy among Arab
leaders toward political criticism that can best be described as
``killing the messenger.'' By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
governing coalition came under attack before the Camp David summit
meeting this week, as his biggest coalition partner said it would
quit the government; and his foreign minister, David Levy, said he
would boycott the talks. 1300 words. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-MEETING (Durban, South Africa) _ South Africa's president
addresses the opening of a World AIDS conference. Length TK. By
Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Gracanica, Yugoslavia) _ A U.N. agreement to
provide better security to Kosovo's Serbs, designed to get some
Serbs back into international institutions here, has deepened
divisions among them and caused a key Albanian politician to
suspend his own participation. 1200 words. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Seven people were killed in two
separate bomb blasts in southern Russia near Chechnya, raising
fears that Chechen separatists were extending their guerrilla war
beyond the rebel province. 500 words. By Michael R. Wines.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PROTESTS (Portadown, Northern Ireland) _ Orange Order
leaders call for protests across Northern Ireland after Protestants
are barred from taking their traditional parade route through a
Catholic area. 700 words. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-GAYS (Rome) _ Pope John Paul II expresses ``bitterness''
about a gay-pride festival held in Rome during a Roman Catholic
Holy Year, saying the event was an affront to the church and the
``Christian values'' of the Italian capital. 600 words. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-VOTE (Port-au-Prince) _ Haiti holds the second round of
elections likely to hand victory to the ruling party of former
president Jean-Bertrand Aristide but marred by strong criticism at
home and abroad. 900 words. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Istanbul) _ The increasing likelihood that a
73-year-old former prime minister will go to prison for remarks in
a political speech six years ago is sending a chill through
Turkey's political elite and bringing widespread calls to relax
laws that restrict freedom of speech. 700 words. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   PAY-YOUR-WAY-PRISONS (Owensboro, Ky.) _ The county jailers of
Kentucky are eagerly preparing to levy room, board and medical
charges on inmates under a pay-your-way practice that dates to
medieval England but is finding fresh life in America, the global
leader in incarceration. Chief jailer Harold Taylor fondly recalls
his salad days in the 1960s when county inmates were respectful
winos who barely taxed the public budget, versus modern inmates who
sue for full dentistry, he says, running up bills under federal
regulations that under a new state law they will have to begin
footing. It's an increasingly fashionable practice nationwide in a
booming jail market now handling 10 million admissions a year.
1000. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   This item is tentative:
</P>
<P>
   NAKED-SOLES (Lombard, Ill.) _ The barefoot movement is gaining
ground. Hundreds of people are baring their toes in unlikely
places, saying it is more comfortable, healthier, environmentally
friendly, even spiritually uplifting. Some like the dash of
iconoclasm it spices into their lives. And they like feeling
through their feet -- pebbly sidewalk, grainy dirt, velvety moss,
polished floors. The Dirty Sole Society, dedicated to ``helping one
another to get along in a shod world,'' has attracted over 600
members since its inception a few years ago. And there is Parents
for Barefoot Children and 17 Barefoot Hikers chapters. 1200. By Pam
Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   This item is tentative:
</P>
<P>
   FISHING-QUOTAS (Washington) _ The way the government limits the
catch of fishermen may heighten the risks for those who go down to
the sea. In most waters, you can catch all the fish you are able
until the overall quota is reached. That spurs a mad race,
regardless of high seas and foul winds. Instead, reformers want
individual quotas: a boat can catch so much, and it can take its
time. 800. By Carl Hulse.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CUT-POLITICS (Washington) _ With projections of the federal
budget surplus rising and both parties in full election-year mode,
the debate over tax cuts is shifting from whether to what kinds.
Republicans continue to press for bigger reductions than most
Democrats will support, and the super-charged politics of the
campaign season will make it difficult for any tax cuts to be
enacted before a new president and Congress take office next year.
But in Washington and on the campaign trail, Democrats from
President Clinton on down are joining Republicans in backing tax
cuts -- enthusiastically in some cases, grudgingly and with
conditions in others -- to a far greater degree than they were a
year or even six months ago. 1500. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   GOVS-MEETING (College Park, Pa.) _ Governors from around the
nation gather for their annual confab. 1000. By B. Drummond Ayres.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ Commentary by Bob Herbert;
details later.
</P>
<P>
   William Safire is on vacation.
</P>
