<P>
   INTERNET-WIRELESS (Undated) _ The wireless Internet, which
provides Web access on devices that include pagers, cell phones and
Palm handheld devices, is being touted as the most promising
technological development since the Internet itself started taking
off in the early 1990s. In two or three years, there are expected
to be almost as many wireless Internet users as people accessing
the Web on wired PCs. But given the current state of play in the
industry _ and some distinct technical shortcomings _ can the
wireless Web live up to the hype? With INTERNET-WIRELESS-USES. By
Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-WIRELESS-USES (Undated) _ A look at the wide variety of
uses for wireless Internet access that are being offered to
companies and consumers. Are any of them viable businesses? With
INTERNET-WIRELESS. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT-PROFILE (Undated) _ Whatever happens in the aftermath of
Sprint's unraveling merger agreement with Worldcom, Sprint's
wireless network remains a coveted asset. Here's a closer look. By
Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ E-commerce companies have long
coveted the back-end business structures of catalog companies. Now
they've got their eyes on the front end as well. The number of pure
plays that are rolling out their own catalog operations is growing
briskly, as they seek new ways to market themselves in a
cost-effective manner, and generate more revenue. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLESOFT (San Francisco) _ PeopleSoft, hoping to counter
Oracle's latest offering in the so-called
enterprise-resource-planning software market, will announce
PeopleSoft 8 on Tuesday. Here's what the company, and its product,
are up against. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   XM-SATELLITE (Undated) _ In a sign that long-promised satellite
radio broadcasting is coming closer to fruition, XM Satellite Radio
is expected to announce Monday that it has completed its planned
financing, raising the last $235 million from a group of investors.
By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   KETCHUP-KIDS (Undated) _ Heinz will announce a new line of
ketchup for kids on Monday. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   IKEDA-BUSSAN-OFFER (Tokyo) _ Johnson Controls, a U.S. automotive
parts manufacturer, will begin a tender offer for all the shares of
Ikeda Bussan, which is best known for making high-end car seats.
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   REFLECT-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ A high-profile entrant in one of
the most crowded categories of e-commerce is hoping to gain a
competitive edge with a campaign that plays up what are deemed to
be its beautiful points of differentiation. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column, this week on the
