<SLUG> BC-COX-MIDEAST-CLINTON-0710 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELIS AT ODDS ON EVE OF PEACE SUMMIT
 &HT;    Moving in the (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By Bob Deans and Larry Kaplow
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON After hearing a prayer for peace, President Clinton
spent Sunday preparing for this week's Mideast peace summit even as
Israel's fragile ruling coalition seemed to be falling apart over
the Palestinian issue.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the continuing political turmoil in Jerusalem, Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators arrived here to begin setting the
diplomatic table for the make-or-break Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat were scheduled to arrive late Monday for the summit, which
is due to begin Tuesday at the secluded presidential retreat in the
mountains of western Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighting the difficulties, Barak's ruling coalition suffered
its third defection since the summit was announced last week when
the second-largest party in his ruling coalition pulled its support
to protest the peace initiative.
</P>
<P>
   It was yet another embarrassing reminder of his precarious
political position at home.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, Barak's foreign minister, David Levy of yet a
fourth group, the Gesher Party, said he would boycott the summit.
</P>
<P>
   The ultra-religious Shas was the third party in the past week to
withdraw its support from the Barak government. Those losses have
cut Barak's coalition to 42 members in Israel's 120-seat
parliament, the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
   In a move aimed at embarrassing Barak on the eve of the Camp
David summit, the Knesset is scheduled to vote Monday on a
no-confidence motion. Approval would result in the dissolution of
Barak's government.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak is expected to weather that attack, with the support
of about 20 Knesset members who are not formal members of his
coalition but who nevertheless broadly support his approach to the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow I am leaving, heading the Israeli delegation with a
grave and difficult feeling of responsibility,'' Barak said in a
nationally televised address to the Israeli people Sunday night.
``I intend to sign only an agreement that will guarantee the
security of the people of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton hopes to broker a deal to end half a
century of war and enmity between Arabs and Jews by reprising some
of the deft statecraft that enabled President Jimmy Carter deliver
the historic Israeli-Egyptian peace accord at Camp David 22 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the ante in the high-stakes summit, White House National
Security Advisor Samuel Berger warned of ``a slide to turmoil'' in
the conflicted region, should the coming talks fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without an agreement, there is a certain path to turmoil,''
Berger said on CBS' Face The Nation. ``You are going to have, I
believe, an unraveling,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton felt the weight of the moment during church services
replete with powerful symbols of the ancient struggles he hopes to
help resolve in lands holy to Christians, Moslems and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blessed are the peacemakers,'' senior minister J. Philip
Wogaman said during his sermon. At one point he looked down to
Clinton's second-row pew and said, to applause by the congregation,
``Mr. President, you go with our prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, White House officials continue to voice confidence in
Barak's ability to represent his country in good faith efforts to
secure a peace accord. Barak has pledged to submit any such
agreement for a nationwide referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``He trusts his ability to negotiate a fair deal,'' Dennis Ross,
senior White House envoy for the Middle East, said in an interview
with CNN. ``... He trusts his ability to be able to take that to
the Israeli public.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright spent the
afternoon with working-level Israeli and Palestinian officials,
attempting to refine areas of possible give and take in a complex
and contentious agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The chief aim of the talks is to bring to fruition a peace
process that began in earnest seven years ago with the
Israeli-Palestinian agreement reached through secret negotiations
in Oslo, Norway. Under the so-called Oslo accords, Israel is
obligated to turn over occupied territory to Palestinian control in
exchange for security guarantees and full diplomatic and economic
relations with its Palestinian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   While Israel has turned over to Palestinian control the Gaza
Strip and more than 40 percent of the occupied West Bank of the
Jordan River, the remaining thorny issues form the core of the
long-running Israeli-Palestinian dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Those include the question of Palestinian statehood, borders,
water rights, the ability of Palestinian refugees to return to
former homelands now under Israeli control and the future of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Together, agreements on those issues would constitute a
comprehensive set of accords that could end five decades of
fighting between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   (Deans reported from Washington; Kaplow reported from
Jerusalem.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
