<DOCNO> NYT20000709.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-2TA     07-09 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-RETAILERS TURN TO THE PRINTED PAGE TO PUT THEIR WARES BEFORE
CONSUMERS
</HEADLINE>
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online retailers have been putting their marketing budgets on
crash diets this year _ replacing pricey, fatty television ads and
portal deals with leaner print ads and e-mail efforts that, like
all diet foods, may be less sumptuous but are far healthier in the
long run. More recently, dot-com retailers are testing a new item
on the low-fat marketing menu: catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Long a staple of the direct marketing industry, catalogs are the
newest fad among Web merchants who, in their pursuit of
profitability, have cast off any pretensions of Internet-only
retailing.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise, of course, that Web merchants
like RedEnvelope.com, eHats, Food.com, and eZiba.com, among others,
have either begun mass mailings or are developing such programs. It
is an accepted fact that online shoppers and catalog consumers are
a similar breed, preferring to browse through merchandise without
the help of a sales clerk, and accepting the risks inherent in
long-distance purchasing. And the back-office operations of catalog
and consumer-oriented e-commerce companies are nearly identical.
</P>
<P>
   But the catalog leanings of Internet retailers can also be
explained by looking at their executive rosters. The dot-coms spent
much of 1998 and 1999 raiding the management teams of L.L. Bean and
other giants of the direct mail realm, so it was probably
inevitable that many Web merchants would expand into catalog
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Although these Internet executives are not abandoning other
marketing campaigns as they adopt catalogs, they express delighted
surprise about how well catalogs compare with other popular
marketing approaches, like e-mail advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can produce and mail a catalog that costs about the same,
if not less, than a targeted e-mail campaign,'' said Matt Jackson,
vice president for marketing at eHats, an online hat retailer that
is developing its first catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies that conduct custom e-mail campaigns on behalf of
e-tailers may charge 25 cents or more per e-mail sent, Jackson
said. According to the Direct Marketing Association, most catalogs
cost 50 cents to $1 to print and mail to each household.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an e-mail, people either delete it or look at it quickly
and delete it,'' he said. ``But if we execute a catalog properly,
we know it'll not only get eyeballs, but it'll stay in someone's
house, so it has a shelf life and a much longer lasting impact than
a targeted e-mail campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   With catalogs, e-tailers also see a way to reach an objective
that no amount of digital alchemy can achieve _ selling goods to
the 50 percent of American households that remain without Internet
connections. ``We have to reach as many people as possible,''
Jackson said, ``and let them buy in whatever way they feel
comfortable, be it through the phone, the Web site a catalog,
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   And even as they view catalogs as a cost-effective way to reach
offline customers, e-tailers are also looking at them as a means to
increase the Web site's traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Take eZiba.com, which sells handmade goods from far-flung
regions of the world. The company plans to begin testing a catalog
this fall with a mailing to 500,000 consumers, according to Bill
Miller, the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a former executive vice president at F.A.O. Schwarz,
said he would use the catalog primarily to attract customers to the
eZiba Web site. ``Every time we dropped a catalog at F.A.O., we saw
a significant increase in our Web traffic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Catalogs can help create Web site traffic by showing customers a
limited, but enticing, selection of a company's overall merchandise
offerings, executives said. And because a Web order is less
expensive to process than a phone-based order, companies frequently
offer discounts or free shipping to draw customers to their sites.
</P>
<P>
   EZiba has more reason than many other e-tailers to use catalogs
as a device for generating Web traffic, rather than mainly a
vehicle for direct sales, Miller said. Because eZiba's business
involves selling goods with limited availability, the company
cannot stock enough items to support an extensive catalog mailed to
tens of millions of consumers. EZiba will ship a catalog with a
limited number of items that will be well-stocked, in case
consumers order those items in droves.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, at least, Internet merchants are nicely positioned to
produce a catalog at low cost. Many e-tailers already have plenty
of product descriptions and high-resolution digital photographs of
merchandise on hand, as well as in-house creative directors with
experience in print publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Web retailers who have initiated catalog efforts say
incremental production costs are minimal. But executives said that
to market a catalog successfully, companies must overcome far more
difficult, and potentially expensive, hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Inventory management, as Miller noted, can be a huge issue.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tom Bazzone, president of RedEnvelope.com, an online gifts
retailer that began selling through catalogs in February, said
merchants that did not properly manage inventory during a catalog
mailing risked either alienating customers with sold-out items, or
burying their warehouses in unsold merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   For most catalogs, he said, 75 to 80 percent of the sales occur
within 40 days of the mailing. As a result, many catalog operations
engage in what is called ``slotting,'' or staggering their order
volumes with suppliers. So instead of ordering 1,000 items from a
vendor, they would arrange to receive 300 initially, have another
300 delivered two weeks after the catalog is shipped, and then have
the option of either receiving or canceling the remaining items,
depending on sales.
</P>
<P>
   The process is even more complicated for Web retailers, he said,
because the same items sell at different rates through the
different channels. ``It can get very hairy,'' Bazzone said.
</P>
<P>
   Developing an effective mailing list is no snap either,
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies must know their audience well enough to cite specific
customer demographics when they approach so-called list brokers,
who typically sell names and addresses of prospective customers for
$100 to $125 per thousand. And once the first mailing goes out,
merchants must have the personnel and technology in place to
analyze the response rates, so they can fine-tune subsequent
mailings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes Direct Marketing 101 from there,'' said Cindy
Marshall, director of marketing for eZiba.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for dot-coms, the course requirements for Direct
Marketing 101 also include a large section on customer service _ an
area of study that many e-tailers seemed to have slept through in
previous semesters. H. Robert Wientzen, president of the Direct
Marketing Association, an industry trade group, said Internet
merchants ``need to have real customer service when it comes to a
catalog, because customers expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, he said, that requires substantial investment in
phone-based customer-service representatives. ``And it's probably
too late for some companies who are cash poor to make enough of an
investment in customer service to make it work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Internet companies that follow the catalog path can take
some solace in the experiences of Bazzone at RedEnvelope. He said
that only 30 percent of the orders generated by the company's
catalogs were taken over the phone. The rest, he said, came via the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Orton, senior vice president for business development at
Food.com, which delivers take-out food for 16,000 restaurants
around the country, said she hoped the company's coming catalog
effort would, like RedEnvelope.com, yield far more Web orders than
phone orders. Because the company already takes large numbers of
orders over the phone, Orton said she was not concerned about the
effect a catalog might have on customer service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the catalog as a way to migrate people from the phone
to the online experience,'' she said. For instance, Orton said that
in a recent survey 68 percent of the customers who had ordered over
the phone said they would prefer to use the Internet. ``So we see
this as a great opportunity for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
