<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-REFLECT-AD-COLUMN-NYT     07-09 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFLECT-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: CUSTOM COSMETICS AND `RELATIONSHIP MARKETING' ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A high-profile entrant in one of the most crowded categories of
e-commerce is hoping to gain a competitive edge with a campaign
that plays up what are deemed to be its beautiful points of
differentiation.
</P>
<P>
   Reflect.com LLC, formed by the household products giant Procter
&AMP; Gamble and two venture capital funds, is introducing
quirky-looking print advertisements that seek to gain attention for
_ and drive traffic to _ its Web site (www.reflect.com). The site
sells the lotions and potions that have long been emblematic of the
beauty products business, from makeup and fragrances to skin creams
and shampoos.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that merchandise is also being sold online by
companies like Eve.com, Gloss.com, Ibeauty.com and Sephora.com. And
those goods were being sold by online retailers that have already
become casualties of the dot-com downturn, among them Beauty.com,
Beautyscene.com and Jasmin.com.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Reflect.com and its agency of record, Deutsch Inc.
in New York, hope to distinguish the newcomer from its rivals by
stressing the customized products sold at the site, which are, as
the saying goes, not available in stores. The merchandise is
blended to order based on answers to questions asked of women who
visit the site and is even shipped to them in packages labeled with
their names.
</P>
<P>
   That customization _ underlined by the theme of the campaign,
``Active ingredient: You'' _ is indicative of the increasing
emphasis on relationship marketing by Internet advertisers. They
are placing more importance on turning consumers into customers,
particularly as it becomes more difficult and expensive to prospect
for computer users who have still not visited their sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view ourselves as a beauty brand that is Internet-enabled
instead of an Internet brand of beauty care products,'' said
Richard Gerstein, vice president for marketing and design at
Reflect.com in San Francisco, which was started by P &AMP; G in
September along with Institutional Venture Partners and Redpoint
Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really happy to see the dot-com shakeout,'' Gerstein
said. ``It allows our business model to rise to the top. Owning
your own brand allows you to be funded and make money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of inexperienced people with too much money
getting bad advice,'' he added, referring to the general e-commerce
field. ``They focused on building awareness, not long-term brand
equity, and didn't give consumers a reason to stick with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for women to glue themselves to Reflect.com,
according to the campaign, is its ability to provide what are
described as ``one-of-a-kind'' products ``that don't exist until
you help create them.'' The print ads use low-key humor,
underscored with whimsical drawings by an illustrator, Trisha
Krauss, to express that thought.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one ad asserts, ``It's not magic, it's
interactive.'' Another ad declares: ``Supermodels are under
contract. They have to wear certain products. You, luckily, are
free to create your own.'' An ad under development tentatively
carries this headline: ``For years, women have been told what they
need. Maybe it's time for you to tell us.''
</P>
<P>
   Liz Gumbinner, vice president and group creative director at
Deutsch, which joined the Procter agency roster in October with the
Reflect.com assignment, called the understated approach deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we said `It's a revolution in beauty care,' people wouldn't
believe it, because they've been hearing that their whole lives,''
Gumbinner said. ``It's like airline advertising; you're stuck on a
runway for six hours with nothing but peanuts and that's what
people remember, not the beautiful skies.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most visible aspect of the unconventional approach
the campaign takes is how the drawings depict the Reflect.com
customers. They are far more ``real-looking'' than women typically
are in pitches for beauty products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge to the way the beauty industry portrays
women, on a pedestal,'' Gerstein said. ``We're not suggesting you
have to be a perfect, touched-up person, which is where we think
the future is, allowing women to focus on what's right for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam M. Levine, executive vice president and brand director at
Deutsch, noted that there was a deliberately ``unfinished quality
to all the illustrations,'' which were painted by Krauss on
plywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, it's easier for women to project themselves into the
ads,'' Levine said, ``which is also a way to get at the
interactivity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women still have that hope there can be, will be, something
better out there,'' he added, ``and they will try things.''
</P>
<P>
   To capitalize on that quality among consumers whom Levine
labeled as ``beauty-involved,'' the ads will appear in magazines
with a beauty and fashion editorial focus like Allure,
Cosmopolitan, Elle, Essence, Glamour, In Style, Mademoiselle, Marie
Claire, Self, Shape and Vogue. The ads will also run in
publications like Entertainment Weekly and People.
</P>
<P>
   The budget for the campaign is $3 million to $5 million for the
third quarter. The work by Deutsch is in addition to a campaign
created by the interactive agency of record for Reflect.com,
Critical Mass in Calgary, Alberta, half owned by Rapp Collins
Worldwide in New York, part of the Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp Collins had been handling direct marketing duties for the
site, but Gerstein said that he was ``no longer working with'' that
agency and was instead producing direct mail ``using the Deutsch
creative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have a campaign women have told us they love,'' he
added, ``we are starting to integrate it into other elements of our
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as that great philosopher, Madonna, once said, ``Beauty's
where you find it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
