<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7167 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BLACK-BASEBALL0710-CO     07-09 1713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-BASEBALL0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where have you gone, Jackie Robinson?
 &HT;    By Israel Gutierrez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Buck O'Neil was playing for the Kansas
City Monarchs of the Negro Leagues in the 1930s and 1940s, the love
for baseball spilled over onto the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Famer O'Neil, teammate of Hall of Fame pitcher
Satchel Paige, remembers watching black children in the city
neighborhoods playing stickball, imagining themselves as the next
Paige or O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   For years before and years after Jackie Robinson broke Major
League Baseball's color barrier in 1947, baseball was the sport of
choice for America's black youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``All kids played baseball during that time,'' said O'Neil, who
broke the major-league coaching color barrier when he took a
position with the Cubs in 1962. ``Their daddies before them played
baseball. It might have been semipro teams, but everybody played
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time, that was more or less the only outlet for the
black kid _ baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward six decades. Pittsburgh Pirates first baseman Kevin
Young believes Robinson would be disappointed if he saw the racial
makeup of baseball today.
</P>
<P>
   Young and Adrian Brown are the only black players on the
Pirates' 25-man roster. It's a ratio that's become common in
baseball at every level.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have so many Latin players, and their dark skin kind of
makes everybody go, 'Oh, there they (the black players) are,' ''
Young said. ``But you look at our team, and it's me and Adrian
Brown and that's it. And then you have five other Latin players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt you notice that from team to team. It's very
rare now to see a team with four African-American players on it.
It's definitely something that's on the decline and is trying to be
addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of black players in Major League Baseball dropped
to 15 percent in 1998, the lowest percentage of the decade,
according to the Center for the Study of Sport in Society at
Northeastern University. By comparison, the percentage of Latin
players reached an all-time high (25 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of black players on rosters still hovers around
15 percent this season. In 1959, when Pumpsie Green joined the
Boston Red Sox, the last team to integrate its roster, the
percentage was 17.9. In 1980, the number reached 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But 53 years after Robinson, the numbers are on the decline,
prompting concerns about the sport's future with blacks, and asking
the question, ``Why the disinterest?'' At least one former
major-leaguer wonders if the future of the league will look more
like the pre-Robinson days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over history, (blacks) have been excellent players. You want
this to continue,'' said Monte Irvin, who was originally chosen to
break baseball's color barrier but was delayed until 1949 by
military service and health problems. ``You don't want to go to a
game and not see any African-American representatives. The way it's
going, in another 20 years there might not be any. I'd hate to see
that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   While the number of black athletes in basketball and football
also are slipping slightly, the dwindling numbers in those sports
still don't compare to baseball. According to the Northeastern
study, blacks make up nearly 70 percent of professional football
rosters and the number reaches 80 percent in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   So how did baseball reach this point? The answer lies in the
inner cities and with today's youth.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL, FOOTBALL DOMINATE
</P>
<P>
   When O'Neil visits those same neighborhoods where he once saw
stickball played in the streets, he now sees packed basketball
courts and football in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Puerto Rico, Cuba and places like that, it's the same thing
as it was in the inner city when Jackie went in,'' O'Neil said.
``Everybody wanted to play baseball. 'This is my way to get out of
here.' Right now, they've got so many different ways to get out of
the ghetto than they had in my time. Baseball, that was your way
out.''
</P>
<P>
   If athletics is the chosen path, they now gravitate toward the
sports that better promote black players, said Richard Lapchick, a
sports sociologist and author of the Northeastern study.
</P>
<P>
   Even after his retirement, Michael Jordan is a more prominent
television figure than any black baseball star. During his playing
days, Jordan was the poster child of the NBA and played the role of
athletic icon and role model to near perfection. It's an aspect
clearly lacking in Major League Baseball promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. probably is the most marketable black superstar
in baseball, yet baseball has not taken full advantage of his
marketability, Lapchick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caught on a little bit, but not the way that Jordan was
marketed,'' Lapchick said. ``Jordan was clearly the greatest player
of his generation, but a lot of baseball people argued that Griffey
also was but wasn't even close to being marketed that way. I think
they could have done something with it.''
</P>
<P>
   If baseball would have taken a cue from the NBA, the sport could
have more budding black stars like Marlins center fielder Preston
Wilson, even though he too was caught up in Jordan-mania.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson called basketball his ``first love,'' and never seriously
considered baseball until high school, an interest that may never
have developed if not for his family ties to the sport _ Wilson's
stepfather Mookie Wilson played 12 major-league seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while there, Jordan was all everybody saw,'' said
Wilson, 25, one of six black players on the current Marlins roster.
``That was pretty big to see Michael Jordan. Everybody wanted to
play like Jordan. Everybody wanted to take Mike's moves. When you
look at the number of blacks that used to play baseball in the past
decades and how big the sport was for blacks, to see that there
aren't that many playing now, you really have to wonder what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   From Little League teams to high school teams to college teams,
the trend is noticeable. Of the 5,796 athletes who received some
NCAA scholarship aid in baseball during the 1997-98 academic year,
only 376 (6.5 percent) were African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally black colleges such as Florida A&AMP;M and
Bethune-Cookman fill their baseball rosters with whites or Latins
because not enough blacks are interested. Inner-city high schools
across the country are doing away with their baseball programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is looked down upon, at least where I come from,''
said Ron Calloway, a Jupiter Hammerheads outfielder who went to
high school in San Jose, Calif. ``I guess there are some places
where baseball is the thing to do, but it wasn't like that at my
school.''
</P>
<P>
   HIRING PRACTICES QUESTIONED
</P>
<P>
   Lapchick says there's another factor _ Major League Baseball's
hiring practice.
</P>
<P>
   There are no black general managers in the majors and just four
black managers, and minority hiring is a controversial topic that
comes up almost every off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents and families of color have a perspective that is far
different than white families, in that white families don't have to
think about those things because (whites) get those opportunities
irrespective of the color of their skin,'' Lapchick said. ``If
you're a person of color, that is very much a factor of everything
that happens in your life. That's a perspective that parents are
going to communicate to their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has recognized the problem and Commissioner Bud Selig
now requires teams to submit a list of candidates for manager and
front-office positions to make sure minorities are considered.
Lapchick called Selig's decision ``one of the most important things
a commissioner has done about this issue (of race), ever.''
</P>
<P>
   John Young helped institute a more grass-roots solution. In
1989, he founded RBI (Reviving Baseball in Inner cities), a program
that sponsors baseball leagues in inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   Young began the program in Los Angeles, but it has since
expanded into 137 cities worldwide. This year, 10 RBI participants
were selected in baseball's amateur draft.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Brasuell, RBI's director, said the target is not only
black children, but any youths who would not normally be able to
afford the costs of equipment for a Little League team.
</P>
<P>
   But 59 percent of RBI participants are black, a much higher
number than the percentage currently playing the sport in college
or professionally.
</P>
<P>
   Marlins reliever Vic Darensbourg coached in an RBI league in
California and noticed most of the children still favored the more
fast-paced sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun and hectic at the same time,'' Darensbourg said.
``A few of them had a heart for the game. Most of them, they'd
rather play basketball or football.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlins pitcher Chuck Smith acknowledges RBI's success, but
still would like to personally reach out to the inner cities to
find baseball talent. It's how he discovered his own talent.
</P>
<P>
   Smith grew up on the east side of Cleveland in the projects of
Garden Valley, where his father volunteered to coach a city youth
team made up of Rainbow Terrace Projects residents.
</P>
<P>
   That team folded after one year, but Smith and some teammates
went on to another team in the same city league, this one run by
former Negro Leagues player Johnny Rosco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a separated city,'' Smith said. ``You've got your whites
on the west side and you've got your blacks on the east side. So
when we played the city championship it was black against white. We
dominated the city of Cleveland for years.''
</P>
<P>
   That domination made Smith believe in his baseball abilities. So
when he sees the dwindling numbers of blacks playing baseball, he
uses his Cleveland days as an example of the untapped potential in
the inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like they go to the Dominican Republic and Venezuela to
get the talent from over there, there's just as much talent in the
city, you've just got to find it,'' Smith said. ``Baseball isn't
giving those areas enough attention to realize how much talent is
coming out of there. There's so many kids that could be saved. I'm
not saying baseball should try to save people, but there's a lot of
talent that could be given a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
