<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DRYBUGS0710-1STLEDE-C     07-09 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRYBUGS0710-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This version contains tips at the end.
 &HT;    Dry summer makes for thirsty bugs
 &HT;    By Jen Sansbury
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bugged out by watering restrictions?
</P>
<P>
   So are the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   As state and local governments limit outdoor sprinkler time,
homeowners tend to focus their efforts on watering lawns and plants
closest to their houses. By doing that, they end up attracting more
household pests, said Steve Arnold, owner of Atlanta's Peachtree
Pest Control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insects move in as close to the structures as they can get
because that's the only place they can usually find water,'' Arnold
said. ``The drought does the same thing for insects as it does for
people. It gets hot and they go find a place to cool off.''
</P>
<P>
   Ants in particular may head indoors for a drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually they'll make an entrance through a crack or crevice in
the bathroom or kitchen,'' said Winston Eason, a county
agricultural extension agent. ``You can expect it almost every
summer but usually we see a lot more of it when we have very dry
summers, mostly when people aren't able to water.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that ants like to take their food
underground, let it mold and then feed off it, said Don Chesney, an
exterminator at Elite Pest Control. When the ground is dry, it
disrupts the process and stirs up the ants.
</P>
<P>
   Chesney said the increase in ants coming indoors is simply a
function of a growing ant population engaging in typical summertime
habits.
</P>
<P>
   But Arnold said the dry conditions are affecting all kinds of
critters, from crickets and spiders to millipedes and roly-poly
pillbugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These insects are water dependent and are more apt to move
into those areas where water is more readily available, from a
leaky faucet to an irrigation system keeping your plants alive,''
Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   Pets may help bring more bugs inside as well, Eason said, from
ticks that thrive in warm weather to ants making a bee-line for the
water bowl on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are first and foremost attracted to water,'' he said.
``If food is there they will go ahead and help themselves to that,
too. The cat food will be a little bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold said the drought actually creates year-round bug issues.
If the healthier plants are closest to the house or even inside, so
are the insects that feed off the leaves, like leafhoppers,
caterpillars and aphids. They, in turn, lure the bugs that eat
them, such as ladybugs, spiders and earwigs. Some will then
``overwinter,'' or hibernate, inside.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the ladybugs that seemed to be getting inside
your house during the spring may actually have hatched there and
were trying to get out, Arnold said. So expect to see them again
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have more problems every year the drought
continues,'' he said. ``They're going to utilize our homes as a way
of surviving.''
</P>
<P>
   TIPS ON BATTLING INDOOR BUG INVASIONS
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep your house clean.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seal cracks around your home, including places where plumbing
pipes and telephone and cable wiring enter the building.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trim trees so that limbs don't touch your house.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep mulch shallow, no more than 2 inches, near the foundation
of your house.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure air conditioning condensation lines lead away from
the house.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep dryer hoses and vents clean and aimed outside.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have a crawlspace under your house, make sure vent
louvres are open, to allow warm, moist air to escape, and there's a
tight, mesh screen to help keep insects out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
