<P>
   JEWISH-PRESS-MEDIA (Undated) _ Usually, The New York Jewish Week
newspaper, affiliated with the UJA-Federation, sees its job as
putting the Jewish community in a positive light. And so it was a
remarkable departure for the paper to run an extensive
investigative article recently about a local rabbi, the regional
director of the Orthodox Union's summer youth program, who had been
accused for years of sexual improprieties toward teen-age girls.
After the article appeared, the rabbi was fired, despite his
insistence that the accusations were false. The reaction, within
the metropolitan Jewish community, as well as the regional and
national Jewish press, highlights the tension between advocacy and
objectivity in specialized journalism that is aimed at specific
religious, ethnic or cultural groups. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved.)
</P>
