<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      07-09 0284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, July 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The low humidity that has enveloped the Northeast and Middle
Atlantic States recently will yield to stickier conditions on
Monday as breezes from the southwest deliver sultry air to the
region. Scattered thunderstorms will accompany the return of humid
weather, but some sunshine is also expected.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of heavy thunderstorms will occur near the southern
Great Lakes and Ohio Valley as a cool front intercepts sultry air.
The Southeast will stay partly cloudy and humid with afternoon
thunderstorms in a few locations.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive heat will rule the southern Plains and Texas again as
temperatures surpass 100 degrees in some places. In the West,
afternoon storms will erupt in the southern Rockies where uneven
heating of the complex terrain promotes rising currents of
moistened air.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: LINE OF FIRE
</P>
<P>
   Recurrent thunderstorms brought 10 inches of rain to parts of
northern Wisconsin over the weekend. Steady high-level winds from
the northwest repeatedly steered thunderstorms through the upper
Midwest. This corridor for traveling thunderstorms has been
anchored from the Dakotas to the Great Lakes recently, because the
large-scale wind pattern that is responsible for steering weather
systems has been stagnant. A small change of the high-level wind
pattern early this week will cause the firing line of storms to
shift south to the Ohio Valley and the Middle Atlantic States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-00 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000709.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7177 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BOLSTER-PROFILE-MEDIA     07-09 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLSTER-PROFILE-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRASH, HARD-DRIVING EXECUTIVE STEERS CNBC TO TOP OF CABLE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J., Mo.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 and graphic are being sent to NYT
photo/graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three years ago, Bill Bolster, still new to the
president's job at CNBC, announced an ambitious dream: His
financial news network would beat CNN, then the dominant news
provider on cable, in the cable TV ratings war.
</P>
<P>
   Though it seemed at the time a distant, almost improbable goal,
two weeks ago Bolster achieved it. New Nielsen Media Research data
showed that for the first time in its 11-year history, CNBC had
averaged a higher daily audience than CNN for a three-month period.
</P>
<P>
   In short, CNBC had become the highest-rated news and information
network on cable television, ending CNN's long reign and cementing
its reputation as a leading media organization of the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   For Bolster, 56, the ratings represent a crowning victory in a
35-year career in broadcasting. Although he is widely described as
a tyrannical bully who often offends colleagues, he is admired as a
TV genius gifted not only at packaging and promoting programming
but also at selling it to advertisers at top dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his status as king of TV financial news, Bolster is
more a product of Main Street than of Wall Street _ a media mogul
who is far from media-ready.
</P>
<P>
   Bolster, who is 6 feet 4 inches tall and hulking, has spent most
of his career in local markets out of the glare of the national
spotlight, making him an unlikely leader for a network noted for
having made financial news interesting to everyday people around
the country. CNBC is now a regular fixture not only in brokerage
houses and newsrooms, but also in gyms and bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the market has gone up, and in some ways become, at its
worst, the national lottery, CNBC has grown right along with it,''
said Tom Wolzien, a media analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein.
``They're part of the democratization of the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolster is credited both inside and outside his organization
with making CNBC a highly profitable entity with mass appeal by
incorporating some of the flashy graphics and hype associated with
local television news while applying some of the bare-knuckled
sales tactics emblematic of local markets.
</P>
<P>
   Under his tenure, CNBC's ad rates have risen more than
threefold, and profits have more than doubled, executives said.
CNBC, which does not break out its financial results separately
from its parent, General Electric, estimates that it will end the
year with $280 million in profit.
</P>
<P>
   Bolster first learned about sales, he said, from his father,
William, who owned Sweeney's, a women's ready-to-wear business in
Waterloo, Iowa, and who also had an investment in Black Hawk
Broadcasting, which started out as a small radio group. As a
teen-ager, he would help his father with the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I learned the fundamentals of business,'' Bolster
said during an interview at CNBC headquarters in Fort Lee, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he did not become hooked on broadcasting until after
college, when he became an announcer and ad salesman at KDTH radio
in Dubuque, Iowa. He later moved to Waterloo' KWWL-TV, which was
owned by Black Hawk, working up to general manager before moving in
1983 to KSDK-TV, the NBC affiliate in St. Louis, as general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Bolster produced major victories during his time in local
television. KSDK was the No. 3 station in St. Louis when Bolster
arrived. He brought it to first place in two years with heavy
promotions; an early-morning local news program, which was the
first in St. Louis; and an afternoon talk show, ``The Sally Jesse
Raphael Show.''
</P>
<P>
   As head of the news committee of the NBC network's affiliates
board, he helped persuade the network in 1991 to delay the
beginning of ``The Tonight Show'' by five minutes, so stations
would have more ad time to sell during their late newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   Bolster arrived in New York as a virtual unknown in late 1991,
as the general manager of the local NBC station, WNBC-TV, and
scored early ratings victories by heavily using promotions,
starting the city's first early-morning local news program and
introducing flourishes like a news helicopter and high-technology
weather radar.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of his competitors were saying, `Who is this guy from St.
Louis?' '' said Tony Guida, now an anchor with CNNfn who was at
WNBC when Bolster arrived. ``He just cleaned their clocks. He knew
how to market and sell TV better than anyone I've ever worked
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Guida added, ``And I say that grudgingly because there is no
love lost between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Guida is one many on-air people and broadcasting executives who
say they have clashed with Bolster, and who use the phrase ``bull
in a china shop'' to describe him.
</P>
<P>
   He is said to have a propensity for making off-color remarks and
riding people extremely hard. ``He is coarse, impolitic, boorish _
a bully,'' said Peter W. Barnes, a former CNBC reporter now working
for a new financial news Web site, JAGfn.com. Barnes said he had
clashed with Bolster when he tried to break his contract a few
months early and was refused.
</P>
<P>
   Bolster describes himself as one to speak his mind but says that
he does not intend to offend. ``If I've done something,
uncharacteristically, that offends on a very personal basis _ not
professionally, because professionally, that's my job _ I've got to
go back and say I'm sorry, I'm wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly his business manner is full speed ahead. Upon his
arrival at CNBC in 1996 Bolster quickly began making changes.
</P>
<P>
   Within two weeks, he had changed the CNBC logo, incorporating
the NBC peacock. He introduced new wrinkles like real-time stock
quotes and market meters that perpetually run on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   He raised ad rates by arguing to Madison Avenue that he was
delivering a higher-income viewer whom Nielsen could not measure.
To prove it, he gave a real estate firm free time slots advertising
a $3.5 million house in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. There were 400
respondents.
</P>
<P>
   On programming, he and his team approached the stock market as a
big event, a daily Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you say, geez, let's do a pregame show, and it's going to
be `Squawk Box,' '' Bolster said, referring to CNBC's opening-bell
show. ``Then you've got a game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And then, '' he added, ``the post-game show.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for CNBC, once the game is over _ once the main
stock exchanges close for the day _ viewers tend to wander off.
Despite CNBC's daytime gains, its prime-time ratings were down by
about 24 percent this spring compared with last, pulling
significantly smaller audiences than CNN and the Fox News Channel
in the time period.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, executives plan to announce that one nonfinancial
show, ``Upfront Tonight,'' Geraldo Rivera's half-hour news program
weeknights at 7:30, will be replaced by an additional half-hour of
``Business Center.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some debate over how much of CNBC's success belongs to
Bolster, given the public's ravenous appetite for stock market
news. And the network's big name stars like Maria Bartiromo were
there when he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But media industry executives say that even if Bolster was dealt
a great hand, he has played it masterfully. ``When he first
started, I remember he was saying how he was going to take on CNN
and win, and I thought he was being overly optimistic,'' said Tim
Spengler, senior vice president at Initiative Media, a media buying
firm. ``But he was right. He saw what he had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
