<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CUT-POLITICS (Washington) _ With projections of the federal
budget surplus rising and both parties in full election-year mode,
the debate over tax cuts is shifting from whether to what kinds.
Republicans continue to press for bigger reductions than most
Democrats will support, and the super-charged politics of the
campaign season will make it difficult for any tax cuts to be
enacted before a new president and Congress take office next year.
But in Washington and on the campaign trail, Democrats from
President Clinton on down are joining Republicans in backing tax
cuts -- enthusiastically in some cases, grudgingly and with
conditions in others -- to a far greater degree than they were a
year or even six months ago. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-NOOSE (Undated) _ The hangman's noose has long been
one of the most frightening representations of racism in America, a
reminder that thousands of blacks met a horrific death at the hands
of lynch mobs from the end of the Civil War well into the 20th
century. But while the symbolic use of a noose has traditionally
been associated with hate groups like the Ku Klux Klan, employment
experts say that nooses, while still rare, are increasingly turning
up in workplaces. In most cases, they say, the noose was placed
anonymously on an employee's chair, in his locker, or on a door. By
Sana Siwolop.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
