<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7179 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-IKEDA-BUSSAN-OFFER-NY     07-09 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IKEDA-BUSSAN-OFFER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON CONTROLS TO MAKE OFFER FOR NISSAN'S CAR-SEAT AFFILIATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Johnson Controls, the auto-parts manufacturer, will
begin a tender offer Monday for the shares of the Ikeda Bussan Co.,
a Nissan Motor Co. affiliate that is best known for making high-end
car seats.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is another strike at the heart of the tightly-knit
cluster of businesses linked to Nissan, which has been dismantling
a cumbersome and costly corporate empire in an effort to return to
financial health.
</P>
<P>
   It may also herald a rush of mergers and acquisitions in Japan's
highly fragmented auto-parts industry.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson Controls, based in Milwaukee, said Sunday that it would
offer 120 yen a share _ equivalent in total to $100 million _ to
buy all the outstanding shares of Ikeda Bussan. It would also
assume $85 million in debt. Shares of Ikeda Bussan closed here
Friday at 118 yen.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies share joint ventures in Europe and the United
States and so are not strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this acquisition will bring positive benefits to
Ikeda Bussan, Nissan and Johnson Controls,'' James Keyes, Johnson's
chairman and chief executive, said in a statement released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan has agreed to sell its 36.9 percent stake in the company
to Johnson, and people close to the negotiations said Johnson had
been negotiating with other big stockholders and was likely to
attract a significant portion of the outstanding shares.
</P>
<P>
   The French automaker Renault, which bought a 37 percent stake in
Nissan last year, has provided impetus for Nissan to slim down.
Ikeda is the latest of Nissan affiliate to be sold, including its
aerospace unit and its stake in Fuji Heavy Industries. Nissan has
raised 100 billion yen, or $935 million, through the sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ikeda Bussan, which had revenue of 134.7 billion yen, or $1.25
billion, in the fiscal year ending in March, has suffered because
of its heavy reliance on Nissan, whose production has fallen amid
declining sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-00 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
