r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-09 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE WHEELS OF PROGRESS ARE SPINNING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Nick Diamos  &LR; bought a Mister Magoo video from Amazon.com and
found the following ``explanation'' on the box:
</P>
<P>
   ``The character of Mr. Magoo is in no way intended to demean the
blind or visually impaired. Actually, the near-sighted Magoo is
stubborn: He simply refuses to wear his glasses. The humor comes
not from the bumblings of a myopic senior citizen but from the
wonderfully idiosyncratic creations of his imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   - An East Bay reader notes that the new San Leandro Boy Scouts
headquarters, on Davis Street, is painted a lavender shade of gray.
</P>
<P>
   - Instead of selling the Street News (the New York version of
San Francisco's Street Sheet), subway panhandlers in New York have
been selling copies of the Village Voice, a free weekly. ``These
are new issues,'' said a panhandler quoted in New York magazine,
``they just came out yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Voice managing editor  &UR; Doug Simmons &LR;  said the practice is OK
with the Voice. ``Who's the victim there? As long as it ends up in
the hands of a reader, I don't have any complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   - Ghosts may be lurking in your pockets. ``Couture-crazed New
Yorkers are currently gobbling up vintage clothing,'' writes
 &UR; Simon Doonan  &LR; of the New York Observer, ``with a cavalier and naive
disregard for the paranormal potential lurking in those Puccis and
Guccis. Spirits love a nice bit of schmatte as much as you or I:
Does the phrase `Shroud of Turin' mean anything to you?''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Marsha Garland &LR;  and  &UR; Danny Leone  &LR; stopped by the Art Van
mobile gallery, parked outside First Thursday art openings in San
Francisco last week, and saw ``Inverted Art,'' all the paintings
having been hung upside-down. Upon entering, gallerygoers were
strapped into a machine that turned them upside-down to see the
art. Leone says he will never be able to ``look at art in the same
old way again.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDUCATION R US &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - All the modern student needs is a little plastic box with a
screen on top.  &UR; Adrienne Biggs &LR;  saw an L.A. Times ad in which the
school district announced it is auctioning the following obsolete
equipment: printing presses, woodworking tables, engine parts,
lathes, record players, electric and manual typewriters,
projectors, easels, sewing machines, musical instruments, potters'
wheels, a baby grand piano and much more.
</P>
<P>
   _Subversives at the Exploratorium _ whose kitchen bomb-making
instructions scared the Air Force into a recent ban of its Web site
_ are now turning a new generation of Americans into
Travoltas-in-training. Students participating in Science Summer are
learning how to make lava lamps (a jar, vegetable oil, salt, water
and food coloring, and there you go) and disco balls.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Following up: Intrigued by mention of sun-dried opossum,
 &UR; Jere Holbrook  &LR; checked out its food values and found the meat
contains a mere 221 calories per 31/2-ounce serving. Even healthier
is muskrat: only 153 calories per same-size serving. And  &UR; John
Kraft  &LR; has found another use for those free CDs from AOL: to
separate frozen hamburger patties.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Roger Bye &LR;  testifies that the officer he saw driving a San
Francisco police car the other day had a cell phone in one hand and
a cup of coffee in the other. Meanwhile, retiring officer  &UR; Bob &LR; 
 &UR; Geary &LR;  has arranged a fine send-off _ including the Green Street
Mortuary Band, stagecoach and team of four horses _ after he and
his dummy, Brendan O'Smarty, formally retire on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   - During an American Airlines flight from Cleveland to San
Francisco in first class, a flight attendant offered  &UR; Ben &LR; 
 &UR; Fong-Torres  &LR; a steak. ``Can you make it medium rare?'' he asked.
``I dunno,'' she said with a shrug. ``I just heat 'em up.''
</P>
<P>
   - Actress  &UR; Clea DuVall  &LR; tells Glue magazine about going to
``Saturday Night Live'' to see  &UR; Britney Spears &LR; , who she thought
was ``so cool.'' After the show, she went backstage to meet Spears.
``She didn't care,'' says DuVall. ``She's the biggest star I've
ever met. She was really polite, but she didn't care about us. We
were just like every other person in America going, `Britney!
Britney! We love you!' Really lame, like kids who cry to meet
her.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``That Columbine s_ is so touchy. As much sympathy as we give
the shootings, nobody ever looked at it from the point of view of
the kids who were bullied. I've been that mad.''
</P>
<P>
   - Rapper  &UR; Eminem &LR; , who is facing four weapons charges in
Michigan, in Spin magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
