<HEADER>
A7184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THARP-DANCE-REVIEW-NY     07-09 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THARP-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWYLA THARP STRETCHES THE RECIPES FOR TWO STEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ In the entertaining cookbook of recipes from
modern dancers and choreographers just published by the American
Dance Festival here, Twyla Tharp's entry reads as follows: ``Here's
what I can do. Turkey from the deli, sliced. Baked potato, usually
harder than a rock. A banana. Love, Twyla.''
</P>
<P>
   Tharp has always known how to make do in modern dance, a
do-it-yourself art form rooted in individual expression. She
stretches the definition of dance, not just recipes, and her gift
for combining disparate ingredients is embodied in the ferocious
virtuosity that colors the two new Tharp works presented by the
festival from Thursday through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Energy at its most turbulent erupts throughout ``Surfer at the
Styx'' (to be retitled ``Surfer at the River Styx''), a loose
allegory about two souls battling aspects of themselves and the
Styx (symbolized by a quartet) before they cross into a peaceful
place.
</P>
<P>
   Tharp's vision of heaven and hell takes some time to reveal
itself. John Selya, in white surfer's outfit, and Keith Roberts are
magnificent soloists, clearly tormented onstage by a quartet in
black. But before the work's dramatic meaning snaps fully into
place, the viewer is swept away by the sheer dance power of the
choreography. This is nonstop, fierce bravura, delivered with
mind-boggling stamina from the new company that Tharp has just
formed.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Surfer,'' she has found a perfect collaborator in Donald
Knaack, whose music she used so wittily in a now-celebrated duet
for Ethan Stiefel and Susan Jaffe in her ``Known by Heart'' at
American Ballet Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Knaack, an experimental composer who once worked with John Cage,
as well as with the modern-dance pioneer Bella Lewitzky, meets
Tharp on the same maverick level of energy and rhythm. Known
professionally as the Junkman, he was in the pit on Thursday night
in Page Auditorium at Duke University, the festival's home, playing
an assortment of discarded found objects: hubcaps, a basketball
hoop, a mailbox, pots and pans, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   An electronic tape in the same vein produced by David Kahne, who
composed the coda for the heavenly apotheosis, was channeled into
Knaack's multilevel percussion. Tharp replied with a richly layered
design onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surfer'' has the impact of Tharp's most exciting and
athletically inclined classics, namely ``The Golden Section'' and
``In the Upper Room.'' It will be an obvious crowd pleaser in the
new company, Twyla Tharp Dance, that made its debut with these
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Mozart Clarinet Quintet K.581,'' the second premiere on
the program and named after its score, shares certain elements with
``Surfer.'' The three men and two women (who are not on toe) look
more classical as the sound of the clarinet floats poetically above
them. Yet in both pieces, Tharp focuses more than ever on novel
ways of partnering. Conventional ballet lifts yield to startling
images. A woman topples head down repeatedly as if dunked into a
vat while her partner holds her by her knees.
</P>
<P>
   Modern dance and ballet are integrated easily in these works.
Without their ballet training, Selya, Roberts, Benjamin Bowman,
Ashley Tuttle and Elizabeth Parkinson would not be so at ease in
the adagio partnering, which is foreign to modern dance. Nor would
Selya and Roberts, both formerly with Ballet Theater, be able to
display the virtuosity that Tharp draws from traditional ballet
bravura. Yet she also uses Francie Huber and Andrew Asnes for their
compelling energy and clarity, qualities they showed with Paul
Taylor's company.
</P>
<P>
   An immediate tension in ``Surfer'' is set up between a
black-clad chorus and the male soloists, Selya and Roberts. The
bent arms and profiles of the chorus recall the machinelike
movement in ``Known by Heart.'' Yet this time the score has a less
metallic ring. Both the music and the choreography were
commissioned by the festival and the John F. Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts as the last of their ``Modern Dance and Jazz Music
Collaborations.'' To see Knaack's music as jazz would take some
doing. But rhythm, no stranger to jazz, is at the pulse of this
collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   For all their robotic manner, Parkinson, Bowman, Huber and Asnes
become increasingly abstract. They symbolize the surf that Selya
rides through his high leaps as the surfer of the title.
</P>
<P>
   In an unexpected passage Selya is mocked by Asnes and Bowman,
who perform a precious dance with mincing steps on tiptoe. There is
tremendous drive here in the constant interplay between the two
male soloists and the quartet. If Selya is the leaper, Roberts is
the turner and the audience cheered as he spun in a variety of
pirouettes beyond the call of duty.
</P>
<P>
   After all the karate kicks, pelvis swiveling and ballet bravura,
the final never-neverland of healing or redemption, peace after
turmoil, hits the right note.
</P>
<P>
   The same superb performances came from the cast of ``Mozart
Clarinet Quintet K.581,'' whose music was on tape. Tuttle, on leave
from Ballet Theater, and Parkinson were in short tunics over
chartreuse leotards. Roberts, Selya and Asnes, who began the first
section, were in Chinese-style vests by Santo Loquasto.
</P>
<P>
   Here again Tharp does not reveal where her piece will go. The
lyrical male trio, moving in and out of shifting patterns, yields
to two duets that are the work's highlight: one for Tuttle and
Selya and one for Parkinson and Roberts that is amazing in its
acrobatic convolutions. The two ensemble sections, which include a
sketched-out mazurka, are a bit entangled. But there is a novelty
about the ballet that opens up the Mozart score through a mix of
playfulness and seriousness. Scott Zielinski provided the admirable
lighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
