<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7185 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOT-THEATER-REVIEW-NY     07-09 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE HOT L BALTIMORE': WILLIAMSTOWN PRODUCTION RECAPTURES
ORIGINAL'S SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. _ The girl is tireless and should, by
rights, be tiresome. There's that driving adolescent energy, to
start with, plus an unfortunate leaning to whimsy evident in her
insistence on regularly changing her name. Why, listen to her,
declaiming a list of American cities with that radioactive mix of
concentration and anarchic glee. Don't you just want to strangle
her?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, no, you don't. Nor, even more surprisingly, do any of
the characters who share the stage with her in the Williamstown
Theater Festival's affectionate new production of Lanford Wilson's
``Hot l Baltimore.''
</P>
<P>
   Played by the young actress Mandy Siegfried with the happy
unself-consciousness of a colt that has just found its legs, the
19-year-old known simply as, yes, the Girl seems to make everyone
smile, even those who feel honor-bound to despise her.
</P>
<P>
   That's still the overall effect of ``The Hot l Baltimore,'' 27
years after it opened to become the must-see off-Broadway hit,
winning New York Drama Critics Circle and Obie awards. This group
portrait of dispossessed American souls in a seedy hotel on the eve
of its demolition has always sounded impossible to stomach and been
equally impossible to resist.
</P>
<P>
   Even in 1973, reviewers remarked that the play was a throwback
to an earlier, more sentimental era of lyric drama, when William
Saroyan was serving up the dreams of the unsung and the unwanted.
Here again was a parade of lovable prostitutes and mixed nuts,
including an old man who exercised by singing opera in the lobby
and an old woman who had a close acquaintance with ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   Like Saroyan, Wilson generated a democratic glow of love for
American diversity, even as the show symbolically pointed to the
country's decline. Since it was the 1970s instead of the 1930s, it
made perfect sense when the play became the inspiration for a
sitcom on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for those who saw the original ``Hot l,'' as directed by
Marshall Mason with a cast that included the young Judd Hirsch, the
play was hardly just a sitcom in the making. Its more irritating
aspects were transformed by Wilson's and the ensemble's
``sympathetic magic,'' to borrow a term the playwright would later
use as a title, by a marrow-deep compassion and respect for the
lives portrayed. Such unconditional liking is contagious.
</P>
<P>
   The new reincarnation of ``Baltimore,'' staged by the estimable
Joe Mantello, holds on to that infectiousness. The ensemble doesn't
have the necessary rhythmic wholeness. How could it, given the
short rehearsal time at Williamstown?
</P>
<P>
   There are definitely spots of dead air amid the gloriously
shabby hotel-lobby set provided by John Lee Beatty. And those
fabled Wilson sequences of simultaneous dialogue, not unlike those
Robert Altman was creating in film at the same time, never quite
catch fire here.
</P>
<P>
   The compensations, however, are considerable. They are provided
in large part by the sense of fine actors like Lois Smith and Sam
Rockwell fully embracing their characters. Only rarely does anyone
here go for surface pathos or odd-ball cuteness. Mantello has
intelligently steered the evening's tone away from the obviously
poetic and whimsical, encouraging performances that accept
eccentricity as a matter of course.
</P>
<P>
   Take that girl, for example, the 19-year-old prostitute who,
like the father of ``The Glass Menagerie,'' has fallen in love with
long distance and spent her young life in eternal transit,
listening for the rattle of trains she can identify by their
whistles. As played by the enchanting Trish Hawkins in the original
production, she was a rather ethereal creature for someone who
traded in flesh, a fairy-tale dreamer with a hypnotic voice.
</P>
<P>
   Clad in hot pants and platform shoes that bring to mind Jodie
Foster in ``Taxi Driver'' (the sociologically ruthless costumes are
by Laura Bauer), Siegfried emphasizes the raw, overwhelming
vitality and unthinking appetite found in teen-agers. This
sharp-witted actress, seen off-Broadway in ``The Mineola Twins''
and ``Stupid Kids,'' finds her character's soul in her legs, which
seem to have restlessly flexible lives of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The Girl, of course, still has fantasies that, like those of
everyone else in Wilson's world, will never come to fruition. But
Siegfried and Mantello don't let you regard her as a pitiable
symbol. Like many people her age the Girl is, for better or worse,
a life force, existing entirely in the present. As April, the
aging, wisecracking hooker, says of dancing, in what might be the
play's watchwords: ``Nobody knows how. The important thing is to
move.''
</P>
<P>
   April is played by the invaluable Becky Ann Baker, who
definitely knows how to move, not to mention how to sell a salty
joke without shoving it down your throat. As the evening's third
and flakiest streetwalker, Cyndi Coyne is also a treat, flirting
brazenly with caricature and then retreating just in time. The same
is true of Helen Hanft, a veteran of experimental theater whose
presence sets off nostalgic echoes, and George Hall as members of
an older, increasingly lost generation.
</P>
<P>
   Smith brings a stirringly serene air of acceptance to her
spirit-communing character, an old woman with memories of an
aristocratic Southern past and someone who describes herself, in
true Wilsonian fashion, as a perpetual outsider ``with no
particular interest in peering in.'' And Rockwell is excellent as
the irritable desk clerk, a role created by Hirsch.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed as a brown-toned advertisement for everything that was
depressing about 1970s style, Rockwell never lets his period
accouterments overwhelm him, giving instead a discerningly low-key
performance. Unlike Hirsch, whose idiosyncrasies were writ large,
Rockwell fades in and out of the woodwork here, as people who have
been in one job for too long will. His character's revelation of
his own unrealized desire is all the more affecting for its
quietness.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Gilbert, an indispensable member of the brilliant ensemble
of ``Roseanne'' on television, is Jackie, the hyped-up, hustling
health food addict whose dreams are dashed most dramatically in the
play. Gilbert is likably game, but the moody intensity she
registers on camera is strangely diffused here. What should be
sustained fireworks comes across instead as a series of cap-pistol
shots.
</P>
<P>
   This is a reminder of just how much of the theater ``The Hot l
Baltimore'' is. Wilson's characters are necessarily larger than
life, because being alive is really all they have going for them.
It's not that where there's life, there's hope; these are not
hopeful people. Rather, this playwright insists that where there is
life, there is always interest. Even as its most glib and
sentimental ``The Hot l Baltimore'' still pulses with that
fascination.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE HOT L BALTIMORE'
</P>
<P>
   By Lanford Wilson; directed by Joe Mantello; sets by John Lee
Beatty; costumes by Laura Bauer; lighting by Kenneth L. Posner;
sound by Kurt B. Kellenberger; stage manager, Kelley Kirkpatrick;
production manager, Stephen Judd. Presented by the Williamstown
Theater Festival, Michael Ritchie, producer; Deborah Fehr, general
manager; Jenny C. Gersten, associate producer. At Williamstown,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   With: Sam Rockwell (Bill Lewis), Mandy Siegfried (Girl), Lois
Smith (Millie), Helen Hanft ( Bellotti), Becky Ann Baker (April
Green), George Hall (Morse), Sara Gilbert (Jackie), Justin Long
(Jamie), David Wohl ( Katz), Cyndi Coyne (Suzy), Gregor Paslawsky
(Suzy's John), Thomas Sadoski (Paul Granger III), Carol Woods
(Oxenham), Alexander R. Scott (Cabdriver), Jimmi Simpson (Delivery
Boy) and James Robert Lendman (John).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
