<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEOPLESOFT TO INTRODUCE LATEST VERSION OF PROGRAM
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft plans to introduce on Tuesday the latest version of
its ``enterprise software,'' a huge and complex program that
companies use to automate dozens of tasks. The key to the newest
version is that it will be Internet-based, meaning that employees
and customers can use the program with a Web browser instead of
tapping into an internal software program.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for PeopleSoft. Its software release is
months behind those of its competitors, Oracle and SAP. Also,
PeopleSoft is coming off a disappointing year of flat revenue and a
falling stock price.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW CAREER FOR HELEN THOMAS
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months after resigning from United Press
International, the news service where she had spent her career,
including four decades at the White House, Helen Thomas, 79, joined
Hearst Newspapers last week to write columns on the White House and
national affairs. She will write two columns, each appearing
weekly, for the company, whose papers include The Houston
Chronicle, The Seattle Post-Intelligencer and The San Francisco
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   `HARRY POTTER' BOOK SETS RECORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' the latest book in
author J.K. Rowling's popular series about the exploits of a boy
wizard, set records in its first weekend of sales, leaving many
bookstores already out of stock. The book is exactly the big,
clever, vibrant, tremendously assured installment that gives shape
and direction to the whole undertaking and still somehow preserves
the material's enchanting innocence.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER MAY RENT CHRYSLER SPACE
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler said it was considering leasing space in the
landmark Chrysler Building in New York, which could help the
company in its attempts to lure Wall Street investors.
</P>
<P>
   `BIG BROTHER' RATINGS SLIDE FURTHER
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend of sharply declining ratings, CBS' ``Big
Brother,'' the latest effort in the reality television trend, is
falling far short of the phenomenon status reached by two other
European imports, ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and CBS'
``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   A NEW KIND OF SYNERGY FOR TALK
</P>
<P>
   Ronald A. Galotti, the publisher of Talk magazine, sent a letter
to a few hundred people who can usually be depended upon to talk
about the magazine on the party circuit, asserting that ``a
magazine of Talk's caliber can only come together through valuable
partnerships'' like its cooperation with Miramax Films, which owns
half of the Talk Media venture. Another important partner, the
letter said, is Bacara, a resort hotel in California that bought
the first two pages of advertising in the August issue.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for publishers to alert select readers that a
new advertiser has bought pages. But it is rare for the publisher
to compare the new advertiser to one of its owners in terms of
importance.
</P>
<P>
   HEINZ HOPES CHILDREN LIKE GREEN
</P>
<P>
   In a move to raise sales of its ketchup, H.J. Heinz plans to
introduce a version on Monday that will be green and is intended to
appeal to children. Heinz has also come up with a bottle that it
says is easier for children to squeeze.
</P>
</TEXT>
