<DOCNO> NYT20000709.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SPRINT-PROFILE-ART-68     07-09 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-PROFILE-ART-685&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRELESS UNIT MAKES SPRINT A LIKELY TAKEOVER TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mention the word ``footprint'' and images of an ill-fated
Himalayan expedition in search of the yeti might come to people's
minds. But when you mention footprint to those familiar with Sprint
Corp., their eyes light up with optimism.
</P>
<P>
   In the argot of the mobile telecommunications world,
``footprint'' refers to the breadth of network coverage, and
perhaps no company has matched Sprint during the last couple of
years in its speed and efficiency at building a nationwide wireless
communications business.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, even if the company's $115 billion merger agreement
with WorldCom unravels, Sprint's wireless network remains a coveted
asset.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators in Europe oppose the WorldCom-Sprint deal on grounds
that it would leave WorldCom with too much control of Internet
traffic, while the Justice Department says it would leave too few
long-distance options. But Sprint is still expected to have
attentive suitors _ possibly Deutsche Telekom, BellSouth, and
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone _ attracted by its wireless prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprint has almost everything that a company wanting to expand
in the U.S. would want,'' said Brian Hayward, manager of the $3.6
billion Invesco Telecommunications Fund in Denver. ``But what
really makes it attractive is extensive digital nationwide wireless
coverage, because that's where many people are betting the future
is at.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS, the company's wireless subsidiary, operates the
largest all-digital wireless network in the United States, covering
an area that reaches more than 70 percent of the population. Aided
by revenue from wireless Internet services that were recently
introduced, Sprint PCS' average monthly revenue per user is $54,
which is 30 percent higher than the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   Although in terms of subscribers, Sprint's wireless network
ranks fourth behind those of Verizon Wireless, SBC/BellSouth and
AT&AMP;T Wireless, the company has led the wireless industry in
subscriber growth for six consecutive quarters.
</P>
<P>
   With its own retail stores, and an aggressive distribution
effort involving more than 12,000 third-party retail outlets that
include Tandy's Radio Shack chain and Best Buy, Sprint signed up an
additional 876,000 customers in the first quarter of this year, an
18 percent increase from the comparable period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect such subscriber growth to continue, with Sprint
signing up as many as 4 million customers this year, accounting for
about 20 percent of the industry's growth in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's built a wireless network that has a lot of buzz
around it with such high-visibility growth, Sprint's an obvious
takeover play if WorldCom exits the scene,'' said Steve Shook, a
telecommunications analyst at Wachovia Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Sprint, based in Westwood, Kan., received merger
overtures from BellSouth, which was eventually outbid by WorldCom.
But the interest of BellSouth, based in Atlanta, could be rekindled
by the possibility of assembling a seamless network that would
theoretically allow a caller to use the same mobile phone from
coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   And the interest of the German communications giant, Deutsche
Telekom, has been more than explicit. The possibility of a German
bid for Sprint has already elicited a reaction from Senate leaders,
who oppose such a deal on the grounds that it might violate a law
preventing the Federal Communications Commission from transferring
radio licenses to companies that are more than 25 percent owned by
foreign governments. Cellular operators use radio waves under
license from the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said that opposition to such a deal might wilt if
the German government were to reiterate its stated intent to reduce
its stake in Deutsche Telekom, Europe's largest telecommunications
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It flies in the face of everything the United States stands
for in promoting free markets around the world for our own
government to oppose investment by a foreign telecommunications
company, whether it's state-owned or not,'' said Frank Marsala, a
telecommunications analyst at ING Barings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sprint is seeking to balance market enthusiasm for
its wireless operations with concern about a management transition
at Sprint PCS. Andrew Sukawaty, who is credited as the driving
force behind much of the Sprint PCS strategy during the last
several years, announced in May that he would step down as chief
executive of the wireless business to pursue business opportunities
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's chief operating officer, Ronald T. LeMay, is serving as
acting president of the wireless unit while a search for a new
Sprint PCS chief gets under way. LeMay and Sprint's chairman,
William T. Esrey, declined to comment on efforts to replace
Sukawaty.
</P>
<P>
   How fast Sprint becomes a takeover target depends on how quickly
its fate is untangled from WorldCom's. By then, Sprint could find
itself competing for attention among other wireless carriers, like
VoiceStream Wireless and Nextel Communications, which have also
been discussed as targets in the nation's fast-consolidating
wireless industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much attention is focused right now on the U.S. wireless
market because of the growth potential that exists here,'' said
Larry Swasey, vice president for communications research at Allied
Business Intelligence. ``Sprint probably offers a nice foothold for
expansion into the U.S., but it's a competitive marketplace with
several opportunities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-00 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000709.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-POTTER-REVIEW0710-COX     07-09 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTTER-REVIEW0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harry Potter and the 734-Page Behemoth
 &HT;    By Jeff Salamon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ J.K. Rowling is fascinated by curses and spells
and suchlike, so here, in case she's interested, is the six-word
incantation that could make her the most hated woman in the Western
world:
</P>
<P>
   And then Harry Potter woke up.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling is too resourceful an artist to ever set those words to
paper, and Harry Potter fans who haven't already made their way
through the fourth book in the series can rest assured that at no
point in ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'' does Rowling have
her boy hero wipe the sleep out of his eyes, look at his friends
and family and say, ``Cousin Dudley _ you were a mean little boy
named Draco Malfoy! And Uncle Vernon _ you were his father, a Death
Eater named Lucius! And Bill Gates! Bill Gates! You were Lord
Voldemort, the most evil and powerful wizard of all!''
</P>
<P>
   Rowling never stoops to the sort of mollycoddling that lesser
children's-book writers fall back on when they fear a narrative has
grown too disturbing for their young readers. Like the Brothers
Grimm before their stories were sanitized by 20th-century
animators, Rowling plays for keeps _ as readers of ``Goblet'' will
find by story's end.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a clear element of wish-fulfillment is at the heart of
the Potter series. At the start of each book, the orphaned Potter
is living with his aunt, uncle and cousin, a dim trio of
middle-class nogoodniks who force him to sleep in a cupboard
beneath the stairway. Harry is scrawny, bespectacled, has no
friends of note, and bears a disfiguring scar on his forehead, a
residue of the same car accident that killed his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the first book, ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's
Stone,'' as Harry is falling asleep, he remembers when he was
younger and ``dreamed and dreamed of some unknown relation coming
to take him away.'' Which, of course, is basically what happens in
the next two chapters _ a large, uncouth man named Hagrid shows up
to bring Harry to Hogwarts, a school for young wizards. Harry's
parents, he explains, weren't killed in a car crash _ they were
wizards murdered by the evil Voldemort, and Harry's scar was
received when he somehow survived the battle.
</P>
<P>
   At Hogwarts, Harry is as honored as he was mistreated at the
Dursleys' (to whose house he must return every summer). He quickly
learns that he is famous, that he is special, that he is powerful.
The secret life all sad children share _ an imaginary counterlife
in which they have unique talents, are descended from greatness,
and even their weaknesses qualify as a sort of offbeat wisdom _ is
the stuff of the Harry Potter series, and surely accounts for much
of its popularity.
</P>
<P>
   But Rowling, to her credit, isn't satisfied merely to coo at her
young audience's inner Prozac client. As the series goes on, it
becomes clear that Harry won't be able to coast on his gift.
</P>
<P>
   For all its surface pleasures (and make no mistake, Rowling can
be a very funny writer) the first Potter book, ``The Sorcerer's
Stone,'' was mildly unsatisfying _ at least to the adult reader. No
sooner did Potter face a crisis than Rowling would resolve it, well
before a sense of dread could embed itself in the narrative. As
most occult literature worthy of the name makes clear, the exercise
of magic power always comes at a cost _ or at least a risk. And
Rowling's universe seemed a frictionless place.
</P>
<P>
   But as the series has unfolded, her plan has become clearer. In
the first books, she was repairing Harry's wounded ego. By last
year's ``Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban'' and,
especially, ``Goblet,'' Harry is going through the first steps of
adult character formation _ the willingness to sacrifice for
others, to act rationally in the face of anger, to put off instant
gratification for long-term payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Such lessons are hard-learned, and though Rowling gets off some
funny lines in the margins of her narrative (``Miss Granger remains
the only person in this class who has managed to turn a hedgehog
into a satisfactory pincushion. I might remind you that your
pincushion, Thomas, still curls up in fright if anyone approaches
it with a pin!''), ``Goblet'' is a genuinely dark book, complete
with oozing sores, dismemberment and murders that might be too much
for the 5-year-olds said to be among Harry's fans (though maybe
``Goosebumps'' has already inured them to this sort of thing). Even
some of Harry's closest friendships begin to strain under the
weight of class differences, hidden agendas, and _ in case you
doubted these children are now teen-agers _ sexual jealousy. Unless
I miss my guess, in the next (and, apparently, last) three books,
Harry will grow stronger and begin to feel the tug of Voldemort's
worldview, the pitiless logic of self-justification that the
powerful call Truth and the rest of us call Evil.
</P>
<P>
   There's been much hullabaloo about the size of ``Goblet''; each
book in the series is longer then the previous, and at 734 pages
``Goblet'' is a big leap from ``Azkaban's'' 435. Overindulgent, the
naysayers have whispered, wondering if success hasn't gone to
Rowling's head. But ``Goblet'' moves along steadily enough, and by
confronting her young readers with such a tome, Rowling has given
them the opportunity to develop their powers of reading as Harry
develops his powers of sorcery.
</P>
<P>
   At Book People's Friday night party for the ``Goblet''
unveiling, I felt a twinge of envy when our host asked one little
girl how long she planned to take to read the book. ``Two weeks,''
the little girl said into the microphone. I wasn't jealous just
because I was going to spend the next 32 hours plowing my through
the book so I could hit a Sunday review deadline, but because I
remembered how long it had been since I got lost in literature, the
way children do.
</P>
<P>
   Tolkien's Middle Earth, Asimov's Foundation universe, Lewis'
Narnia: They were places you took up residence in, and unless you
were a precociously fast reader, for a long time. The schoolday
kept you busy until 3, sports until 5, dinner, homework and TV
until bedtime, and then, until lights out (and maybe, if you could
get away with it, well past), you'd dive into the book on your
night table before drifting off to sleep. And then, through the
whole school-sports-dinner-homework cycle the next day, find
yourself daydreaming about that other world, constructing fanciful
versions of what
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
