   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON _WASHINGTON _ President Clinton goes to Camp
David Sunday forwhat's likely to be his last clean shot at a high
stakes foreign policy win to burnish a legacy stained by scandal.
While he'll continue for the rest of his term to juggle an armful
of international issues _ China trade, national missile defense,
Balkans peacekeeping among them _ no other initiative has consumed
so much of his time, so captured the imagination of the public or
is so ripe for completion as the quest to end half a century of
conflict between Israelis and Palestinians. Appropriate to the
stakes for himself and for history, Clinton has chosen a venue rich
in symbolism and resonant with hope. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-FUNDING _ ANN ARBOR, Mich._ Pioneer High School in Ann
Arbor offers its 2,400 students 27 varsity sports, including water
polo and synchronized swimming in a 14-lane, 25-meter pool built
just two years ago. The academic
</P>
<P>
   curriculum boasts classes in guitar, Latin and advanced jewelry
design. Career-track programs include culinary arts, cosmetology
and home building. Ten miles to the north, the Whitmore Lake Public
Schools enrolls a scant 290 high school students district-wide. All
elementary, middle and high school students go to school in
side-by-side buildings that also include the superintendent's
office. Course offerings and extracurricular programs are limited.
(Dayton Daily News) 45.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the first in a series of three stories on education
funding running Sunday-Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-PRISONS _ STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ Ohio may not have to build
another prison for at least a decade, state officials said Sunday,
after remarks by retired Gen. Colin Powell who urged the nation's
governors to invest more in children, not prisons. ``Hopefully we
have built our last prison for the next 10 years,'' said Reginald
Wilkinson, director of Ohio's Department of Rehabilitation and
Correction. ``Gen. Powell is right. We need to be building up kids,
not jails, so they develop character and never end up in a
prison.'' Powell was keynote speaker at the National Governor's
Association
</P>
<P>
   conference, which runs through Tuesday and is being attended by
38 governors, including Ohio Gov. Bob Taft. The conference,
centered on state's taking advantage of the new economy, continues
today with an address from President Clinton on health care.
(Dayton Daily News) 16.
</P>
<P>
   ALZHEIMER'S _ WASHINGTON _ A study of twins supports previous
research indicating that education may protect against Alzheimer's
disease and other forms of dementia, scientists reported at a
meeting here of dementia researchers. Meeting is continue through
July 18. (Nesmith, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP _ WASHINGTON _ The NAACP convention in Baltimore is next
on the presidential candidate's summer tour. President Clinton also
speaks. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   DRYBUGS _ ATLANTA _ In their relentless search for water during
the ongoing drought, bugs are heading indoors _ into bathtubs,
under kitchen sinks, into air conditioning units. (Sanbury, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVEDOPED/EDITORIALGARCIA-COLUMN _ AUSTIN,
Texas _ Largely overlooked in the coverage of the Mexican
presidential election is the grace with which incumbent President
Ernesto Zedillo and losing candidate Francisco Labastida accepted
the results. Zedillo and Labastida, ranking members of the Party of
the Institutional Revolution (PRI) were both class acts as the
results came in with surprising swiftness _ not to mention clarity
_ July 2. (Arnold Garcia is editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Ever heard of snorkeling in North
Georgia? Talk to Brent Martin. Snorkeling on the Conasauga River in
the state's northwest corner is one of the joys the former history
teacher counts in the career change he made five years ago. ``Oh
man,'' Martin exclaims, ``it's like being in an aquarium.''
(Ezzard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
