   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   NETSCAPE-BROWSER _ MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. _ A tongue-in-cheek
shrine commands a second-story wall at Netscape Communications
Corp.: collages of cut-out photos, articles, cartoons and e-mail
jokes ripping Microsoft Corp. founder Bill Gates. Deep in the heart
of the Netscape engineering department, where software writers
create the Navigator browser, the anti-tribute is a motivational
tool of sorts. The enemy's in sight, but he's stripped of his
imposing aura. (Cocks, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   COMICS _ After crushing every cosmic threat conceivable, comic
book heroes like the Fantastic Four and Captain America are
fighting for their own future _ which may be downloadable. Costumed
crimefighters that have thrived for years on the pages of comic
books are in need of a hero themselves. Comics sales are plummeting
and rival forms of entertainment, including computer games and the
Internet, are drawing away potential readers. But comic publishers
are now looking to the same technology for a rescue. (Fernandez,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COMICS-SIDE _ Comics may not be big business themselves, but
they're worth millions to the corporations that own them. These
movies, TV shows and merchandising bonanzas all were spun off of
comics: Men In Black, Sabrina the Teenage Witch, Teenage Mutant
Ninja Turtles, Spawn, The Mask. (Fernandez, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-BASEBALL _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Buck O'Neil was playing
for the Kansas City Monarchs of the Negro Leagues in the 1930s and
1940s, the love for baseball spilled over onto the streets. The
Hall of Famer O'Neil, teammate of Hall of Fame pitcher Satchel
Paige, remembers watching black children in the city neighborhoods
playing stickball, imagining themselves as the next Paige or
O'Neil. (Gutierrez, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOMERUNS _ Everybody's got a theory, but none is more hands-on
than Aaron Boutwell's. Boutwell works for Rawlings, and this week
the marketing manager is spending his days hand-stitching baseballs
for rapt audiences at the John Hancock All-Star FanFest at the
Georgia World Congress Center. If you want to know why so many
baseballs are flying out of parks this year, Boutwell starts his
argument with a bat, which, under any circumstances, is a hard
argument to lose. (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
