<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELEN THOMAS IS BACK AS A COLUMNIST WITH HEARST 
ELLE DECOR EDITOR JUMPS TO HOUSE BEAUTIFUL 
TALK FINDS NEW SYNERGY, OR IS IT JUST SOAP?
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four decades in the White House covering the assassination of
John F. Kennedy, the humiliations of Richard M. Nixon and the
indiscretions of Bill Clinton did not leave Helen Thomas feeling
disillusioned, jaded or in need of rest. It left her longing to
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to be there every day,'' said Thomas, the unofficial
doyenne of the White House press corps. ``I sort of consider it
almost a second office.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months after resigning from United Press
International, the wire service where she had spent her career, the
79-year-old journalist joined Hearst Newspapers last week to write
columns on the White House and other national affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas worked at UPI for 57 years, surmounting discrimination
against women in the newsroom to become the organization's most
famous correspondent. But she quit in May, the day after a company
controlled by the Rev. Sun Myung Moon, founder of the Unification
Church, bought the wire service. ``It was a bridge too far,''
Thomas recalled last week.
</P>
<P>
   After her abrupt departure, she had doubts about working again.
Not that she wanted to retire. At her age, she simply thought it
might be hard to find a job. ``I was amazed,'' Thomas said. ``I had
no idea I would have so many nice offers.''
</P>
<P>
   She will write two columns a week for a company whose papers
include The Houston Chronicle, The Seattle Post-Intelligencer and
The San Francisco Examiner. One of her weekly columns will recount
the many political anecdotes she has amassed. The other will tackle
the issues of the day: families without health insurance, children
in poverty, guns and violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outrage, that's my adrenaline,'' she said. ``People should be
reminded of the injustices around them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Greg Winter
</P>
<P>
   Elle Decor Editor Jumps to House Beautiful
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything more important in the world of interior design
than the new popularity of the $10,000 AGA 59-inch radiant-surface
cooker stove? Any story more pressing than the sad decline of
chintz? What about the befuddling hegemony of Restoration Hardware
chic?
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that could eclipse such decorating puzzlements is
having the top editor of one home-design magazine jump ship for
another. Marian McEvoy, the editor in chief of Elle Decor,
published by the Hachette Filipacchi Magazines unit of Lagardere,
resigned on Thursday to take over House Beautiful, a 104-year-old
publication owned by Hearst Magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Oliver Gropp, House Beautiful's longtime editor in chief,
who favored features on traditional decorating styles, announced
his retirement in May. McEvoy made her mark at Elle Decor by
featuring stories on a starker aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for McEvoy will be to reconcile her more eclectic
sensibility _ she has used a glue gun to cover entire rooms of her
apartment with seashells, for instance _ with the expectations of
House Beautiful's 876,262 readers.
</P>
<P>
   Her appointment could significantly weaken Elle Decor, which has
441,122 readers, and no clear candidate in mind to replace her.
</P>
<P>
   It will also affect House &AMP; Garden, the other large home-design
magazine. Published by the Conde Nast unit of Advance Publications,
House &AMP; Garden has a circulation of 770,325, but newsstand sales
dipped 18.7 percent the last six months of 1999, according to the
Audit Bureau of Circulations.
</P>
<P>
   McEvoy said she had not made any editorial decisions yet. ``It
is certainly a big challenge to have more readers,'' she said.
``You have to be clever about addressing the needs of more readers.
And we love cleverness. We've got lots of cleverness.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Alex Kuczynski
</P>
<P>
   Talk Finds New Synergy, or Is It Just Soap?
</P>
<P>
   First, synergy. Now, miniature bath soap.
</P>
<P>
   When Talk magazine was introduced a year ago, the editor in
chief, Tina Brown, discussed the potential for cooperative efforts
with Miramax Films, which owns half of the Talk Media venture.
</P>
<P>
   The Miramax relationship came up again in a letter from Talk
Media's president, Ronald A. Galotti, to what is known at Talk as
``Tina's hot list'' _ a few hundred people who, apart from those in
the news media, include demicelebrities and so-called A-list people
who can usually be depended upon to talk about the magazine on the
party circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Galotti's letter last week asserted that ``a magazine of Talk's
caliber can only come together through valuable partnerships'' and
pointed out how, for example, Talk has ``embraced its multimedia
partnership with Miramax Films.''
</P>
<P>
   And as of August, Galotti's letter went on, Talk magazine will
have a yet another corporate ``association.'' This one is not with
a company that is an owner of the magazine, nor is it even with a
media company; it is with Bacara, a resort hotel in California that
is not yet open. Galotti's letter was accompanied by a pamphlet
promoting the creature comforts of the resort. (``In-room spa
services. Bathrobes and slippers. Luxurious bathroom amenities.'')
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for magazine publishers to alert select
readers that a new advertiser has bought pages in the magazine. But
it is rare for the publisher to compare the new advertiser to one
of its owners in terms of importance. In this instance, a hotel
does not offer the synergistic opportunities for film-making,
screenwriting or developing young talent that Miramax, a unit of
Walt Disney, does.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members at Talk say that Bacara, as an incentive to
advertise, was offered the sweetener that the publisher would
promote the hotel to a select group of Hollywood heavyweights. And
Bacara accepted, buying the first two pages of advertising in
Talk's August issue.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Talk needs ad pages. According to an independent
count (Talk's ad pages are not yet monitored by the Publishing
Information Bureau), it started with 126.3 ad pages in its first
issue last September but dipped to 48.6 pages in February, 70.8 in
April, 41.3 in March and 36.1 in the June/July issue.
</P>
<P>
   Galotti was unavailable for comment. Hilary Bass, a spokeswoman
for Talk, said that the relationship with Bacara should not be
construed as a corporate partnership _ even if Galotti had compared
it in depth and importance to the magazine's tie to Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new association is standard procedure,'' Bass said. ``This
is just to show that they are a new advertiser in the magazine and
we hope to do more business with them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Alex Kuczynski
</P>
</TEXT>
