<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7203 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-WIMBLEDON-VENUS0709-C     07-09 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-VENUS0709-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Venus generates media flurry
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Richard Williams might have called it
``Venus' Party'' on his hand-written sign, but she didn't have much
time for the celebration after winning her first Grand Slam title
at Wimbledon on Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams turned into a media belle the moment she leapt in
victory at Centre Court. Photographers immediately started
recording images that would fill the morning papers in London,
across the ocean in their U.S. home and all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Many headlines in England played on Venus' first name. ``Venus
In Orbit'' read the front of the Sunday Times' sports section,
while the Sunday Mirror called her ``Venus de Smile'' and
``Victory-V. Venus on a different planet as she wins it by a
smile.''
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as the trophies had been awarded Venus and runner-up
Lindsay Davenport, the interviews began for Venus. She handled 15
engagements for 11 individual media outlets, plus a group interview
and group photo shoot for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Her television obligations included the BBC, NBC, Turner, ESPN
and stations from South America, Germany and Spain. She also talked
with USA Today and Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   That ended her work on Saturday and she was free to continue
hugging her trophy or to eat a good meal or celebrate in any other
way.
</P>
<P>
   But she wasn't free much more 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m., Venus and sister Serena Williams _ a singles
semifinalist ousted by Venus and doubles finalist with Venus _ were
due on the golf course across the street from the club to do an
interview via satellite for a Sky News show called ``Sunday with
Boulton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very big thing in London,'' said WTA spokeswoman
Raquel Martin, who is based in Europe. ``He talks to the biggest
politicians and celebrities.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the sisters went to a house in Wimbledon village
owned by IMG to tape a segment for ``Good Morning, America'' that
will air this morning. They spent about 15 minutes there, then
returned to the club grounds for a joint session with a company
that does an annual Wimbledon documentary for the tournament's
museum.
</P>
<P>
   They finished about noon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Venus went to buy shoes for the ball,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Venus named the fact that she bought a gown for the famed
Wimbledon Champions Dinner before she left Palm Beach Gardens as
motivation for her victory here. She wouldn't reveal details about
the dress _ except that it has beads _ but hoped to show it off at
the 10:30 p.m. ball Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was held at the Savoy Hotel in central London, considered one
of the city's ``poshest'' hotels. Singles finalists each received a
table so the Williams' entourage all was expected. Others among the
approximately 400 invited included All England Club members, former
singles champions, seniors participants and the presidents of the
international tennis federations.
</P>
<P>
   But if Venus and Serena went, they probably didn't stay long.
The doubles final they had expected to play Sunday afternoon was
postponed until today because of heavy rain that delayed the men's
final between Pete Sampras and Patrick Rafter for hours.
</P>
<P>
   That match ended four minutes before 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the eighth-seeded Williams sisters will play fourth seeds
Julie Halard-Decugis and Ai Sugiyama at noon today. They'll be
seeking another history-making day, as they try to become the first
all-black doubles team to win Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
