<HEADER>
A7204 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHINA-EXAM-NYT &LR;      07-09 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-EXAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `BLACK JULY,' A SINGLE TEST DETERMINES FATE OF CHINA'S
STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Madly poring over notes one last time, giddy after
months of dawn-to-midnight cramming, the students skittered into
the exam site, a Beijing high school.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the school gates, hundreds of parents just stood and
stared for hours, fanning themselves furiously, as if to dissipate
their tension along with the muggy summer heat.
</P>
<P>
   This is ``Black July'' in China, time for the long-anticipated
single exam that determines who goes to college in a country where
a degree is seen as a ticket to prosperity, and failure can mean
consignment to drudgery.
</P>
<P>
   The 4 million high school seniors who took the entrance exam
these past three days across China have worlds riding on the
outcome _ what rank of college they may enter, or whether they can
attend college at all.
</P>
<P>
   Their parents, many of whom were robbed of a chance at higher
education by the turmoil of Mao's Cultural Revolution, are often
more nervous than their offspring, and have at least as much
invested in the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our time, young people had to go work in the countryside,''
said Zhang Mei, whose 19-year-old daughter and only child, Li Hui,
hopes to study business management and somberly called the exam ``a
turning point in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhang and her husband were among those who missed out on college
in Mao's upheaval, and then, as things returned to normal in the
late 1970s, were held to a single child by newly stringent family
planning rules. So their daughter is the repository of stifled
dreams. ``We weren't well educated,'' said Zhang, who works in a
railway personnel office. ``But to make it in society these days
you just have to go to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a growing number of parents, Zhang and her husband splurged
to rent an air-conditioned hotel room near their daughter's
assigned test site, so she would have a comfortable place to rest
between sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really big event in her life,'' Zhang said. ``She
needs to be relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some classmates, though, her daughter decided not to
supplement her fierce studying with much-advertised pills like
``Brain Relaxer'' or ``Never Forget,'' fish-oil products said to
improve blood flow in the brain and to enhance memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more nervous than my daughter,'' said Yan Yanan, one of
the furiously fanning mothers waiting outside the Chen Jinglun High
School, one of 77 testing sites in Beijing, and another parent
whose own educational hopes were crushed by Maoist excess. ``I'm
worried that she might fail, or have to go to a second-rate
university, but college has become a `must' these days.''
</P>
<P>
   In just one sign of the importance attached to this exam, the
Beijing city government banned nearly all night-time construction
work for the last few weeks, lest any student's concentration be
disturbed. The city also set up a special hotline for noise
complaints. Newspapers have been filled with admonitions not to put
pressure on the students, about ideal diets and even strategies for
how to avoid traffic jams en route to the test.
</P>
<P>
   In the five-part exam, universally agreed to be murderous,
everyone must take the tests in Chinese, English and math and then
must choose either the science track, involving tests in chemistry
and physics or the liberal arts track, with tests in politics and
history.
</P>
<P>
   According to government projections, only about half of the
test-takers - themselves an elite who tested into academic high
schools after junior high - will gain entry to college. Overall,
because of the scarcity of slots, only about 12 percent of young
adults in China can attend college, a far lower share than in most
Western countries, which only enhances the value of a degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``This exam is like a big mountain in front of you,'' said He
Jianming, a Beijing writer who just published a book about its
social impact. ``If you get over the top, you'll see a bright
future, the pot of gold. If you fail, your life seems to be at an
end.''
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, most of those taking the exam will find their way to
college _ preferably, of course, into the most prestigious schools
like Beijing University or Qinghua, China's equivalents of Harvard
and MIT.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are incomparably higher for students in smaller towns
and rural areas, for whom a good score can mean the difference
between a life with open horizons _ including the prized right to
live and work in a big city _ and a life of near-certain hardship.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Guangli knows all about the pressures and potential
payoffs. In 1985, as a student from a poor farm town in Sichuan
province, he tested brilliantly, escaped to a university in
Shanghai and is now a successful documentary filmmaker in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My classmates who didn't pass have horrible lives now,'' he
said bluntly. Most of them, he said, either remained as poor
farmers or became migrant workers in the cities, holding menial
jobs at best.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, Wang flew back to his hometown of Meishan to
help his nephew, Zhao Hao, prepare for the exam. He did this, Wang
said, not to tutor the boy _ he had already studied 16 hours a day
for months _ but to help him relax in the final hours by talking
about anything but chemistry and math.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of what he hopes will be his ticket to a legal
career, the nephew sounded more philosophical than his uncle.
``They say all roads lead to Rome,'' the boy said by telephone.
``But I think the college exam is a shortcut.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone complains about the iron rule of this single,
standardized test and the way it distorts young people's lives and
the curriculum they study. Yet the exam, which prolongs a venerable
imperial tradition of examinations for high office, is also seen as
a relatively fair and honest way to hand out scarce college places.
And with the existing curriculum so intertwined with the exam,
change comes hard.
</P>
<P>
   But complaints are growing about the system's discrimination in
favor of already privileged residents of Beijing and Shanghai. Many
universities, including the nation's finest, are located in these
two cities and a disproportionate number of their slots are
allocated to local residents.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Beijing students are admitted to good universities
with scores far below those of students from large provinces like
Hunan or Hubei who may find no college spot at all.
</P>
<P>
   While the exam still provides a way for smart students from poor
families to crack into the elite, its equalizing effect is also
undermined by the rising tuition and other fees charged by public
universities. Since they know their families could never raise the
$1,000 a year or more that is required to attend college these
days, He said, some bright students do not even bother to enroll
for the entrance exam, while others score high but cannot take
advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   Children from better-off families, even if they test abysmally,
can also pay to attend one of the hundreds of generally second-rate
private colleges that have sprung up to meet the demand for college
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In the final days of July, students will learn their test
scores. Those who don't make it to college have a dismal fallback:
they can try again next ``Black July,'' in fact every July until
they turn 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
