<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-BROTHER-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS'S `BIG BROTHER' TRAILS IN THE TV RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a weekend of sharply declining ratings, CBS's ``Big
Brother,'' the latest effort in the reality television trend, is
falling far short of the phenomenon status reached by two other
European imports, ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' and CBS's
``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, without a turnaround in its downward momentum, ``Big
Brother'' runs the risk of becoming a hugely expensive flop.
</P>
<P>
   After a big rating for the show's first episode on Wednesday,
ratings dropped precipitously every night for the episodes on
Thursday, Friday and Saturday. The show lost more than 40 percent
of its rating on Thursday night. On Friday, based on ratings for
the nation's biggest cities, which approximate what the national
rating will be, it dropped an additional 25 percent. And Saturday,
again based on those ratings from the biggest cities, ``Big
Brother'' lost 20 percent and sank to the status of an also-ran,
beaten by a repeat movie on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   National ratings will be available Monday. But the trend for the
show was clear from the so-called overnight ratings from the
biggest cities. On Friday, ``Big Brother'' scored a 6.1 rating. It
had scored a 13.9 on Wednesday in the national ratings and an 8 on
Thursday. Each national rating point represents just over one
million homes.
</P>
<P>
   The 6.1 overnight rating Friday was still good enough for ``Big
Brother'' to claim leadership in its 8 p.m. time period. But two
other shows later that evening, ``Dateline'' on NBC and ``20/20''
on ABC, both scored much higher ratings, an 8.4 and a 7.3
respectively. The other reality shows that became hits as summer
series, ``Millionaire'' and ``Survivor,'' have both consistently
beaten everything else on the nights they have been on.
</P>
<P>
   The news for CBS got much worse on Saturday night. The overnight
rating for ``Big Brother'' plunged to just a 4.85 for an hourlong
episode. (Thursday and Friday's shows were each a half-hour). That
was not even good enough to win the time period in the overnight
ratings. ``Ground Control,'' a repeat of a movie on ABC, managed a
4.9 for that hour. The movie eventually averaged a 5.3 for two
hours. ``Big Brother'' also trailed other shows on later in the
evening, a repeat of ``NYPD Blue'' on ABC and ``America's Most
Wanted'' on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is worrisome for CBS because the network spent $20
million to acquire rights to ``Big Brother,'' which has been a hit
in Holland, Spain and Germany, and CBS committed to running the
series for 89 nights this summer. Having seen the ratings decline
every night for the first four shows, CBS now has 85 more nights to
go. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-00 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000709.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RACE-FILM-ESSAY-(1200     07-09 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-FILM-ESSAY-(1200)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: VULGARITY HELPS WHEN PLAYING THE RACE CARD FOR LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It struck me, while laughing my way through ``Me, Myself and
Irene,'' that its creators may be the only comic filmmakers in
America who truly find white people at least as preposterous as
they find black people. And given that they are white, this is a
real accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been deduced from what the writing-directing trio
of Peter Farrelly, Bobby Farrelly and Mike Cerrone did with (and
to) the white characters of ``Dumb and Dumber'' and ``There's
Something About Mary.'' Such goings on! Such rambunctious ids and
demented egos! But whites are rarely considered ``white'' until
nonwhite characters show up on the same screen.
</P>
<P>
   I did remember seeing a black midget in the trailer for
``Irene,'' but he was attacking Jim Carrey first with his tiny
fists and then with a nightstick. It was easy to think, ``Well,
boys will be brats'' and go on about one's business. After all, the
midget was cited in passing, if at all, in most reviews as just one
more example of compulsive cinematic vulgarity, along with sex
toys, barnyard animals and toilet jokes.
</P>
<P>
   But vulgarity can be the best weapon against a standing army of
platitudes and pieties. Bless that midget. He is a loud, paranoid
cabdriver who picks a pointless fight with Charlie (Carrey), the
sweet state trooper who is about to escort his new bride over the
threshold of their home. Surely the joke is on political
correctness, you think, as he rants on about bigotry (It's racism!
It's a small people thing!) in his ghetto voice.
</P>
<P>
   But our midget is also a graduate student at Brown and a chapter
president of Mensa, the self-described organization ``for bright
people'' whose sole qualification for membership is a high IQ.
Charlie's lithe blonde bride is a Mensa chapter president also. The
two lock eyes and eventually end up running away together, leaving
Charlie with three black sons (Anthony Anderson, Mongo Brownlee and
Jerod Mixon). And since he refuses to acknowledge that the triplets
were fathered by the black midget, he refuses to acknowledge that
they are black.
</P>
<P>
   Do you remember ``My Three Sons'' with Fred MacMurray as the
wrly avuncular TV dad? The home scenes here are demented episodes
of that show, with MacMurray's confident wryness turned slightly
anxious and _ when he tosses a few ``soul'' expressions their way _
ingratiating. It is nice racial trompe l'oeil that the actors
playing the triplets don't really resemble one another much more
than they resemble Carrey. True, they're all big, and they're all
about the same shade of brown. (Carrey and a number of male cast
members are tall and all about the same shade of pale beige.)
</P>
<P>
   The boys banter like street thugs, love and honor their father,
and trade competitive chaff _ shall we say signify on each other _
about physics problems and SAT scores. One brother protests that he
got 1,430 out of a possible 1,600 points because he had the flu.
You'd have to have an aneurysm to get 1430 he is told with cheerful
disdain.
</P>
<P>
   Is it believable that black triplets who talk like street thugs
(or rappers) can be top students and good sons? Let's look at it
this way. In 1967, when Sidney Poitier played a distinguished
scientist who is a candidate for a Nobel Prize in Stanley Kramer's
film about interracial love and courtship, ``Guess Who's Coming to
Dinner,'' how many people found it believable? Viewers and
reviewers both complained about the lack of realism. Why did
Poitier's character have to be so dazzlingly exceptional, they kept
asking? It strained credibility.
</P>
<P>
   And it isn't as if the intervening 33 years have brought us a
spate of movies in which blacks are terrifically smart and
confident about much beyond their clothes, their sexual prowess or
their criminal records. (And clearly we're talking about men here.
There haven't been a lot of movies in which black women played
anything that could be called a leading role.)
</P>
<P>
   So I loved these vaudevillian whiz kids. Ditto the jungle-fever
kisses exchanged by the black midget and the full-size blonde as
they drove off together. ``I guess the heart wants what the heart
wants,'' she tells Charlie. And it's true of comedy, too. However
outrageous the situation, once it compels our laughter, we've let
it into our world. The absurd wouldn't matter if we didn't know it
was the shadow side _ disdained, longed for, or both _ of the
normal.
</P>
<P>
   The actors playing the whiz kid sons as vaudeville join a long
line of black comics who started out in late-19th-century minstrel
shows and worked like mad to turn a style that signified the
bumptious, the bombastic and the genetically inept into an
innovative form of verbal and physical comedy. Of course the
triplets watch Richard Pryor and Chris Rock on television.
</P>
<P>
   And so does their Daddy, which is just right in terms of comic
genealogies. Carrey got his first real break in 1990 as one of two
white performers on ``In Living Color,'' the Wayans Brothers'
raucous black comedy show.
</P>
<P>
   And he out-minstreled everyone in sight. He was shameless and
outrageous: a white fool or a maniac who kept his white face on at
all times. Steve Martin had given us a sweeter less staccato
version of the white minstrel in his early years; it was no
accident that in his first movie, ``The Jerk,'' he played a
character who thought he had been born black.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Old-time vaudeville made fun of most white ethnics for a time:
the Irish, the Italians, the Germans, the Jews, sometimes playing
themselves and sometimes playing one another. And there have been
plenty of comics since who played dumb, dumber and dumbest with
gusto, from Lou Costello to Tommy Smothers and Dick Martin; from
Art Carney as Ed Norton on ``The Honeymooners'' to Jerry Lewis at
his most infantile and Dean Martin at his most mentally woozy.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Carrey who keeps the race engine fueled and running.
And he's wonderful here as the man with two inadequate
personalities: Charlie, the sweet, repressed sap, and Hank, the
mellifluously crude bully. Every muscle of his face and every bone
in his body are utterly committed to these alternating bouts of
mousiness and mania.
</P>
<P>
   People keep saying that since the script for ``Me, Myself and
Irene'' was written 10 years ago, the Farrellys dragged it out of
their drawer and tossed it cynically onto a movie screen because
they knew they were on a roll. I won't overstate things by
insisting that we have a masterpiece of radical entertainment here,
especially since the movie drifts into a formula feel-good rescue
and happy ending. But really could they have gotten it made with
all the racial nose-thumbing intact before they became famous?
</P>
<P>
   Interracial lust and familial warmth are still pretty much taboo
in the movies, as is the sight of not one, not two but three
super-smart, well-adjusted and hip black male teen-agers. However
race is lived off screen in America, people are still happiest when
it makes its on screen appearance as fantasy. It might be the
science fiction of ``The Matrix,'' the high-tech espionage of
``Mission Impossible'' or the comic improbabilities of ``Me, Myself
and Irene.'' And when it comes to comedy, race is still the best _
and the worst _ joke ever played on the United States of America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-00 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
