<HEADER>
A7214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-GEORGE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-09 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GEORGE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GEORGE: A FAMILY DOCUMENTARY': PORTRAIT CAPTURES INSIGHT INTO
TRIALS OF AUTISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a documentary that asks a great deal. It asks you to be
patient, for one thing, as you spend an hour and half in the
company of an articulate but oddly distracted boy who clearly has
no capacity for patience himself.
</P>
<P>
   Stick with it. This film, which begins with a series of
seemingly disjointed impressions, coalesces into a moving study of
the boy, his family and his condition. The more you know, the more
you care. The more you care, the more your heart will break.
</P>
<P>
   ``George: A Family Documentary,'' the film by Henry Corra and
Grahame Weinbren that HBO is showing Monday night, is Corra's
loving portrait and guilty apology to his autistic son, George.
Made in 1995, when the boy was 12 and his father gave him a
videocamera for his birthday, it intersperses bits of George's own
monologues and quirky interviews with his father's professional
sequences and quirky interviews.
</P>
<P>
   At first George, handsome and energetic, seems no different from
any boy his age. But when he starts to share his passion for planes
and recites his storehouse of statistics about every type of
airliner, the distinctions begin to come into focus. Although he
must be reminded to look people in the eye when speaking to them,
he has no trouble addressing his own camera head-on with random
information like the day's weather forecast.
</P>
<P>
   His father's camera follows George on a real flying lesson
(``That was great,'' he says) and on a visit to the United Nations,
where he can name the country represented by every flag flying
outside.
</P>
<P>
   The camera also trails him at his special school, where his
classmates share with Corra their observations on being different
themselves. Thrilled at the prospect of being on television, they
perform a song, written by one of the students, that describes
their lives as being ``caught between a rock and a hard place.''
</P>
<P>
   If this weren't all bittersweet enough, Henry Corra gets word
that HBO has decided to withdraw from the project because George
does not seem ``autistic enough.'' (Corra vows to press on.) And
hovering over the film is the figure of George's uncle Tom Corra.
He plays melancholy music on his cello and talks about the boy, who
can deal with endless facts but ``not concepts that have to do with
interrelationships, especially of human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is dedicated to the memory of Tom Corra, who died in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The months covered by the documentary also include the decision
by George's parents to separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not, you're not gonna stay with us anymore,'' the boy,
eyes fixed on a videogame, says to his father in an uninflected
statement. But it is quickly followed by an anguished question,
``Not anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking off-screen, Henry Corra admits that to escape his own
distress over George's autism, he kept diving ever deeper into his
work. At least that work ultimately helped bring the two of them
closer, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Only toward the end does the film bring out the talking heads to
help the viewer begin to make sense of all this, including a
psychologist who speaks of the sensory overload the autistic must
bear. But that burden is not totally negative, says Mark Ramoser,
an autistic adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see and hear things that the rest of you might have to have
pointed out,'' he says, things like the sound of a brook or the
grain pattern in a piece of wood. ``I gather most of you
neuro-typicals barely even notice that.''
</P>
<P>
   Much is left unexplained by ``George.'' You're left to wonder
what has happened to the family members since 1995. And you're left
to wonder what led the neuro-typicals at HBO to show the film now,
and at an inconvenient hour.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is much to be learned from this documentary. Yes,
some of its concepts are difficult to process. But that just may be
the whole point.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GEORGE: A FAMILY DOCUMENTARY'
</P>
<P>
   6 p.m. ET Monday on HBO
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Henry Corra; directed by Henry Corra and Grahame
Weinbren, with George Corra. For HBO, supervising producer, Carole
Rosen; executive producer, Sheila Nevins.
</P>
</TEXT>
