u e BC-LATIN-HUNKS0710-COX     07-09 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-HUNKS0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans receive a double dose of hunka burnin' Latin love
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Unless your ceiling is the underside of a rock, you
probably know that Latin pop has made a serious dent in the
mainstream music charts in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that chart action has been generated by the tropical
triumvirate of testosterone: Ricky Martin, Marc Anthony and Enrique
Iglesias. Let's take a look at the accomplishments and relative
merits of these two superstars.
</P>
<P>
   WHO, WHEN, WHERE
</P>
<P>
   Anthony: Born Marco Antonio Muniz to Puerto Rican parents in New
York on Sept. 16, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Martin: Born Enrique Martin: Morales in San Juan, Puerto Rico,
on Dec. 24, 1971.
</P>
<P>
   THE HITS
</P>
<P>
   Anthony: The salsa-flavored ``I Need to Know'' and the current
Top 20 hit ``You Sang to Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin: ``She's All I Ever Had,'' ``Shake Your Bon-Bon'' and the
ubiquitous ``Livin' la Vida Loca.''
</P>
<P>
   THE ALBUMS
</P>
<P>
   Anthony: His first three albums (``Otra Nota,'' ``Todo a Su
Tiempo'' and ``Contra la Corriente'') were solid salsa affairs. His
latest release is his double-platinum, self-titled English-language
debut, which supplied the hits.
</P>
<P>
   Martin: His Spanish-language debut, like his later
English-language debut, was titled ``Ricky Martin.'' That was
followed by ``Me Amaras'' and ``A Medio Vivir.'' With ``Vuelve,''
and the World Cup anthem ``La Copa de la Vida,'' Martin began
making inroads into the pop mainstream. After a galvanizing
performance of that tune at the 1998 World Cup, the buzz became
deafening in the weeks leading up to the release of his first
English-language album.
</P>
<P>
   THE LATIN GRAMMYS
</P>
<P>
   Anthony: In the first-ever nominations for these awards, he
scored five nods _ including Record of the Year for ``I Need to
Know.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin: He was nominated in two categories, including Record of
the Year for ``Livin' la Vida Loca.''
</P>
<P>
   THE EARLY YEARS
</P>
<P>
   Anthony: Before releasing his first album in 1993, Anthony was
performing with Little Louie Vega. His first chart appearance (on
Billboard's dance chart) was on a recording with Vega called ``Ride
on the Rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin: From age 12 to 16, Martin was part of Latin factory boy
band Menudo.
</P>
<P>
   THESPIAN EXPLOITS
</P>
<P>
   Anthony: He played the lead in Paul Simon's short-run Broadway
musical ``The Capeman.'' He has also appeared in the movies
``Bringing Out the Dead,'' ``Hackers'' and ``Big Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin: A luxuriantly coiffed Martin played Miguel on the
daytime drama ``General Hospital,'' made stage appearances in
Mexico and had a role in ``Les Miserables'' on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   THE HUNKA BURNIN' LOVE FACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Anthony: From the February issue of Cosmopolitan: ``Although
(he) might not be tall and brooding like Enrique Iglesias or
chiseled and swivelicious like Ricky Martin, he has a fierce
following of devoted fans _ most of them female. Chalk it up to a
mixture of guy-next-door accessibility, smoldering sexuality, and a
willingness not to take himself too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin: He possesses the most celebrated hip-swivel since Elvis
Presley shocked the nation on ``The Ed Sullivan Show'' in the
1950s. Martin's days on ``General Hospital'' inspired much
swooning.
</P>
<P>
   ISN'T IT ROMANTIC?
</P>
<P>
   Anthony: On May 9, he married former Miss Universe Dayanara
Torres. The wedding took place in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Martin: Speculation about his sexuality runs rampant, abetted by
his coyness about his personal life in interviews. He has been
linked with Mexican television personality Rebecca de Alba.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM LINE
</P>
<P>
   Anthony: With three albums of hot salsa to his name, Anthony
wins the rootsy authenticity sweepstakes, for what it's worth. His
vocal dexterity and soulful delivery are what really give him the
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Martin: Martin's music has always been pop, through and through
_ not that there's anything wrong with that. The Latin flavor is
there in more than the Spanish words, but he's a pop star in any
language. His voice is not the most versatile instrument, but he
and his producers know what material works best for him. His
greatest asset is his seemingly boundless energy and enthusiasm _
along with that marvelous mug and his widely worshipped bon-bon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
