<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7219 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGO-KOSOVO-ART-NYT     07-09 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-KOSOVO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. AGREES TO BETTER PROTECT SERBS IN KOSOVO, AS STRAINS THREATEN
COHESION 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRACANICA, Kosovo _ The first agreement between the Serbs and
the U.N. administration here may provide some better protection for
the Serbian minority, but threatens to unravel key Albanian
participation and Western hopes for a multi-ethnic Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Maneuvering by the province's majority Albanians and the Serbs
is intensifying ahead of municipal elections scheduled for October.
The international administration here hopes this ballot will be the
first step toward cutting Kosovo loose from its foreign lifelines;
so far, however, almost no Serbs have registered to vote.
</P>
<P>
   And Albanian leaders jostling for power in Kosovo's majority
community also seem to be increasingly willing to fight out their
differences on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   A year into the effort to rebuild Kosovo, many in the U.N.
administration say they are wearying of the recalcitrance of
Albanian leaders. They are also under new pressure to better
protect the Serb minority against persistent attacks, especially
the more openly cooperative Serbs grouped around religious leaders,
Bishop Artemije and Father Sava, who are based at the early
14th-century monastery here.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration in particular has negotiated with
Artemije to convince him to join the executive council established
by Bernard Kouchner, the chief U.N. administrator. The bishop's
decision to do so was viewed as traitorous by the government of
Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade and by a rival Kosovo Serb grouping
led from the northern town of Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   Some formal participation by Serbs is considered vital to the
success of the Western effort to restructure Kosovo as a
democratic, self-governing entity where all ethnic groups can live
peacefully _ even if separated into enclaves behind barbed wire and
guarded by foreign peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   And there is pressure from Washington to begin the return to
Kosovo of at least some Serbs who fled Albanian revenge when NATO's
bombing war against Yugoslavia ended a year ago, enabling hundreds
of thousands of Albanians driven from home by the Serbs to return.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is eager to promote the bishop and his Serbian
National Council over the harder-line Mitrovica Serbs led by Oliver
Ivanovic, who is more closely, if not definitively, allied with
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, after Artemije protested increased attacks on Serbs
last month by walking out of Kouchner's council, the Clinton
administration helped his group of Serbs and the United Nations to
negotiate an agreement on security for the Serbian minority that
coaxed the bishop back in, at least for another three months. It
was the first direct accord between the United Nations and Kosovar
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no other choice but to participate,'' said Father
Sava, the bishop's aide and spokesman. ``We cannot live on rhetoric
and criticism, but we have to give our own constructive
contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum drew fierce protest from other Serbs, nearly
every Kosovo Albanian party and the government of neighboring
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Hashim Thaci, once the leader of the Kosovo Liberation Army and
now head of the Democratic Party of Kosovo, himself withdrew from
U.N. organizations, at least ``temporarily,'' on July 4, just
before attending a party at the American diplomatic mission here.
</P>
<P>
   Thaci says the agreement, which he first read about in
newspapers, ``opens the door'' to the partition of Kosovo into
separate ethnic enclaves. What bothers him most, his aides say, is
not Gracanica, and its Serbs, but partitioned Mitrovica, which is
divided into a Serb-dominated north and Albanian-dominated south,
and where the River Ibar still marks the effective beginning of
Serbia proper. The actual border is a few miles to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian Mitrovica remains a neuralgic point for Albanians.
Thaci's aides say that Kouchner and the NATO officers who lead the
peacekeeping force here may mean well, but are naive and open to
Serbian manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, U.N. and NATO officials admit privately that it is
becoming less likely that the West will act forcefully to end the
partition of Mitrovica, and therefore of Kosovo itself, because of
the risk to alliance troops and the fear that it would drive
thousands more Serbs from the province.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement with Artemije, the United Nations promises
to improve the safety and freedom of movement of Serbs by
developing a special police task force for Serb enclaves; to get
more Serbs, particularly those nominated by the bishop, into
Kosovo's multi-ethnic police force; to promote the return of Serbs,
find more Serb and international judges to adjudicate crimes and
disputes and, crucially, to establish up to 20 ``local community
offices'' in Serb areas.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians criticize the special offices and arrangements for
Kosovo Serbs, saying that they undermine the principle of a unified
and multi-ethnic Kosovo. But Father Sava points to Albanian attacks
on Serbs that make enclaves necessary, and notes that if the U.N.
and NATO peacekeepers do not deliver, the position of Gracanica's
Serbs will be further undermined.
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner stresses that every institution is ultimately under his
control. He admits that he did not consult Thaci or other Albanian
leaders, saying that he has always dealt with security issues as
his responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I have always been on the side of those who
suffer,'' Kouchner said. ``Earlier they were the Albanians, but now
it is the Serbs and members of other communities.''
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Kouchner suggested that Thaci is losing popularity
and needed to stand up to the United Nations, although he conceded
there are deeper issues at stake. He noted that Ibrahim Rugova, the
more moderate and passive Albanian leader of the Democratic League
of Kosovo, has not left the council.
</P>
<P>
   The aide predicted that the summer months, leading up to the
first elections in post-war Kosovo, are likely to be marked by more
violence, especially among the Albanian parties.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Thaci's followers and those of Ramush Haradinaj, a
former KLA commander who heads another rival party, the Alliance
for the Future of Kosovo, have been attacking each other, as well
as Rugova's followers. In one such attack early Friday, Haradinaj
and his brother were themselves wounded in an exchange of gun fire
with Rugova supporters in the village of Stroece, near Pec.
Haradinaj, the third former KLA leader attacked in recent weeks,
was flown on Sunday to an American military hospital in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing violence _ both intra-Albanian and inter-ethnic _
has depressed U.N. workers struggling to build a new Kosovo with
limited resources. ``There is mission fatigue,'' said one senior
official. ``But there is also Albanian fatigue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
