<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7221 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-COX-NAACP-0710     07-09 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-NAACP-0710 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAACP TO HOST PRESIDENTIAL RIVALS
 &HT;    Moving in the (a) National and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ As Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush come before the NAACP's national convention here this week,
Bush remains at a clear disadvantage in seeking to woo African
American voters in November.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the likely Republican nominee, ``has a harder row to hoe''
than Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee, NAACP President
Kweisi Mfume said Sunday on the eve of the governor's speech to the
nation's oldest and largest civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Bond, the chairman of the NAACP, echoed Mfume's
</P>
<P>
   words, contending that Bush ``has an enormous amount of
baggage'' that he carries into the coming campaign, mostly as a
result of the positions and political tactics his party has taken
in past years.
</P>
<P>
   ``African Americans, like all Americans, have long memories,''
Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   Just how hard it will be for Bush to cut into black support for
Gore was apparent as protesters clad in woolen Confederate Army
grey waved the Confederate flag outside the NAACP's convention
during a rally sponsored by the newly formed Southern Party of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Bond called the flag ``a Confederate swastika'' and vowed that
the organization will continue its boycott of South Carolina, which
recently relocated the Confederate flag from atop the state capitol
to less prominent location on the statehouse grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, during the Republican presidential primary in South
Carolina, said the Confederate flag was a matter for South
Carolinians alone to decide.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bush's first campaign appearance in South Carolina
was at Bob Jones University, a fundamentalist school that, at the
time, still maintained a long-standing policy of banning
interracial dating. The policy since been ended.
</P>
<P>
   But the Confederate flag flap, which initially overshadowed his
message of political inclusion, is not the only issue that is going
to make it difficult for Bush to lure African American votes away
from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor also opposes affirmative action as a remedy
to racial bias. And he has rejected a moratorium on the death
penalty, an issue that arose with the recent execution of Texas
inmate Gary Graham. The NAACP called the execution ``a grave
travesty of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore defends affirmative action as a legitimate
tool for combating discrimination. And early on, he advocated the
removal of the Confederate flag from all public accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   But the vice president, like Bush, also opposes a death penalty
moratorium - one issue that ``we're at odds'' with him on, said
Mfume.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Mfume said the Republican Party ``can make inroads''
with African American voters despite the party's recent history of
ignoring blacks and employing political tactics calculated to turn
white voters against the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's appearance before the NAACP convention apparently signals
at least an end to the party turning its back to African American
voters. Bob Dole, the GOP's presidential nominee in 1996, snubbed
the NAACP's national convention, charging that Mfume was ``trying
to set me up.'' Dole later said his decision was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said the Texas governor expects ``a
polite reception'' from the NAACP delegates Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume said Bush ``obviously doesn't think this is a setup.'' He
added, ``We want to hear what compassionate conservatism really is.
We are interested in compassionate commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, Bush has sought to raise his profile
among minorities. He spoke last week to two major Hispanic
organizations, the League of United Latin American Citizens and the
National Council of La Raza.
</P>
<P>
   And two weeks ago, he appeared before a conservative black
organization, the Congress of Racial Equality, giving a speech that
might have been a rehearsal for his address to the NAACP. He spoke
about a ``school liberation movement,'' tax cuts, economic
empowerment and, most tellingly, his view that racism remains a
fact of life in American society. Such an approach is in sharp
contrast to the ``color blind'' rhetoric of affirmative action
foes.
</P>
<P>
   But Bond suggested that African Americans want more than
campaign rhetoric window dressing from Bush. ``We don't want to be
a back drop,'' he said, referring to the frequency of news
photographs showing the Texas governor with African American
children.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the NAACP volunteers have already registered about
2.8 million new voters since last July, according to Mfume, about
70 percent of the 4 million voters they hope to register in time
for the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's courtship of African American voters, Gore holds
a commanding lead among African American voters. A recent NBC/Wall
Street Journal poll showed Gore with 71 percent of the black vote,
compared to 17 percent for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for Gore's standing with African Americans is
President Clinton, one of the most popular political figures ever
in the African American community. Clinton is scheduled to address
the convention Tuesday, the day before Gore's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.naacp.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
