<SLUG> BC-XM-SATELLITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XM SATELLITE RADIO COMPLETES ITS FINANCING 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a sign that long-promised satellite radio broadcasting is
coming closer to fruition, XM Satellite Radio is expected to
announce Monday that it has completed its planned financing,
raising the last $235 million from a group of investors, people
close to the transaction said.
</P>
<P>
   This latest investment includes $50 million from Honda Motor
Co.'s sales and marketing subsidiary in the United States, $20
million from DirecTV, a provider of satellite-delivered television
service, and money from several private investment firms. The
investors received convertible preferred stock in XM, which is
based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction brings XM one step closer to its plan to
introduce satellite-delivered radio by the middle of next year. The
company would compete with Sirius Satellite Radio, which also plans
to provide nationwide satellite radio broadcasts. Each company
would charge approximately $10 a month for as many as 100 different
audio channels.
</P>
<P>
   So far, XM has raised a total of $1.26 billion with the private
placement on Friday of this latest round of stock. Most of the
company's capital will be used to launch the satellites it needs to
start service. The company also plans to officially open its
headquarters Monday in Washington, where much of the radio
programming will be produced.
</P>
<P>
   Much in the same manner that cable and satellite television have
changed the way television programming is delivered, proponents of
satellite radio are hoping that a broader array of listening
options and improved broadcast quality will appeal to consumers.
People whose cars would be equipped with small satellite receivers
are intended to be a prime audience.
</P>
<P>
   XM's backers include General Motors, with which it has an
installation agreement, and the company is discussing a similar
agreement with Honda, people close to the talks said. Sirius, which
is based in New York, has installation deals with DaimlerChrysler,
Ford Motor Co. and BMW.
</P>
<P>
   XM and Sirius have been awarded the only licenses that the
Federal Communications Commission has granted so far for satellite
radio service. Sirius successfully launched its first of three
satellites last week at a site in Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   XM is planning to launch a satellite, the first of two it plans
to send into space, from a mobile launching vessel in the Pacific
Ocean later this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
