<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7230 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HOMERUNS0710-COX     07-09 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMERUNS0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Research team concludes baseballs are no different
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Everybody's got a theory, but none is more hands-on
than Aaron Boutwell's.
</P>
<P>
   Boutwell works for Rawlings, and this week the marketing manager
is spending his days hand-stitching baseballs for rapt audiences at
the John Hancock All-Star FanFest at the Georgia World Congress
Center.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know why so many baseballs are flying out of
parks this year, Boutwell starts his argument with a bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baseballs aren't juiced,'' he says, picking up a 31-ounce
wooden Adirondack with one hand, pointing at it with the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``See this handle? Players today wouldn't play with the bats
that old-timers like Babe Ruth used, which had thick handles. This
handle is skinny. It makes the bat lighter and more whippy. Players
can swing it faster and hit the ball farther.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one reason there are so many home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Boutwell then runs through a litany of other reasons: bigger
hitters, smaller parks, worse pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball,'' he says, with the gravity of words chiseled in
granite, ``is exactly the same ball as they've been using for
decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't know that from the fan chatter and sports-bar
speculation that have been juicing the juiced-ball debate since
they lowered the pitching mound in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   With baseballs leaving stadiums at a record pace _ through June
29, there have been an average of 2.56 home runs per game, compared
to 2.28 a game during the same period of the 1999 season _ Major
League Baseball commissioned a study to settle the issue.
</P>
<P>
   EXHAUSTIVE TESTING
</P>
<P>
   The answer is no, according to researchers at the Baseball
Research Center at UMass-Lowell, who spent months batting balls
with a $350,000 machine known as a BAUM, then sorting through the
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The players may be pumped, and the stadiums may be smaller, but,
by golly, it ain't the baseballs.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, researchers report, this season's supply of baseballs,
on average, travel 1.4 feet less than last year's baseballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the margin of statistical error is one and a half
feet,'' says Lawrence Fallon, a co-author of the report, ``that
means there's no difference, or the difference is negligible.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who are mechanical engineers, studied the
dimensions and make-up of the balls as well.
</P>
<P>
   Measurements were made of the seam height and cover frictions to
determine how that could affect the pitcher's control and ball
movement.
</P>
<P>
   The seams on this year's ball are approximately the same height
as the seams on last year's ball, according to the researchers, and
the cover friction is about the same.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers couldn't measure the effect of a ball's spin on
how far it's hit, however, since the BAUM machine throws a
knuckleball.
</P>
<P>
   In the test of 192 balls from the 1999 and 2000 season, the
machine pitched the ball 70 mph, and the machine's bat hit the
balls with a swing speed of 70 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers: On average, a 1999 ball hit by the BAUM traveled an
estimated 400 feet; the average 2000 ball traveled an estimated
398.6 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The testers didn't actually measure the distance the balls
traveled because the research was done indoors at the research
facility. The distance was computed, based on the speed of the
balls as they came off the bat.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers and baseball officials also sought to debunk
theories that it's something about the ball's cork center or
cowhide cover that's different.
</P>
<P>
   They visited the plants that manufacture the balls' components:
a ball-stitching facility in Costa Rica; the factory that produces
ball yarn in Ludlow, Vt.; the ``pill plant'' _ where the cork core
is coated with red rubber _ in Batesville, Miss., and the plant
where the rawhide covers are made in Tullahoma, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Short answer: The components of the ball and manufacturing
process are the same this year as last.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers even researched the researchers at Rawlings' Ava,
Mo. ball-testing site, where baseballs are fired out of a cannon at
60 miles per hour into a wall of northern white ash, the wood
major-league bats are made of.
</P>
<P>
   They measured whether the Coefficient of Restitution (COR) is in
keeping with major-league rules. The COR number measures how much
the ball bounces back.
</P>
<P>
   The number, 57, which means it bounces back 57 percent as fast
as the speed it hit the wall, is roughly the same this year as
last, and roughly the same as it has always been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's within the acceptable range demanded by the rules,'' said
Fallon.
</P>
<P>
   The study, of course, will hardly settle the juiced-ball debate
any more than the Warren Commission got people to quit theorizing
that it was a gunman on the grassy knoll who shot President
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   And, no thanks to the researchers, either. Already they're
testing more balls, from the '60s, '70s, '80s, and earlier '90s, to
see how they compare to this year's model.
</P>
<P>
   And not just any old ball will do. They have to have been kept
in an ``environmentally controlled packaging,'' says Tim Mustone ,
another one of the researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting calls from all kinds of people trying to give us
old balls,'' says Mustone. ``But any old ball won't do, even if it
was autographed by Ted Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
