<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7231 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-EGYPT-RIGHTS-NYT     07-09 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS GROUPS ALARMED BY ARREST OF EGYPTIAN SCHOLAR
</HEADLINE>
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ The recent arrest of a prominent sociologist on
suspicion of ``defaming'' Egypt has alarmed human rights advocates
around the region who say it reflects a policy among Arab leaders
toward political criticism that can best be described as killing
the messenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has convinced the people that Egypt and the
government are one and the same thing,'' said Gasser Abdel Razik,
secretary general of a legal aid center in Cairo. ``If someone
criticizes the government, then it is an insult against Egypt. If
any crisis erupts, they do not solve it but they punish the one who
reported it.''
</P>
<P>
   The sociologist, Saad Eddin Ibrahim, who has been held in an
Egyptian prison since June 30, has taught at the American
University in Cairo for 25 years. He founded the Ibn Khaldoun
Center for Developmental Studies, a private group in Cairo that
includes two government ministers on its board and conducts
research on democracy, civil society and minority rights.
</P>
<P>
   He recently wrote an article that appeared in a Saudi magazine,
Al Majala, and satirized the efforts by some Arab leaders to groom
their sons for succession. Among others, Ibrahim mentioned
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt. He also has written frequently on
the status of the Christian minority in Egypt, where the subject of
religious tensions is taboo.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim has been held since security agents began interrogating
him on June 30 about a documentary his center produced to instruct
Egyptians about their voting rights and encourage them to take part
in parliamentary election scheduled for November.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Saada, who is one of Ibrahim's lawyers, said investigators
had accused him of defaming Egypt because the film refers to
complaints about fraud filed after past elections.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim has not been charged with a crime but is being held for
15 days for questioning. Under Egyptian law, detention without
charge can be extended up to 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the U.S. Embassy in Cairo who visited Ibrahim this
week said he had reassured them that he was not being mistreated.
The American ambassador, Daniel Kurzer, has expressed concern about
the arrest to Egypt's prime minister, according to an embassy
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that his detention is not inspired by a desire to
silence a voice advocating freedom of expression and democracy,''
said the spokesman, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim, a former adviser to the Egyptian government who holds
dual Egyptian and American citizenship, earned a Ph.D. from the
University of Washington and has written or edited 30 books in
English and Arabic. He has been a frequent guest at international
conferences on Arab political life.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim's arrest has worried human rights groups and advocates
around the Arab Middle East, where nongovernmental organizations
and journalists who criticize their governments are routinely
harassed or imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saad Eddin Ibrahim's arrest reminds us that one of the leading
sources of instability and political-economic distortion in the
Arab world is the unchecked use of state power, combined with the
state's whimsical ability to use the rule of law for its own
political ends,'' wrote Rami G. Khouri, a political analyst, in The
Jordan Times last week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite apparent progress in a handful of countries that declare
themselves to be democracies, like Egypt and Jordan, independent
organizations have found themselves fighting for their lives, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt, like its neighbors, tightly regulates nongovernmental
organizations and the press. Labor unions can be formed and hold
internal elections only with government approval. The government
licenses political parties _ and has approved only one new party in
the past 22 years. A handful of others operate, but most were
allowed only after appealing to the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Egypt enacted a law requiring all nongovernmental
organizations to register, report any foreign financing and submit
the names of their trustees for approval to the government. The law
was seen as an attempt to control groups that might serve as fronts
for Islamic militants, but it was widely criticized by human rights
and legal aid groups. It was declared unconstitutional, on
technical grounds, by the Constitutional Court last month.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt has more than a dozen groups that investigate human rights
abuses and many newspapers that publish reports on torture, illegal
detention, prison conditions and other topics. They have fax
machines, speak openly to foreign journalists and post reports on
their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But when the subject turns to a few particularly sensitive
topics _ among them election fraud, official corruption and
religious tension _ the government has cracked down, often using a
provision in the penal code that makes it a crime to defame Egypt's
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Five journalists at the daily newspaper Al Ahrar, for example,
were recently sentenced to jail terms because they published a
Government Accounting Office report on mismanagement at the
government airline, Egypt Air. Officials of the Egyptian
Organization for Human Rights were jailed last year, accused of
defaming the country and illegally accepting foreign funds, after
publishing a report on the police handling of a clash between
Christians and Muslims in Upper Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government wants to finish off all civil society
organizations in Egypt,'' said Hafez Abu Saada, the secretary
general of the group, who was himself jailed for several weeks last
year after his group published the report on police brutality.
``Either we agree with them all the time or we are the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jordan, it is still a crime to insult the dignity of the king
and, as in Egypt or other Arab countries, courts can shut down a
publication or jail people who are found to have harmed the
``public interest'' or criticized members of the government.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials in Egypt said Ibrahim was the subject of a
lengthy police investigation before he was arrested. Hisham Saraya,
the chief prosecutor of the state security agency, said Ibrahim was
suspected of illegally taking money from a foreign entity, using
that money fraudulently and forging election ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim's lawyers said the election ballots were printed for use
in the documentary. They said he received money from the European
Commission, the executive body of the European Union, to make the
film.
</P>
<P>
   Saraya, the government prosecutor, said protests from diplomats
and other human rights advocates would have no effect on the police
inquiry against Ibrahim. ``No other authority _ nothing but truth
and justice _ can influence our prosecution,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
