<DOCNO> NYT20000709.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      07-09 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAIL TERM FOR FORMER PREMIER BRINGS CALLS FOR REFORM IN TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ The increasing likelihood that a 73-year-old
former prime minister will go to prison for remarks in a political
speech six years ago is sending a chill through Turkey's political
elite and bringing widespread calls to relax laws that restrict
freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, an appeals court upheld the one-year sentence and
lifetime political ban imposed on former Prime Minister Necmettin
Erbakan on the charge of ``provoking hatred'' in a 1994 speech.
Since the ruling, political leaders have scrambled to diminish the
decision's impact on Turkey's efforts to portray itself as a modern
democracy and to join the European Union. Even Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit said he was saddened at the prospect of Erbakan going
to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the concerns translate into a genuine overhaul of laws
regarded outside Turkey as violations of free expression is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders across the political spectrum indicated that it may be
time to modify elements of the code that make it a crime to promote
religious or ethnic differences and to criticize the government or
military.
</P>
<P>
   Elements in the influential military and the politicians most
strongly wedded to Turkey's secularist state still oppose change,
however, for fear Turkey will turn more toward Islam.
</P>
<P>
   A leader of the Islamic-oriented Virtue Party told Ecevit on
Thursday that the organization would consider supporting changes to
the criminal code in exchange for leniency for Erbakan, according
to the Turkish press. Backing for revisions also came from parties
that form Ecevit's coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make radical improvements to the civil and criminal
codes,'' Bulent Akarcali, a member of Parliament who is deputy
chairman of the Motherland Party, one of the coalition members,
said in an interview. ``It is a must.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunduz Aktan, a former senior Turkish diplomat, said laws
categorized in the criminal code as ``crimes against the state''
need to be revised to recognize the difference between legitimate
political speech or criticism of the government and threats. ``We
need to separate violence and threats to public order from
legitimate free speech,'' Aktan, a former ambassador to Greece and
Japan, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Erbakan was prime minister for a year in 1996 and 1997. He
resigned under pressure from the military and political opponents
who charged he was plotting against the secular order of Turkey.
His pro-Islamic party was outlawed, but later re-emerged as the
Virtue Party, with most of the same leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Erbakan was convicted of a crime against the state
for a speech he made in a Kurdish-dominated area before he became
prime minister. In the speech, he contended that Turkey had
abandoned its Islamic roots and that secular politicians had
divided the Kurds from other Turks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country there are two parties: the righteous and the
fallacious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Erbakan's jail sentence and ban were upheld by the appeals
court, and he is expected to serve about five months in prison
unless the chief prosecutor's office recommends reducing the
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The uproar over the court ruling stems in part from fears that
it threatens Turkey's prospects for European Union membership.
Guenther Verheugen, the European Union's commissioner for
enlargement, is scheduled to visit Ankara this week and Western
diplomats have already expressed concern over imprisoning an aging
former leader.
</P>
<P>
   Seyfi Tashan, director of the Foreign Policy Institute in
Ankara, noted that the threats that validated the restrictions on
speech for many Turks appear to have eased. Kurdish separatism is
less threatening and concern over Islamic fundamentalism may also
be diminishing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether the perception of threats has
decreased to the point where free expression can be condoned,''
Tashan said.
</P>
<P>
   But others argue that the Islamic threat is still too potent to
warrant easing restrictions. ``There is no such thing as mild
Islam,'' said Suna Kili, an author and political science professor
at Bosporus University. ``The republic has the right to protect
itself. Even in France and Germany there are laws protecting the
secular state.''
</P>
<P>
   The strictness of the laws was demonstrated on Friday when a
prosecutor increased charges against Nadire Mater, a Turkish
journalist who wrote a book last year recounting stories of
soldiers who fought the Kurds in southeast Turkey. Rejecting an
independent report that Mater did not violate criminal statutes,
the prosecutor said the author would face two to 12 years in prison
if convicted of insulting the military.
</P>
<P>
   Mater, who was honored last week by Human Rights Watch, said
after the hearing: ``I'm not very optimistic about changes in
Turkey today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-00 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000709.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PAY-YOUR-WAY-PRISONS-     07-09 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAY-YOUR-WAY-PRISONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KENTUCKY JAILS, INMATES PAY TO STAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Fla., Iowa, W.Va., Mich.)  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OWENSBORO, Ky. _ The county jailers of Kentucky are eagerly
preparing to levy room, board and medical charges on inmates under
a pay-your-way practice that dates to medieval England but is
finding fresh life in America, the global leader in incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   The chief jailer in Daviess County, Harold N. Taylor, is
awaiting his new hotelier's powers with a touch of nostalgia for
his salad days as a deputy sheriff in the '60s. Back then, he
recalls, respectful town drunkards barely taxed the public budget
as they gratefully slugged down black coffee and slept off their
misdeeds in a far less complex world of the jail house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, you have the situation where one inmate went to
court to sue me to get all his teeth replaced,'' said Taylor,
echoing the complaints of county jailers across the country that
rising medical and housing costs in small-town jails necessitate
turning to the inmates to help foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new law that takes effect this month, the state's 85
jails will have the power to charge up to $50 a day for room and
board, plus a $20 paperwork fee and other special charges for
unruly inmates who sling their food about or damage bunks or
plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more jails across the country are turning to these
fees,'' said Stephen Ingley, executive director of the American
Jail Association, which has 5,000 members. Each year the nation's
jails have 20 million admissions and exits, with more than 600,000
inmates in residence each day, including many felony defendants
awaiting trial. Handling this torrent is no longer a sleepy-time
industry, Ingley said, and inmates are covered by federal and state
standards for housing, diet and medical care that have grown
stronger and more expensive in modern times.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who lobbied for the new law as chief of the Kentucky
Jailers Association, said: ``There's the old saying, `Crime doesn't
pay.' Well now there's the thought that maybe the criminals should
start paying.''
</P>
<P>
   Local jailers say that jails in Florida, Iowa, Michigan, West
Virginia and elsewhere saw improvements in budgets and inmate
behavior when they began levying fees in recent years. To
complaints from civil libertarians that the levy amounts to a
double-dipping of punishment, jailers reply that judges have long
had the power to levy court costs on defendants and there was no
attendant controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a law without compassion,'' said state Sen. David
E. Boswell, D-Owensboro, who was the chief sponsor of the measure.
``It has to be shown an inmate can afford to pay, and a jailer has
up to a year to collect once an inmate becomes a productive citizen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The law sailed through the Legislature with barely a dissent. It
covers only county inmates typically sentenced to a year or less in
jail, not state and federal felons who serve longer terms in
prisons. Proponents contend that it can provide an extra measure of
deterrence when the public sees, for example, a drunken driver
doing his jail time but also tapping his own resources for good
measure. Proponents also cite the potential for compensation in
coping with modern criminal life in which well-capitalized drug
dealers routinely cycle through local jails.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of dealers come through here after arrest with $2,000 or
$5,000 in their pockets,'' Taylor said, putting such inmates at the
top of his most lucrative lodger list.
</P>
<P>
   Jailers will have the power to take money from inmates'
commissary accounts and even pursue them through collection
agencies if jailers decide it is worth the trouble. They concede
that the levy has practical limits for the many jail house
deadbeats serving time, but Taylor hopes to net $250,000 a year for
his $3 million budget, and proponents promise millions more for the
state's other 119 counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know you can't get blood out of a turnip,'' said Dan
Fackler, the jailer for Bullitt County, sympathizing with some down
on his luck inmate suddenly shocked with a lodging bill at
checkout. ``But we hear they're getting maybe 30 cents on each
dollar due with this in other parts of the country, and taxpayers
think it's a step in the right direction: You should pay for what
you do in this life, whether it's good or bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Jail house costs vary, but the federal government estimates the
average room and board costs $34 per day, with medical costs
additional. Jailers say that, more than any other factor, the
rising expense of mandated medical care is spurring the current
move to levy fees on inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're becoming more like a hospital and a care center,''
Fackler said. ``That's OK _ it could be my brother in there with a
need _ but nowadays his medicine can cost $300.'' And under the
current state mandate of three jail beds for every 1,000 citizens,
Fackler said he must find extra resources to help build an $8
million, 300-bed jail for his fast-growing county south of
Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what got people tore up around here,'' Fackler added.
``So if, say, McAdoo owes me $495 when he's checking out and he
only has $180, well I'll just take the $180 and say thank you,
McAdoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, Kentucky jailers will have the option to charge
their inmates or not, to negotiate a compromise payment, and even
to carry negative balances on the books for the next time a repeat
offender might return flush with cash.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor intends to charge $20 a day for room and board plus
medical costs and a $20 admission fee. ``In the old days, you'd
find someone curled up on the sidewalk with his bottle of
Thunderbird; you'd take him in,'' he recalled. A regular miscreant
might not even be written up back then, and there was a mutual
kindness of jailer and inmate that, Taylor insisted, was as
commonplace as the jail's old baloney sanndwich. ``Now we've got a
minimum of two hot meals a day and each inmate has his required
square footage,'' said the jailer, busily preparing a detailed
computer program to retally a modern inmates' debt to society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
