u a BC-FISHING-QUOTAS-NYT &LR;      07-09 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-QUOTAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING SAFETY, MANY ARE SEEKING END TO SHORT FISHING SEASONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL HULSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Wayne Werner, a commercial fishing skipper, and
his boat's crew, the frenzied competition for prime catch in the
Gulf of Mexico is a no-win proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Werner, captain of the Wayne's Pain in Galliano, La., says short
seasons for prized fish like red snapper and king mackerel are
proving hazardous, occasionally forcing boat crews to choose
between braving threatening weather and skipping a payday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have 10 days to fish in September and a hurricane comes
along, you either don't fish or you go out and it is dangerous,''
said Werner, 42. He said he knew of three members of Gulf fishing
crews lost in rough seas in recent years, and a couple of boats
sunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are running for 20 hours,'' Werner said. ``It is
inevitable you are going to have accidents. It is just such a race
for fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to restore a bit of calm to fishing in the Gulf and
elsewhere, some fishermen have struck a rare alliance with
conservation groups. They are seeking to end the scramble
associated with the so-called derby approach, in which captains are
given a strict limit of fish to compete for and a brief time to
catch them.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, red snapper fishing was allowed in the first 10
days of February, March and April but was cut off early in May when
the spring quota of 3 million pounds was reached. The fall season
will open Sept. 1 with a smaller goal of about 1.6 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Those unhappy with this system would instead allot fishermen
individual quotas, enabling captains to spread their trips out over
the year, reducing risk and making fresh fish more regularly
available at the seafood counter.
</P>
<P>
   Under a typical quota program, the total catch of a species
would be divided among eligible captains, each receiving shares
based on his fishing history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The derby fishery is unnecessarily subjecting us to dangerous
conditions all the time,'' said Felix Cox, a snapper captain from
Aransas Pass, Texas. ``We don't have the flexibility to make the
judgment calls it takes to run a business like this.''
</P>
<P>
   A four-year federal moratorium on new individual fishing quota
programs is to expire Sept. 30. But some members of Congress,
moving to protect fishing interests in their regions that oppose
the idea, are poised to extend the moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia J. Snowe, the Maine Republican who is chairwoman of
the Commerce Subcommittee on Oceans and Fisheries, wants to keep
the ban in place for three more years as part of a fishery
management measure facing a committee vote. Snowe has enlisted
backing from the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, R-Miss., those
following the legislation say.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Snowe said that even though a series of hearings
she had conducted found support for individual quotas in the Gulf
of Mexico and the Pacific Northwest, the senator was worried that
they could be acquired by large commercial interests that would
squeeze out smaller independent fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Lackey, an aide to Snowe, said that in New England the
individual quotas were ``pretty broadly opposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all environmental groups are ready to see the moratorium
expire either. Lee Crockett, executive director of the Marine Fish
Conservation Network, an umbrella organization of environmental and
commercial fishing groups, said the moratorium should not be lifted
without the enactment of strict regulations. Those would include a
fair allocation system, a five-year term on any quotas and a
mechanism to let conservation groups buy and hold quota shares _
never actually catching the fish _ to protect and replenish fish
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Defense, a group that advocates market-based
techniques to protect the environment, is strongly behind the
fishermen in their push for individual quotas, calling them a
common-sense solution to fishing problems like weather risks and
the discarding of millions of pounds of fish unintentionally caught
out of season.
</P>
<P>
   The group has been lining up support for eliminating the
moratorium from senators like Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, and
John B. Breaux, D-La. Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, who was a chief
proponent of the ban when it was imposed in 1996, has signaled a
softening in his stance. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the probable
Republican presidential nominee, also favors individual quotas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tool vests fishermen with an incentive to conserve the
fishery, eliminates such bureaucratic restrictions as minimum size
limits and season closings and reduces dangerous operating
conditions,'' Bush wrote in an April 28 letter to Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   A National Research Council report issued last year also
recommended that regional fishery councils be given the option of
trying individual quotas, a concept in limited use domestically but
employed on a broad scale internationally.
</P>
<P>
   A study of Alaskan halibut, one of the few fish covered by
individual quotas, done for Environmental Defense found measurable
safety improvements since the mid-1990s, when fishermen were
allowed a few chaotic 24-hour periods each year in which to make
their catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one 24-hour opening, 2,000 or more boats might enter the
fishing grounds, regardless of weather conditions, each setting
excessive amounts of gear in a make-or-break race to land a full
year's catch,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Search-and-rescue missions by the Coast Guard were reduced to
seven in 1996 from 33 in 1994 under the halibut quota system. No
halibut-fishing fatalities occurred from 1995 to 1996, compared
with 11 from 1991 to 1994, Environmental Defense said.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen say some of the opposition to individual quotas comes
from fish dealers and processors, who enjoy an advantage under the
current system because the supply of fish is so large during short
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the dealer has control,'' said Cox, the Texas fishermen,
who said Gulf fishermen were getting prices for snapper and
mackerel below those of a decade ago. ``With quotas, the fisherman
would regain the power he has lost through regulation over the
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
