<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRRORBALL-TV-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ABSOLUTELY FABULOUS' TEAM HAS NEW SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The team that produced ``Absolutely Fabulous,'' one of the most
successful comedy series ever imported to the United States from
England, has created another series that will have its premiere on
the BBC early next year before it eventually makes its way to two
cable channels in the United States, BBC America and Comedy
Central.
</P>
<P>
   The show, ``Mirrorball,'' will star Jennifer Saunders and Joanna
Lumley, the two women who also starred in ``Ab-Fab,'' as the
previous hit series came to be called. Saunders, who wrote the
original, will also write this series, which will focus on
theatrical characters involved in London's West End musicals.
</P>
<P>
   The two actresses will play new characters, one a former dancer,
the other a former disco diva, both past their prime but still
game. Paul Lee, the chief operating officer of BBC America,
described the show as ``irreverent, indecent and completely
inebriated,'' three adjectives that were often attached to the
previous series.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rest of the supporting cast from ``Absolutely
Fabulous'' will also reappear as new characters, including Julia
Sawalha, June Whitfield and Jane Horrocks. Horrocks, who also
starred in the stage and movie versions of ``Little Voice,'' will
play an Icelandic waitress-singer in the new series.
</P>
<P>
   The deal to bring ``Mirrorball'' to the United States involves
both BBC America and Comedy Central because BBC America, which is
seeking to expand its distribution on American cable systems, will
carry the pilot while Comedy Central, which built ``Absolutely
Fabulous'' into a significant cable hit, will then gain rights to
the rest of the series. The number of episodes has not been
determined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
