<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRS.CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON SAYS LIFTING GASOLINE TAX WOULD BE A `SERIOUS ERROR' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTICA, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton continued her emphasis on
economic issues Sunday, renewing her call for the Federal Trade
Commission to broaden its investigation of sharply increased
gasoline prices and urging Congress to pass legislation to create
an oil reserve for states in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth day of her Senate campaign tour through western
New York, Clinton rejected as ``a serious error'' any move to
eliminate the gasoline tax, a proposal advocated her Republican
rival, Rep. Rick A. Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reject my opponent's proposal of eliminating the gas tax,''
Clinton said, speaking a a press conference earlier in Rochester.
``One of the few sources of revenue that we actually get more of
than we send to Washington is gas tax money for our transportation
needs. It would be hard to imagine how upstate can finish all the
work we need to do without the federal help that comes from
transportation dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   On the investigation of gasoline prices, Clinton said it is
imperative for the commission to ``go beyond where it has already
begun to try to figure out why, while fuel costs have gone up over
50 cents in New York, profits for major oil companies have gone up
more than 500 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In a tour of a dozen communities, Clinton has sought to discuss
policies that would affect the troubled economy of western New
York.
</P>
<P>
   While her campaign has dubbed the trip as the ``Upstate Economic
Tour,'' it has been more of a cookout and picnic tour. The first
lady has appeared at picnics and rallies sponsored by the
Democratic Party in upstate counties. Sunday afternoon, she
addressed a gathering in Van Buren, N.Y., hosted by party officials
of Cayuga, Oswego and Onondaga counties. She addressed another
gathering of Democrats from five counties Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been asked most frequently about her ideas and
proposals to revive the economy in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   She began Sunday at Mount Olivet Baptist Church in Rochester. It
had not been announced in advance to members of the church that
Clinton would be there, and her presence seemed to take nearly
everyone by surprise. Seated beside William Johnson, the mayor of
Rochester, Clinton swayed and clapped to the music by the choir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand here today before you today to thank those of you who
prayed for me and my husband,'' Clinton told the congregation. ``I
believe that we were both sustained and uplifted because of prayer.
And so I thank you and ask you not to quit yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
