<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-COMIC-SIDE0710-COX     07-09 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMIC-SIDE0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `X-Men' just latest to be trying screen
 &HT;    By Don Fernandez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Comic books may not be highly profitable in
themselves, but as properties for other media, they're priceless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The revenue from film and television can be 500 to 1,000 times
what comics bring,'' said Matt Hawkins, editor in chief of Top Cow
Comics in San Diego. ``They're invaluable.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Top Cow`s characters, Witchblade _ a female detective who
possesses a mystical gauntlet _ will debut as a two-hour television
pilot on Atlanta-based TNT in August.
</P>
<P>
   DC Comics' Batman and Superman have been lucrative television
and movie franchises. ``Dick Tracy'' and ``Teenage Mutant Ninja
Turtles'' conquered the box office in the early 1990s. Long before
Jim Carrey donned green face paint, ``The Mask'' was a Dark Horse
Comics creation. ``Men in Black,'' ``Blade,'' ``The Crow'' and
``Spawn'' were all born in comics before film. Even TV's ``Sabrina
the Teenage Witch'' has comic-book roots.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a highly anticipated movie version of ``The X-Men,''
one of the most popular comic book series of all time, will hit
theaters. Film deals are also in the works for ``Spider-Man,''
``The Hulk'' and ``The Fantastic Four,'' and new Superman and
Batman movies are possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins expects 50 percent of Top Cow's revenue to come from
movies and television within a few years, up from the current 20
percent. Another of the company's books, ``The Darkness,'' is in
development at Columbia Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood is finding comics more interesting,'' Hawkins said.
``You have the characters, costume designs and the storyboards
already done.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Jenkins writes the monthly ``Witchblade'' book, as well as
``Peter Parker: Spider-Man'' and ``The Hulk'' for Marvel. With
those characters soon getting their own live-action movies, he
thinks the spotlight may lead people back to comic books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't hurt,'' Jenkins said. ``The way you can tell a story
in comics is like no other medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-00 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000709.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7256 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-COMICS0710-COX     07-09 1613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMICS0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Threatened by the Internet, comic books now are turning to it as
possible salvation
 &HT;    By Don Fernandez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After crushing every cosmic threat that came their
way, comic book heroes such as the Fantastic Four and Spider-Man
are now fighting for their own future _ and it may be downloadable.
</P>
<P>
   Costumed crime fighters, who have thrived for years in comic
books, need a hero themselves. Comic book sales have steadily
declined as computer games and the Internet draw potential readers
away.
</P>
<P>
   Some comic publishers hope that same technology can rescue them.
Artists are turning from pencils to pixels as their companies
explore online comics, Internet animation and other computer-based
graphic technologies to reach new readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think in time digital comics will probably eclipse their
printed forebears,'' said Scott McCloud, author of ``Understanding
Comics'' and one of the industry's top analysts. ``The function of
print is going to shift. You're going to find electronic
distribution is the best way to communicate. This year, you're
going to see amazing growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Comic books emerged as a major form of escapism during World War
II. Colorful tales of superhuman patriotism, romance, humor and
adventure captured millions of readers monthly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not uncommon for a comic to hit a million'' in sales,
said John Miller, managing editor of Comics Buyer's Guide, the
industry newspaper. ``Comics were the nation's baby sitter. It was
cheap to pay 10 cents and keep Junior busy. It was the peak of the
comic book as an icon of American culture.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the war came television, and comic book circulation
began dropping. The books had all but disappeared from newsstands
by the 1970s. Specialty comic shops arose, often with an atmosphere
unfriendly to potential new readers. And the average book, once
just a dime, now sells for $2.50 to $2.99 _ or more.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a comic title is considered impressive if it sells
250,000 copies a month. In 1999, the industry's total take was $275
million.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers hope the Internet will make their tales more
affordable and accessible. The early efforts range from still
images to drawings with limited movement. Some offerings more
resemble cartoons than comics, with lots of motion, sound effects,
voices and music.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see some major changes over the next 10 years.
We all have to look at technology improvements,'' said Cliff
Biggers, publisher of Marietta, Ga.-based Comic Shop News, the
country's largest comics trade publication. ``This is a big debate
going on in the industry, and it's too early to see how it's going
to shake out.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvel Comics, one of the two industry leaders, is going beyond
comics to capitalize on its many characters. Movie deals (such as
``The X-Men,'' opening Friday) and merchandising draw cash that
dwarfs the profits of the most successful 22-page comic book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get back to basics and tell our comic stories
online,'' said Bill Jemas, president of publishing and new media at
Marvel Enterprises in New York. ``It's a wonderful opportunity to
reach a whole new generation with comic books.''
</P>
<P>
   Click to the Omnitheatre section of www.marvel.com and you'll
find CyberComics: original stories of Marvel heroes using limited
animation and sound effects that complement the comic book titles.
Marvel.com soon will introduce ``Spider-Cam,'' a series of online
comics that use photographs instead of artwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in our heart a company that has to do a lot of things
at the same time to be successful,'' Jemas said. ``Comic writing
and storytelling is a great way to be inventive and take great
risks. But to reach a lot of consumers, big media is a must.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Stan Lee _ the writer-editor who launched Spider-Man, the
Hulk and other popular Marvel superheroes in the 1960s _ has jumped
to the web. His StanLee.net site offers original comic characters.
``The 7th Portal,'' about computer beta-testers who become
superheroes, and another series, ``Accuser,'' make major use of
animation and music, with voices instead of printed dialog
balloons.
</P>
<P>
   Just 1 1/2 years after debuting, the material on stanlee.net has
already spawned merchandise, movie deals and plans for theme park
rides.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Lee) published his books at Marvel, it worked because it
was the most cost-effective medium to reach the biggest audience
with a superhero story,'' said stanlee.net co-founder Peter Paul.
``Now the biggest medium is the Internet. It makes no sense to go
back to an anachronistic technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 77, is invigorated by the response to his Internet venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so instantaneous,'' Lee said. ``In comic books, it takes
so long to print it. It takes time to get reaction and know how
much it sold. On the Internet, one second later you can get
comments.The Internet is going to be the most powerful force for
information and entertainment that the world has ever known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is the evolution of comics books,'' he
said. ``I think it's just another way to tell bigger-than-life,
high-concept stories. Everybody's going to want to get into it.
Eventually, you have to get into it.''
</P>
<P>
   But DC Comics _ the industry's top-selling publisher _ isn't
putting Batman, Superman and Wonder Woman online yet. ``To my
knowledge we have nothing in development right now,'' said Patty
Jeras, spokeswoman for DC Comics in New York. ``Marvel is being
much more aggressive on this front than we are.'' DC is owned by
Time Warner, and other branches of that conglomerate are exploring
online comics, often with DC's characters.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' entertaindom.com offers ``The Multipath Adventures
of Superman,'' a series of 30 original cartoon shorts featuring
Superman, some written by comic book authors.
</P>
<P>
   Other comics material is available at www.warnerbros.com,
including a series based on ``The Matrix.'' Female characters from
the Batman titles will get their own online series, ``Gotham
Girls,'' later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Small companies and independent creators are also exploring
Internet options.
</P>
<P>
   Dark Horse Comics, which publishes tales based on such TV shows
as ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and ``Xena: Warrior Princess,'' has
versions of these on www.darkhorse.com. One series, ``The Haunted
Man,'' is created exclusively for online, using limited animation.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Eliopoulos was hunting for a way to expose his offbeat
series ``Desperate Times'' and keep production costs down. Soon
he'll be a comic pioneer of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   In a few months, ``Desperate Times'' will be the first comic to
be offered through the Internet as an eBook. Using free technology
from software company JamBooks, readers will be able to download
and read his series on a computer, Palm Pilot or similar device.
</P>
<P>
   The cost: only $1 an issue, compared with $3 on a comic store
shelf. A $15 trade paperback featuring previously printed material
will cost $4 as a download.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be a good test market,'' Eliopoulos said. ``I've
got a fan base; people have read the book. But ... a lot of people
were afraid to spend $3 on a book they didn't know if they would
like, which killed a lot of potential buyers. Hopefully
(downloadable comics) won't scare people off so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Artist Phil Jimenez, who writes and draws ``Wonder Woman,'' and
has drawn both Marvel's X-Men and DC's Justice League of America,
is negotiating another superhero project that would debut online.
Comics, he said, will likely evolve into another art form
altogether as the concepts and characters converge with technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think simply it's a natural evolution,'' Jimenez said. ``A
large amount of material will be available online, and some of it
exclusively. I would be creating characters and environments that
would be turned into three-dimensional images by computer people.''
</P>
<P>
   Writer/artist Brian Michael Bendis has been hired by Marvel to
write two new comic book versions of ``Spider-Man'' and ``The
Fantastic Four.'' But for his independently owned crime series,
``Jinx,'' he's creating an animated version to premiere on the
Internet next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do see room for both,'' he said. ``But I still see the value
of printing the work.''
</P>
<P>
   McCloud`s just-published ``Reinventing Comics'' expounds on the
need for creators to embrace technology so the art form can evolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great hope for the Web as a means for artists and
readers to connect and as a way for the medium of comics to grow
into some exciting new shapes,'' McCloud said. ``Technology has an
enormous role to play in comics growth in the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   But can a computer image compete with a book that can be held
and thumbed through? Will collectors, who have hundreds of comics
sealed in plastic bags and stored in boxes, be drawn to building an
electronic library?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a strong fetish factor,'' Comic Buyer's Guide's John
Miller said. ``Whereas the recording industry has had to worry
about people copying exact duplicates of its songs, comics haven't.
People really still want to have the physical item.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds writer-artist Bendis: ``You can't replace the feeling of
reading a comic. You can read nearly every magazine for free online
but people still buy them. People like touching paper.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB:
</P>
<P>
   Marvel Comics: www.marvel.com/omni/
</P>
<P>
   Stan Lee: www.stanlee.net
</P>
<P>
   Dark Horse Comics: www.darkhorse.com
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros: www.entertaindom.com
</P>
<P>
   and www.warnerbros.com
</P>
<P>
   Desperate Times: www.desperatetimes.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
