<HEADER>
A7269 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SCARY-BOX-OFFICE-NYT &LR;      07-09 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCARY-BOX-OFFICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEKEND OF FAUX FRIGHT HELPS BOX OFFICE REBOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
  HOLLYWOOD _ The summer box-office slump is officially over.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Scary Movie,'' a raunchy spoof of teen-age horror flicks that
cost $19 million to make, earned an estimated $42.5 million at the
nation's box offices over the weekend, roughly $1 million more than
``The Perfect Storm'' earned in its opening last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second-biggest opening of the year (behind $57.8
million for ``Mission: Impossible 2'' over Memorial Day), the
biggest opening ever for an R-rated movie and the biggest opening
ever for Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood has made so many horror movies in recent years,
including our own `Scream' series, that the genre was ripe for a
spoof,'' said Bob Weinstein, who runs Miramax with his brother,
Harvey. ``And then we decided to put the movie out in the
summertime, against all these big studio behemoths. They are one
type of movie, and we're another. Our special effects are laughs,
and they're very inexpensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scary Movie,'' directed by Keenen Ivory Wayans, drew decidedly
mixed reviews for its gleefully vulgar jabs at films like ``The
Blair Witch Project'' and ``I Know What You Did Last Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Miramax was also eager to point out that its exit polling showed
that about one-third of the movie's audience was over 25, a much
older demographic than teen-age slasher movies usually enjoy. ``It
just tells you the audience wants comedy,'' said Dennis Rice,
president of marketing for Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dergarabedian, chairman of Exhibitor Relations, a Los
Angeles company that monitors box-office performance, said ``Scary
Movie'' succeeded because it was the first recent wide release to
be aimed primarily at a young audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the critics were saying, `The movie looks really cheesy,
it looks like it was shot on video,' but so what?'' Dergarabedian
said. ``The most voracious filmgoing audience, young people, is
ready and eager to go to the theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, when box-office figures were slumping, the top weekend
openings were generally $20 million to $25 million, and the dropoff
as movies went into their second and third weekends was often quite
severe. Now the story is different.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did ``The Perfect Storm'' and ``Scary Movie'' earn more
than $40 million in their openings, but several other movies were
also holding up well. This weekend's estimated box-office total for
the top 12 films was $136.6 million, an increase of 26 percent from
the same weekend last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Perfect Storm'' earned $27.7 million in its second
weekend, a drop of about 35 percent, indicating that it should
continue to draw sizable audiences in coming weeks. Dan Fellman,
president of distribution at Warner Brothers, said the film became
only the third movie in the studio's history to earn $100 million
in 10 days; the other two were Batman movies. ``What's nice about
it is it shows that the box office has come back,'' Fellman said.
</P>
<P>
   The news was also quite good for two other films, ``The
Patriot'' and ``Chicken Run.''
</P>
<P>
   In its second weekend, ``The Patriot,'' the Revolutionary War
epic starring Mel Gibson, earned an estimated $15.5 million, a drop
of only 31 percent from its opening, indicating that it, too, will
probably play well in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has the earmarks of a film that adults want to see,
but they're not necessarily going to run out over the opening
weekend,'' Dergarabedian said. ``I think `The Patriot' will have
long legs.''
</P>
<P>
   The stop-motion animation of ``Chicken Run'' has apparently
captured the family audience, earning an estimated $9.5 million in
its third weekend, a drop of only 28 percent from last weekend, for
a total of $63.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Disney's `The Kid,''' a family-oriented time-travel
fantasy in which Bruce Willis' character meets himself as a boy,
opened in fourth place this weekend with a relatively disappointing
$12.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The new Jim Carrey comedy, ``Me, Myself and Irene,'' also
continued to stumble, dropping 40 percent in its third weekend, to
$8 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
