</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON STRESSES THE ECONOMY IN HER UPSTATE CAMPAIGN SWING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTICA, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton continued her emphasis on
economic issues Sunday, renewing her call for the Federal Trade
Commission to broaden its investigation of sharply increased
gasoline prices and urging Congress to pass legislation to create
an oil reserve for states in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth day of her Senate campaign tour through upstate
New York, Clinton rejected as ``a serious error'' any move to
eliminate the gasoline tax, a proposal advocated by her Republican
rival, Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reject my opponent's proposal of eliminating the gas tax,''
Clinton said at a news conference in Rochester. ``One of the few
sources of revenue that we actually get more of than we send to
Washington is gas tax money for our transportation needs. It would
be hard to imagine how upstate can finish all the work we need to
do without the federal help that comes from transportation
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   On the investigation into gasoline prices, Clinton said that it
was imperative for the commission to ``go beyond where it has
already begun to try to figure out why, while fuel costs have gone
up over 50 cents in New York, profits for major oil companies have
gone up more than 500 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tour, which is covering a dozen communities across the
state's western, Southern Tier and Finger Lake regions, Clinton has
sought to discuss policies that would affect the troubled economy
of upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   While her campaign has called this trip the ``Upstate Economic
Tour,'' it has in fact been more of a cookout and picnic tour.
Clinton has appeared at several picnics and rallies sponsored by
the Democratic Party in a number if upstate counties. Sunday
afternoon, in Van Buren, N.Y., she spoke at a cookout organized by
party officials of Cayuga, Oswego and Onondaga counties. At a
similar event in Utica Sunday evening, she spoke to a gathering of
more than 500 Democrats and union members from four counties. After
the audience's enthusiastic greeting, Clinton spoke about the need
to lower utility costs, to stimulate job growth and to rehabilitate
the roads and highways in this region.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking with voters at the picnics and other events, as in
previous visits to this region of the state, Clinton has been asked
most frequently about her ideas and proposals to revive the economy
in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began the day at the Mount Olivet Baptist Church in
Rochester. It had not been announced in advance to members of the
church that Clinton would be worshipping there, and her presence
seem to take nearly everyone by surprise. Seated beside William A.
Johnson Jr., the mayor of Rochester, Clinton swayed and clapped to
the music by the choir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand here today before you today to thank those of you who
prayed for me and my husband,'' Clinton said, standing in the
sanctuary of the church and addressing an enthusiastic
congregation. ``I believe that we were both sustained and uplifted
because of prayer. And so I thank you and ask you not to quit
yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
