<DOCNO> NYT20000709.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7281 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-WIMBLEDON-MAIN0710-CO     07-09 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-MAIN0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sampras with his seventh Wimbledon title
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ When the match ended three minutes before 9
p.m., they still sat virtually anonymous in the deeply shadowed top
rows of Centre Court.
</P>
<P>
   Sam and Georgia Sampras stood and watched their youngest son
soak in all the emotion of the moment: the flash bulbs shimmering
in pale purple dusk, the American flag waving, the nearly 14,000
fans applauding his history-making performance, the joy and the
tears on their 28-year-old boy's face.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sampras had just survived a painful leg injury, terrible
nerves and four hours of rain delays to win a record-tying seventh
Wimbledon title Sunday and become the first man to win 13 Grand
Slams in his career, breaking Australian Roy Emerson's record of
12.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is amazing how this tournament just panned out for
me,'' Sampras said. ``I didn't really feel like I was going to win
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Rafter fought hard to protect his fellow Australian's
record, coming within three points of a two-set lead, but
ultimately got overwhelmed. Sampras hit a 122-mph service winner to
clinch the match 6-7 (10-12), 7-6 (7-5), 6-4, 6-2 after two hours,
57 minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras threw his arms into the air, then bent over and rested
his elbows on his knees as he cried. He stood and wiped his eyes on
his shirt and waved to his coach, friends and fiancee in the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great moment,'' Sampras said. ``It was an amazing
setting because it was getting dark, the flashes, the roar of the
crowd. (It) was a moment that I'll never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few seconds, he wandered the court, taking it all in
almost in disbelief. Then he looked toward the Friends Box.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all pointing to my parents, that I should go up
there,'' he said. ``It took me a while to find them. They were up
in the rafters.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't because he couldn't get them better seats. That was
because they prefer the background. He had to speak firmly to
convince them to fly from their Los Angeles-area home to London
even for this match.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the second Grand Slam final they'd ever seen him
play in person. The first was the 1992 U.S. Open he lost to Stefan
Edberg. But his absence doesn't mean they've been absent from his
career.
</P>
<P>
   His parents introduced him to tennis when he was 7, ferried him
to lessons and tournaments as a child and endured the many hours he
hogged the television to watch tapes of idol Rod Laver's matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've always kept their distance,'' Sampras said. ``They
supported, did what parents do. They just love you.''
</P>
<P>
   And after he turned pro at 17, they let him go and gave him his
``space.'' He even moved to Florida for many years before returning
to Southern California last year because he wanted to be closer,
finding family more important as he gets older.
</P>
<P>
   But like most parents, they still find watching so difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get very nervous,'' Sampras said. ``Not just that, but
being superstitious, they are very shy people. They don't want to
be on camera.''
</P>
<P>
   The cameras found them Sunday, although they declined to talk to
reporters. A BBC commentator even pointed out Sam Sampras in a
crowded shot as ``the man with the eyebrows.'' And once Sampras
found his parents, he made a deliberate climb up 20 rows into the
stands to hug them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to share it with my parents,'' he said. ``I've
wanted them to be a part of it. They gave me a chance to play this
great game.''
</P>
<P>
   But for most of the match, the tennis took precedence over the
parents. Rafter's also flew in, from Australia, for the final.
</P>
<P>
   When they took the court an hour late, both players started well
but Sampras dominated on his serve. Two rain delays later, the
first tiebreaker began. Sampras had two set points before Rafter
won it on his third chance -- when Sampras double faulted.
</P>
<P>
   The second set was similar, with no breaks of serve, and Sampras
started the second tiebreaker the same way he ended the first one:
with a doublefault. Rafter built that into a 4-1 lead, which he
celebrated with a fist pump, when Sampras lofted a forehand volley
long despite a wide open court.
</P>
<P>
   But then Rafter netted a volley, double faulted and hit a short
forehand passing shot into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I knew I was screwed,'' Rafter said. ``Then I just
thought, 'Oh God, this is really going downhill.' I was really
going to find it hard to deal with the nerves. That was a mental
blow more than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   And a lift for a worried Sampras. He won the second set four
points later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt like it was slipping away,'' he said. ``(I went)
from feeling like I was going to lose the match (to) I felt like I
was going to win the match within two minutes. That's grass-court
tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, darkness loomed. Neither player felt bothered or
rushed, but they knew time was limited. Sampras converted his first
of 10 break points in the fifth game for a 3-2 lead and Rafter
unraveled from there.
</P>
<P>
   In Sampras' first-ever speech to the crowd, he choked up when he
thanked fans for their devotion to him on ``the best court in the
world.'' He owns seven titles and 59-5 record at Wimbledon. Only
William Renshaw, father of grass-court tennis, earned as many
trophies, but his record is just 22-3 because in the 1880s,
defending champions played only the final.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras also added about $700,000 to his $39.5 million in career
earnings with the victory and joined a list of just five others to
win four consecutive Wimbledon titles.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, who won his 12th Grand Slam at the 1967 French Open,
planned to watch the match at his tennis camp in Switzerland. Since
Sampras moved within two of his 12 at Wimbledon 1998, ``Emmo'' has
remained gracious in saying he hates to see a record go, but
Sampras is a good man to have it.
</P>
<P>
   For Sampras, the record means a lot, especially after he
developed severe tendinitis and inflammation of his left shin
during his second-round match. He would have withdrawn from any
other tournament, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never, ever planned on ever breaking this record,'' Sampras
said. ``It's kind of transcended into something that I put myself
in a position to do. It hasn't hit me. It won't hit me for
months.''
</P>
<P>
   But what next, what more for this player?
</P>
<P>
   Sampras already has scaled back his schedule to concentrate on
the major tournaments. Perhaps he'll seek a 14th Grand Slam. He's
added Davis Cup as a priority this year but admits his injury might
hamper him if he joins the U.S. team to play Spain later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter said the French Open is the only glaring hole on a
stellar resume for the position of all-time greatest player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Pete's last big challenge,'' Rafter said. ``Like all
great champions, I think you've got to win on all surfaces in
majors. Pete, in my eyes, still goes down as the greatest player
ever. It would just be something that would really concrete it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras admitted the same but won't start working out for the
clay season just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an achievement standpoint, I've done what I've wanted to
do,'' he said. ``It's time to sit back and soak this up, not really
worry about what's next, just reflect on these last two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
