</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVS-MEETING-785&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNORS MEET BUT ARE DIVIDED BY POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.D., Ky., N.C., Md., Del.)   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ Republican governors outnumber Democrats
almost 2-1, and they were a confident, even cocky, bunch as they
descended on this university town in central Pennsylvania for the
92nd annual meeting of the National Governors' Association.
</P>
<P>
   One of their own _ George W. Bush of Texas _ was a shoo-in to
win this year's presidential race, they boasted at every
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   And, they predicted, Republicans would hold onto Congress and
win most, maybe even all, of the 11 governorships that are up for
grabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could hardly feel better about the way things are going,''
said Gov. Edward Schafer of North Dakota, chairman of the
Republican Governors' Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, not to be outdone, insisted that Vice President
Al Gore would turn things around once the summer nominating
conventions were over and voters focused on the fall election.
``We're extremely optimistic,'' said Gov. Paul Patton of Kentucky,
chairman of the Democratic Governors' Association. ``We're looking
to majority Democratic leadership in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   So confident was the Bush campaign that it did not send an envoy
to brief the Republicans here _ neither Bush nor his brother Jeb,
the governor of Florida, made an appearance. But Gore sent William
Daley, his campaign manager, to reassure and assuage the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Daley met privately with the Democratic governors. No sooner had
he gone than both Republicans and Democrats scheduled news
conferences, events that were so politically partisan that they
totally submerged what was meant to be the main business of the
meeting _ a four-day, nonpartisan discussion about ``strengthening
the American states in the new global economy.''
</P>
<P>
   There was instead endless speculation about whether any of the
40 or so governors present might end up as vice presidential
choices. No fewer than eight had been mentioned as possible
candidates and just as the dueling news conferences by the
Democratic and Republican governors' groups overshadowed the
convention, so did the vice presidential stir, which also had its
moments of one-upmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer was asked whether the stir was causing tension among the
governors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What tension?'' replied Schafer, who is not the subject of any
serious speculation about vice presidential candidates. ``I haven't
noticed any tension. I don't see them in any competition.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Patton, Daley exuded confidence during the briefing
of Democratic governors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very, very upbeat,'' Patton said. ``He said that this
race would turn around as soon as people began focusing on it,
after the conventions. They're not doing that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would the focus after the conventions improve Gore's
standing with voters, since nine out of 10 national polls have had
him trailing Bush by five to 10 points for several months?
</P>
<P>
   Because, Patton replied, other polls indicated that on most
major social and economic issues, a majority of voters favored the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters are with us,'' he said, ``and when people focus on
what they want, Al Gore will win.''
</P>
<P>
   Did the Democratic governors, by predicting a postconvention
collapse of the Bush campaign, see a parallel with the 1988
campaign of Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts? Dukakis, a
Democrat, led Bush's father by a substantial margin for months but
lost after the nominating conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't necessarily say that,'' replied Gov. James Hunt of
North Carolina, a Democrat. ``What I do say is that when people
finally focus on what counts and what they want, Al Gore will be
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Parris Glendening of Maryland, a Democrat, argued that Gore
would win not just because of his stand on issues but also because
he was a ``proven leader,'' experienced at the highest level in
handling both domestic and foreign issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrast that to the less than stellar performance and
experience of George W. Bush,'' Glendening said.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any anti-Bush argument that the Democrats presented
here that hit home with the Republicans, the assertion that Bush
was not up to handling the White House job was it. They devoted
most of an hourlong press conference to arguing otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, prominently mentioned as a
possible Bush choice for vice president, said that Bush qualified
as an experienced leader because he had served as chief executive
of one of the nation's largest states and understood how to
``practice the politics of what works.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not understand that governing principle, Ridge added,
because he had never been in an executive position. Rather, argued
Ridge, Gore saw governing as a you're-for-us-or-against-us
proposition.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the issue of supplying pharmaceuticals to the elderly and
poor, Ridge said, Gore saw it as ``you're either for the drug
companies or for senior citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You should try to get people together,'' Ridge said. ``The
politicization of that issue is not how to get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the governors managed to break free of partisan
politicking for an hour or so to hear Colin Powell discuss programs
that they might put in place to help the nation's young people, a
cause he has been promoting since he retired from the U.S. Army.
But in the end, the talk came around to politics.
</P>
<P>
   First, the general was asked again whether he would accept an
offer to be Bush's vice presidential candidate, or maybe run for
president himself at some point, given his popularity not only with
Republicans but also with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   No, Powell replied, as he has been replying for months. But some
day, he went on, he might accept an appointive job in the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just as the general was preparing to depart the convention
hall, Gov. Thomas Carper of Delaware had a word with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think you'd make a good president,'' Carper said.
``Now I know you would.''
</P>
<P>
   Carper is a Democrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
