u w BC-TAX-CUT-POLITICS-1STL     07-09 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CUT-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1220(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE OVER TAX CUTS IS SHIFTING TO SPECIFICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Rewrites story from 2nd graf to graf that begins ``There is a
changing ....'' And changes ``he said'' to ``Schmelzer said'' in
5th-last graf, since Schmelzer is female.) 
By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With projections of the federal budget surplus
rising and both parties in full election-year mode, the debate over
tax cuts is shifting from whether to what kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans continue to press for bigger reductions than most
Democrats will support, and there is unlikely to be any legislative
breakthrough this year.
</P>
<P>
   But in Washington and on the campaign trail, Democrats from
President Clinton on down are joining Republicans in backing tax
cuts _ enthusiastically in some cases, grudgingly and with
conditions in others _ to a far greater degree than they were a
year or even six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the clearest signs of shifting sentiment, nearly a
third of the Democrats in the House broke ranks with the party last
month and voted to repeal the federal estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore doubled his proposed tax-cutting package
a few weeks ago, to $500 billion over 10 years, moving him closer
to the $1.3 trillion plan offered by his Republican rival for the
presidency, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton announced recently that he would agree to a $250
billion, 10-year tax cut for married couples on Republican terms if
Congress would pass his plan to add prescription-drug coverage to
the Medicare system of health insurance for the elderly and
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The new political dynamics will be on display in Congress this
week when the Senate takes up the two big tax-cutting bills of the
year: the repeal of the federal estate tax, and the reduction of
taxes on nearly all married couples in the name of eliminating the
``marriage penalty,'' the quirk in the tax code that leaves some
two-income couples paying a bigger tax bill than they would if they
had remained single.
</P>
<P>
   On the estate-tax repeal, the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott
of Mississippi, said he was hopeful that he might be able to
attract enough support from Democrats to overcome procedural
hurdles and force a final vote on the bill this week.
</P>
<P>
   If they can get past those hurdles, Republicans are all but
assured of passing the bill. Repealing the estate tax has long been
one of the Republicans' priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate legislation, identical with the version passed by the
House, would gradually reduce and eventually eliminate the tax,
which applies only to estates valued at $675,000 or more, a
threshold that is already scheduled to rise to $1 million by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has made clear that Clinton would veto the bill.
But Republicans say just passing the legislation with bipartisan
support would be a powerful political symbol of opposition to the
tax, and they have not ruled out bringing the bill up again as part
of an end-of-the-year budget package.
</P>
<P>
   For years it was Democratic orthodoxy to label repeal of the
estate tax a giveaway to the very richest people in the country.
But to try to reduce defections from their ranks and display their
own tax-cutting credentials, Democrats in the Senate are planning
to offer a less expensive alternative proposal on the estate tax,
as their counterparts in the House did last month. The Democratic
proposal is expected to call for the effective elimination of the
tax for two politically powerful constituencies that say they are
hard hit by it _ owners of small businesses and family farms _ but
to continue to impose the tax at reduced rates on the very largest
estates.
</P>
<P>
   Lott also plans to bring up the marriage-penalty bill by the end
of the week under a procedure that would keep Democrats from
stalling the bill or loading it with amendments.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would cut taxes on married couples by $248
billion over 10 years, is larger than a version passed this year by
the House. As with the estate tax, Democrats plan to offer a less
expensive alternative. They would seek to eliminate the marriage
penalty without giving a tax cut to couples who already receive a
marriage bonus _ that is, a lower tax bill than they would pay if
they had remained single.
</P>
<P>
   Since Republicans have shown no signs of accepting his proposal
to swap a tax cut for the prescription-drug coverage plan, Clinton
is likely to veto the marriage-penalty bill if it passes. But
Republicans said that they would nonetheless be able to go to their
party convention at the end of the month and tell voters they had
done their part to enact big tax cuts, and that it was a Democrat
in the White House who had blocked them.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the two parties will remain stalemated on
fiscal policy as long as control of Congress and the White House
remains divided. Others are more optimistic about a compromise on
tax cuts, perhaps even this year, because there is enough money for
both parties to get what they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a question of horse trading at this point,'' said
Bruce Bartlett, a fellow at the National Center for Policy
Analysis, a conservative research group.
</P>
<P>
   But the supercharged politics of the campaign season will make
it difficult for any tax cuts to be enacted before a new president
and Congress take office next year.
</P>
<P>
   The muddled outlook reflects in part the uncertainty in both
parties about how much demand there is among voters for tax cuts.
And the evolving politics of tax cuts are just one illustration of
how the quickly increasing surplus projections are forcing both
parties to rethink their ideology and tactics on fiscal issues.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the White House increased its estimate of the total
budget surplus for the next 10 years by nearly $1.3 trillion, to
$4.2 trillion. Long-term budget forecasts are notoriously
unreliable, and the fiscal outlook could change substantially based
on how the economy performs.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties have agreed not to use the portion of the
surplus generated by Social Security _ $2.3 trillion over the next
decade _ for tax cuts or general spending. But that still leaves a
projected windfall of $1.9 trillion on the table, and just as
Democrats are becoming more open to tax cuts, Republicans are
proving more willing to go along with expanding government
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a changing climate on tax cuts,'' said Sen. William
Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Finance Committee. Roth said that the
larger surplus projections, the possibility that the long economic
expansion might be starting to run out of steam, and Clinton's
willingness to negotiate a deal have combined to give tax
reductions new political viability.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also said the rosier fiscal outlook has made tax
cutting more appealing _ or at least made it more difficult
politically to reject all tax cuts out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   But they said tax cuts are getting more bipartisan consideration
because Republicans in Congress have dropped their insistence on
putting forward all-encompassing tax-reduction bills that would use
all or most of the projected surpluses and instead are addressing
specific types of tax cuts one by one.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats generally remain solidly opposed to broad-based
tax-cutting packages of the type proposed by Bush in his
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats have always been willing to consider if not support
tax cuts that are fair, while reflecting our priorities and the
need for sound fiscal management of the surplus,'' said Gene
Sperling, the director of the White House's National Economic
Council.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``What has changed is that instead of the Republicans in
Congress offering a single, excessive tax-cut package that could be
rejected immediately as breaking the bank,'' he said, ``they are
now trying to slice their tax agenda into smaller pieces, which can
be individually considered on the basis of fairness, fiscal
prudence and priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   In the coming week, Democrats plan to hit the Republicans hard
on those points, asserting that the Republican versions of the
estate-tax and marriage-penalty bills are much too expensive and
too tilted to the wealthy. And they intend to make a case that tax
cuts are justifiable only after the two parties agree on more
pressing issues, in particular adding prescription-drug coverage to
Medicare and allocating more of the surplus to reducing the
national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats believe you can eliminate the marriage penalty and
reduce the estate tax, and at the same time provide Americans with
a prescription-drug benefit,'' said Ranit Schmelzer, communications
director for Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans just want to do the tax cut,'' Schmelzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said that Republicans, too, think there is enough money for
a sizable tax cut, a prescription-drug benefit and steady reduction
of the national debt. And he said that as he travels through his
home state, he finds considerable support among voters for acting
now to repeal the estate tax and cut taxes on couples.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are banking on getting support from Democrats who
are up for re-election this year and do not want to have to explain
their opposition to tax cuts. They point to Democrats like Sen.
Charles Robb of Virginia, who is in a tough race this year in an
anti-tax state and supports repeal of the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans acknowledge that their party also needs to
be willing to compromise if it wants Clinton to sign any tax cuts
into law, and that if they play politics with the issue they will
be exposed to assertions by Democrats that Republicans have run a
do-nothing Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a strong believer that what people back home want to see
at election time is what you've accomplished,'' said Roth, who is
also locked in a tight re-election race. ``There are some on both
sides who want an issue, not legislation, but I think that's
short-sighted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
