<DOCNO> NYT20000709.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7294 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SCHOOL-FUNDING0710-CO     07-09 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-FUNDING0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Michigan school funding reforms brings up new issues
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ Pioneer High School in Ann Arbor offers its
2,400 students 27 varsity sports, including water polo and
synchronized swimming in a 14-lane, 25-meter pool built just two
years ago. The academic curriculum boasts classes in guitar, Latin
and advanced jewelry design. Career-track programs include culinary
arts, cosmetology and home building.
</P>
<P>
   Ten miles to the north, the Whitmore Lake Public Schools enrolls
a scant 290 high school students district-wide. All elementary,
middle and high school students go to school in side-by-side
buildings that also include the superintendent's office. Course
offerings and extracurricular programs are limited.
</P>
<P>
   Six years after Michigan residents and their political leaders
tore apart and rebuilt the state's school-funding system to make it
fairer and more equitable, the state of Michigan allocates $8,430
for every Ann Arbor Public Schools student, compared to $5,696 for
each Whitmore Lake student. That rankles Whitmore Lake
Superintendent Glenn Bachman: ``What makes my Whitmore Lake student
worth $3,000 less than students at Ann Arbor or other wealthy
districts?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators and educators have suggested Michigan's funding
reform could serve as a blueprint for Ohio, and indeed, the
Michigan method would take steps toward satisfying the Ohio Supreme
Court's two strongest concerns about this state's school funding
system: that it relies too heavily on property taxes and provides
an unequal education. Michigan's overhaul, brought about by a March
1994 ballot issue dubbed ``Proposal A,'' shifted the burden of
school funding from local property taxes to the state sales tax. It
boosted funding for that state's poorest districts, narrowing _ but
not eliminating _ the funding gap between Michigan's poorest and
wealthiest school systems.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's hard to find much enthusiasm for Michigan's system,
particularly among that state's educators, some of whom feel the
Michigan ``solution'' created a whole new set of problems.
</P>
<P>
   They suggest school funding is being ``leveled down,'' with some
of Michigan's wealthiest and highest-performing districts feeling
an increasingly tight budget noose with little or no ability to
raise operating money from local voters. They cite the continuing
unfairness of the funding formula to some less-wealthy districts
such as Whitmore Lake. And they wonder what will happen to a school
funding system heavily reliant on a statewide sales tax when an
economic slowdown strikes the state.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Addonizio, associate professor of educational policy
studies at Wayne State University who has written extensively about
Michigan school funding, said proposal A was warmly received by
most parents and taxpayers the first two years after it took
effect. Some of the state's poorest school districts enjoyed a
substantial increase in their state funding in the years
immediately following proposal A, and residents' property taxes
dropped. In one year, the state's portion of school funding jumped
from 37 percent to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To determine how much money each school district should get
under the new sales tax system, the state took a look at how much
each district spent, per pupil, during the 1993-94 school year.
Property-rich districts were funded at their previously high
levels, while state officials pumped some additional money into the
lowest-spending districts. Michigan then adopted a complex funding
formula that would boost funding for the state's poorest districts
at a faster rate than the wealthiest districts.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Arbor and other relatively wealthy districts saw their
annual increases in per-pupil funding slow to a crawl. Between 1994
and 2000, Ann Arbor received an average annual increase in state
per-pupil funding of 1.8 percent per year. Even the poorer
districts that enjoyed a funding boost during the mid-1990s watched
that growth slow dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more districts hitting a wall each year, seeing their
revenue growth slow down. . . .But if the cost of maintaining your
educational programs rises 3 to 4 percent or more every year, you
eventually are going to have to make cuts,'' Addonizio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, more and more people are growing impatient with
proposal A,'' Addonizio said. ``Eventually there will be more
political pressure'' to make changes in the funding system.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Arbor school officials estimate they've lost $7.3 million to
inflation to Proposal A. The district has a $148 million budget.
Meanwhile, Pioneer High School, one of Ann Arbor's two
comprehensive high schools, is bursting at the seams with students,
housing 2,500 in a school built for 1,900. The local school board
would like to build a new high school, and they could go to local
voters to seek approval of a property tax bond issue for the
construction money necessary. But Proposal A prohibits them from
seeking a local tax levy to pay for staffing and operating the
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communities do not have any choices about what kind of school
district they want. That's the biggest problem'' with Michigan's
system, said Deb Small, community relations director of the Ann
Arbor Public Schools.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Shulman, head of Ann Arbor's parent-teacher organization,
said Proposal A has had a profound effect on her community's
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone from gleefully spending on whatever sounded good,
to allocating scarce resources,'' Shulman said. ``The impact is
just beginning to be felt. It's going to hit us like a freight
train.''
</P>
<P>
   The district has had to eliminate administrative positions and
reduce technology support in schools, among other cuts. And the
budget looks bleaker next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to keep the cuts as far from the classroom as
possible at this point, but they're getting closer,'' Small said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Doernte, grants supervisor for the Ann Arbor district,
said ``How much reduction can we take and still maintain the
quality of programs? How much reduction can we take until the
parents begin to walk out? That's the scary part.''
</P>
<P>
   The Birmingham School District in suburban Detroit, also one of
Michigan's wealthiest districts, is in similar predicament,
wrestling with a budget deficit and bracing for staff and program
cuts. Ten teaching and five staff positions as well as a handful of
popular programs, including elementary school Spanish classes, have
been targeted as officials try to bring the district's budget into
balance for next school year. School officials blame Proposal A for
their shortfall and say the problem is only going to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitmore Lake Superintendent Bachman shakes his head
ruefully at such talk. Bachman says he gets a kick out of listening
to his fellow superintendents commiserate about cuts they'll have
to make to an elementary art program or school nurses _ luxuries
that Whitmore Lake has never seen, but which other districts take
for granted.
</P>
<P>
   It was schools such as Whitmore Lake that Proposal A was
supposed to help. And it has, to some extent: the district's
per-pupil funding has grown from $4,106 to $5,696 since Proposal A
took effect. Most of that bump, though, occurred the first three
years after the constitutional amendment was passed; the increases
have slowed considerably since 1997, and Whitmore Lake still badly
lags the state's wealthiest districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Proposal A had been implemented as it was sold and as it
was intended, there would be very few issues with it,'' Bachman
said. ``But our education budgets are still at the whim of the
legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   The playing field sure isn't level, Bachman said, when the
difference in per-pupil funding between Ann Arbor and Whitmore
Lake, if added up over 12 years of school, would pay for a Whitmore
Lake student's four-year bachelor's degree at the University of
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Plevek, president of Whitmore Lake's Parent Teacher
Student Organization, said she would like to see the
``equalization'' occur at a more rapid pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to attract and keep good teachers, because we
can't pay them'' as much as surrounding districts can, Plevek said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators seem reluctant to reopen the school-funding debate.
Last month, they passed a three-year education budget that made no
major changes to the funding formula.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators also know if they allow school districts to go to
local voters for additional operating money, the equity gap could
begin to widen again, as property-rich districts reap the benefits
of their communities' wealth. Addonizio said some states have
avoided that trap by requiring communities who vote in additional
operating millage to share some of the money raised with other
districts in the state. For example, for every dollar raised by a
local levy, 25 cents could go into a statewide pot of money to be
distributed to other districts.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Arbor PTO president Shulman said schools must look
aggressively for alternative funding, from considering
``pay-for-play'' for sports and other extracurricular activities to
soliciting local businesses and individuals for donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not make public schools your favorite charity?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
