u s BC-LACROSSE-NYT &LR;      07-09 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LACROSSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACROSSE PLAYING BROTHERS FIND THE SPORT PROVIDES THEM NEW
HORIZONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SOPHIA HOLLANDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ryan Powell's teammates funneled him passes as he hovered around
the goal in the men's national lacrosse final against Princeton on
May 29. It was the final game of the 22-year-old's storied career
at Syracuse, and there were seven minutes left, then four, then
one, and though he would get his first championship, he was a
single point from tying his older brother Casey's school record of
287 career points.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers had competed against each other their entire lives,
trying to be the best in every sport they played. But in this one
moment Casey rooted for his brother to break his record, and Ryan
decided he wanted to tie it.
</P>
<P>
   Casey, 24, watched tensely from the stands in College Park, Md.,
as the final seconds left the clock. Then, with 18 seconds
remaining, Ryan scooped up the ball and smoothly flipped a pass to
a penetrating Ethan Mills, who scored. Ryan had done it. As he
pounded to the sideline, arms raised, his brother roared. It had
been two years since they played on the same front line at
Syracuse, but the four-time all-Americans are linked in school
lacrosse lore.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, the Powell brothers stood on a field in
Columbus, Ohio, and again they made their mark. They were the
starting attackmen for one of two all-star lacrosse teams that are
traveling the Northeast this summer as part of an ambitious
experiment to promote the first professional outdoor lacrosse
league. On Saturday, their team lost, 23-21, but Ryan had four
goals and one assist, and Casey had three goals and three assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little bit of strangeness because I don't get to go
out and play with him that much; but every time that we go out
there and step on the field it seems like we always want to bring
our `A' game to the table because we don't want to get shown up by
the other one,'' Ryan said, grinning. ``So that helps us play a lot
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Powell brothers and 40 other top players will showcase major
league Lacrosse in six more cities: Philadelphia; Baltimore;
Uniondale, N.Y.; Buffalo; Rochester; and Newark in the conclusion
of the tour on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The league's co-founder, Jake Steinfeld, has said that a crowd
of 5,000 is the target audience for each site. Strong support would
mean the founding of an official league next summer.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface it seems like a risky proposition. Lacrosse
remains rooted in the Northeast, though it has still failed to
catch on in major eastern cities, including New York.
</P>
<P>
   Steinfeld, chairman of Body By Jake Enterprises, is joined by
league partners Dave Morrow, president of Warrior Lacrosse, a
leading lacrosse equipment company he founded while playing
championship lacrosse at Princeton; and Timothy Robertson, former
chief executive officer of the Family Channel and the SFX Sports
group. Each partner is skilled at marketing.
</P>
<P>
   All the games will be televised, two nationally. A shot clock
and a two-point play will be added in an effort to inject more
excitement and draw in viewers unfamiliar with the game. Fireworks
and half-time contests are planned and tickets range from $9 to
$15.
</P>
<P>
   Where sports such as soccer have struggled to generate and
promote a series of stars, SFX, which represents Michael Jordan and
Kobe Bryant, will concentrate on creating recognizable faces. The
Powell brothers' extraordinary physical talent and competitiveness,
combined with their open, embracing personalities, have placed them
at the center of that strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Carthage, N.Y., about an hour outside of Syracuse,
the Powells were introduced to lacrosse when an elementary school
gym teacher brought in a lacrosse stick to show his classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was like: `You've got your baseball gloves, football,
basketball. What do you need these sticks for? What's this game?'''
Casey recalled.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks of whining, their father finally agreed to buy
the $30 sticks. The Powell brothers carried them onto the school
playground, where they chalked boxes, devised challenges and broke
school windows, and into their backyard, where they would play for
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Through high school the Powell brothers teamed up on paper
routes, to mow the lawn at the local cemetery and sell candy at
school to raise money to compete in summer lacrosse camps.
</P>
<P>
   After high school they went to Syracuse, where they quickly
became role models for star-struck lacrosse students. They left New
York state for the first time as they flew to games, staying in
different hotels, in different cities, eating in different
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lacrosse allowed me to do so many things in my life that I
would never have been able to,'' Ryan said. ``Since I've been in
New York, I kind of find myself sitting around people watching
because it's just so exciting to see every different culture. It
all collides here in New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
