u a BC-OHIO-PRISONS0710-COX     07-09 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-PRISONS0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Powell: Build character, not prisons
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ Ohio may not have to build another prison
for at least a decade, state officials said Sunday, after remarks
by retired Gen. Colin Powell who urged the nation's governors to
invest more in children, not prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we have built our last prison for the next 10
years,'' said Reginald Wilkinson, director of Ohio's Department of
Rehabilitation and Correction. ``Gen. Powell is right. We need to
be building up kids, not jails, so they develop character and never
end up in a prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell was keynote speaker at the National Governor's
Association conference, which runs through Tuesday and is being
attended by 38 governors, including Ohio Gov. Bob Taft.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, centered on state's taking advantage of the new
economy, continues today with an address from President Clinton on
health care.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, is
national chairman of America's Promise: The Alliance for Youth, a
national crusade started in 1997 to build character of the nation's
youth.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked the governors for helping his program reach millions
of kids and then told them they need to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all of our wealth and success the government is spending
$2 billion on jails,'' Powell said. ``Our children don't start out
there. They deserve to have the right people in their life, people
who will let them know that someone cares.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson and Taft said Ohio's prison population has decreased
by about 2,500 inmates over the last two years. A new $93 million
prison with 1,000 beds is scheduled to open in Toledo this summer,
and Wilkinson believes the state won't need another correctional
facility for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio houses about 46,000 inmates at 31 prisons around the state.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that the state's inmate population continues to
shrink, Taft said the state must continue to support ``character''
classes that have been implemented in some school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Taft said he doesn't want to mandate a character education
program, so that local schools can maintain control of development
classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to start character development at the elementary level
so no child gets left behind,'' Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   Following his address Powell received a standing ovation from
the governors and it was clear that the retired general remains a
key political figure in the Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   Powell has taken himself out of contention to become the running
mate of Texas Gov. George W. Bush on the Republican presidential
ticket. But the retired general said he and Bush remain close
friends and he would be open to accepting a cabinet position in a
Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those conversations with Gov. Bush are private,'' Powell told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Taft won't do much ``policy heavy-lifting'' during the
conference, but his agenda includes lobbying on behalf of the
Piketon uranium plant, which is scheduled for closing by the U.S.
Enrichment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Taft spokesman Scott Milburn said the governor hopes to speak
with Clinton on the Piketon plant closing. ``We don't think Ohio
got a fair deal,'' Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   Taft also will press fellow governors to pass a resolution to
resolve a conflict with Canadian officials who want to authorize
Canadian television stations to use the same frequency as Ohio's
Multi-Agency Radio Communications System.
</P>
<P>
   If TV stations share the frequency, it would interfere with
Ohio's $272 million, state-of-the-art radio and data communications
network that has been in the works for two years and will be
completed in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
