<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBERT THE GREAT GAINS THREE-LENGTH UPSET 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nick Zito's rookie star, Albert the Great, threw his
hat into the ring for 3-year-old honors Sunday when he opened the
second half of the racing season by outrunning three veterans of
the Triple Crown and leading all the way to score a three-length
upset in the Dwyer at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   Zito reasserted himself after his Triple Crown candidate,
Greenwood Lake, was injured before the Kentucky Derby. And this was
a trainer who won the Derby with Strike the Gold in 1991 and Go for
Gin in 1994. But Zito bided his time, found a new runner in his
barn _ a son of Go for Gin, at that _ and unfurled him Sunday in a
four-horse field that included More Than Ready, fourth in the
Derby; Red Bullet, winner of the Preakness; and Commendable, winner
of the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The only outsider was Albert the Great, who did not race as a
juvenile but who won his previous three races this year while the
others were competing for horse history. It was a rare lineup of
classic winners and contenders, and they produced a rare result:
Albert the Great first by three lengths, More Than Ready second by
a length and three-quarters, Red Bullet third by half a length and
Commendable last in a select four-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ecstatic,'' said Zito, who had predicted that his colt
would make a second-half impact in the race for the year's honors.
``It's the best feeling to be opening the second half of the season
by getting back in the 3-year-old campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds at post time reflected the unlikely mix of star horses
and their stories. Red Bullet, who had not run since he won the
Preakness almost two months ago, was the favorite at 3-5. More Than
Ready, who had not run since finishing fourth in the Kentucky Derby
two months ago, was next at 9-5. Commendable, who had not run since
he won the Belmont four weeks ago, was a juicy 9-1. And Albert the
Great, who had not run since he won an allowance at Belmont Park
last month, was listed at 7-1 as he took the long stride upward
into stakes racing in his eighth start.
</P>
<P>
   The principal absentee was Fusaichi Pegasus, winner of the Wood
Memorial and the Kentucky Derby, who was widely rated the horse of
the year until he sustained a minor foot injury and missed the
Preakness and Belmont. But his spirit, and his record, hung over
the four horses as they raced to overtake him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that it's over, you can come up with a million reasons why
you won,'' Zito said. ``Red Bullet, coming off the Preakness win
and having time off; Commendable, coming off the mile-and-a-half
Belmont; and More Than Ready, coming off the Derby, all favored
Albert. It takes an exceptional horse to come off allowance wins
and beat those type of horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Richie Migliore, the rider on Albert the Great, reported that
``we bounced out of the gate perfectly,'' and added: ``He really
has a smooth stride once he gets going. Nick and I talked before
the race and figured we wanted to be outside because the rail was a
little dead. Commendable came to me on the outside, but we pushed
it out a notch. More Than Ready came up the inside of us, and my
horse just took off. This colt is only going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Pletcher, who trains More Than Ready, thought ``the winner
came over on More Than Ready in the homestretch, but didn't make
contact and he was clear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For not having raced in two months,'' he said, ``that was a
good race for him. He beat the Preakness and Belmont winners, and
he finished second.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bailey, back to work after contending with a kidney stone
all week, noted that Red Bullet ``flipped in the gate,'' and ``he
just didn't have anything.'' And Joe Orseno, who trains the colt
for Frank Stronach, said that Red Bullet was ``totally flat, and
we'll have to rethink our plans.''
</P>
<P>
   But D. Wayne Lukas said that his plans for Commendable hadn't
changed: Next is the Haskell at Monmouth Park on Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come off the Triple Crown,'' he said, ``you have to
regroup for the second half of the season. You can't crank them up
for every start.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert the Great ran the mile and a sixteenth in 1:42 3/5, paid
$16 for a $2 bet to win and earned $90,000 for his arrival in the
big leagues. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
