u s BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-09 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS, YANKS AND ANOTHER OPERA BOUFFE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's Roger Clemens' story, and he's sticking to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to hit him in the head; I was trying to crowd
him, pitch him inside,'' Clemens said Sunday, reiterating what he
had said the night before. ``The guy's hit me well and I was trying
to make an adjustment, but the adjustment I was trying to make
wasn't to hit the guy in the head.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' pitcher was talking about his pitch that hit Mike
Piazza in the head Saturday night at Yankee Stadium. While Clemens
held to his explanation, the Mets were not buying it. To the Mets,
the pitch, which they viewed as deliberate, signaled the outbreak
of a New York baseball war that may be hostile enough to get George
Steinbrenner's juices flowing again. After all, the Yankees'
doodle-dandy owner turned 70 on July 4, and sometimes it takes the
type of reaction that flowed from Mets officials to boil the blood.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the pointed comments the Mets continued making before
the final game of the four-game interleague series with the
Yankees, Steve Phillips, their general manager, threw about half a
dozen members of the Yankees out of the Shea Stadium weight room
and canceled plans for the Mets' All-Star contingent to fly to
Atlanta with the Yankees' group on a chartered plane after Sunday
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Had Steinbrenner been immediately privy to the developments, he
would have had the opportunity to add a line to his legendary
lexicon of choice comments. Phillips could have joined Frank
Cashen, one of his predecessors, in the Steinbrenner version of
``Bartlett's Familiar Quotations.''
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu was not the first target of a Steinbrenner zinger
that used the word pus as an adjective. Steinbrenner used that word
years ago to disparage Cashen after Cashen, then the Mets' general
manager, referred to Yankee Stadium by the name of a movie popular
at the time, ``Fort Apache, the Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the teams became so hostile at one point that
the Mets refused to play spring training games against the Yankees.
The Yankees wanted the Mets to play at their spring site in Fort
Lauderdale but would not go across Florida to play at the Mets'
spring home in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Before that period, the Mets once used Dwight Gooden and Frank
Viola in the same spring game and beat the Yankees. Steinbrenner
sneered at the Mets, saying they were so desperate to beat the
Yankees that they saved their Cy Young award winners for them.
</P>
<P>
   In those years, the most important exhibition games the Yankees
played, according to Steinbrenner guidelines, were those against
the Mets that were televised back to New York. The second most
important were games against the Mets that were not televised.
</P>
<P>
   After a Billy Martin-managed Yankees team lost a televised game
to the Mets, Steinbrenner stormed into the clubhouse and started
screaming at Martin. When Martin retreated to the trainer's room,
Steinbrenner followed. The feisty manager yelled back at the owner,
telling him not to yell at him in front of his players. For
emphasis, Martin slammed a table with his hand. Except a big tub of
ice was on the table, and Martin's hand struck the ice, splashing
water all over Gabe Paul, an innocent bystander of a general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Later on, when Lou Piniella was managing the Yankees, he opted
to play a collection of minor leaguers against the Mets. A
Steinbrenner eruption ensued, prompted by his embarrassment in
front of a group of high-powered friends, including Lee Iacocca.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner would not allow his general managers to make trades
with the Mets. When Piniella was the Yankees' general manager, he
had a deal with Joe McIlvaine of the Mets for Rafael Santana, but
Steinbrenner refused to approve it. Finally, after Piniella
implored him to let the trade go through, Steinbrenner told him,
``If we're going to trade with them, get that guy Jefferson.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella had no idea whom his boss meant until he realized that
the cover of a recent baseball publication featured Gregg
Jefferies.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the skirmishes Steinbrenner staged by using
players. If the Mets had a good young player on their team, the
Yankees had to find one to match him. Thus because Dwight Gooden
was a Mets pitcher, the Yankees rushed Jose Rijo to the major
leagues. Tim Leary's presence on the Mets' pitching staff produced
Gene Nelson prematurely for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1985 season, the Yankees and the Mets made stunning
trades days apart. The Yankees acquired Rickey Henderson, the Mets
Gary Carter. The teams subsequently had their new players in town,
holding news conferences only days apart. Steinbrenner was livid
about the newspaper coverage of the events and ordered his public
relations people to tabulate the column inches each received.
</P>
<P>
   When the count ran heavily in the Mets' favor, Steinbrenner
chewed out his public relations staff, saying the Mets' staff had
done a better job.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner has never taken his feud with the Mets to the
ownership level. He has never spoken ill publicly of Fred Wilpon
and Nelson Doubleday, always saying he liked the two men, which is
more than the two men can say of each other.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Mets have branded Clemens as a low-life of a pitcher,
Phillips, a Wilpon-Doubleday lieutenant, could be a marked man. The
next voice heard may be that of General Steinbrenner. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
