<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WESTERN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLENBY WORKS OVERTIME TO WIN THE WESTERN OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEMONT, Ill. _ Robert Allenby finds a way to make playoffs pay
off.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Allenby captured his first win on the PGA Tour by
defeating Craig Stadler in a four-hole playoff in the Houston Open.
In the Western Open on Sunday, Allenby triumphed in another
playoff. After losing a three-stroke lead on the back nine in
regulation, Allenby outlasted Nick Price, winning on the first hole
of sudden death with a par after Price's poor tee shot led to a
bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a final-round four-under-par 68 at Cog Hill Golf &AMP;
Country Club, Allenby finished at 14-under-par 274 with Price, who
shot a 69. Jim Furyk, Greg Kraft, and Shigeki Maruyama finished in
a three-way tie for third at 12 under par, while Tiger Woods, the
world's No. 1 player and the defending champion, shot a final-round
72 to finish tied for 23rd.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Allenby so cool under pressure? Perhaps because life has
forced him to put golf in perspective. In 1996, Allenby was almost
killed in a car accident in Spain, with multiple injuries putting
his career in jeopardy. Then in 1998, the wife of fellow Australian
Stuart Appleby, Allenby's closest friend on the tour, was killed in
an automobile accident in England. Allenby helped Appleby through
his darkest days, staying with him for about a month, then deciding
to play in the United States largely because he wanted to play with
Appleby.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, Allenby, who turns 29 on Wednesday, took another
step toward being recognized as one of the tour's better players.
He became the tour's sixth multiple winner this year, joining
Woods, Phil Mickelson, Hal Sutton, Jesper Parnevik and Notah Begay
III. That is the kind of company Allenby wants to keep. And with
another playoff victory, he proved again he knows how to capitalize
when he senses a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playoffs must agree with me,'' said Allenby, who started the
day three strokes off the lead but who made eight birdies,
including seven in a 10-hole stretch. ``To beat Nick Price in a
playoff is awesome. He's a great player. He's pretty good under the
heat.''
</P>
<P>
   For Price, who has not won since the 1998 St. Jude Classic, it
was another lost opportunity. Price was doomed after his tee shot
on the playoff hole, the par-4, 452-yard No. 18. His drive drifted
into the right bunker, near the front lip, with trees blocking his
path to the green. His only choice was to hit a sand wedge back
into the fairway, leaving him 107 yards from the green.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing Price hit his tee shot in the bunker, Allenby
wisely hit a 3-wood off the tee into the middle of the fairway,
then hit an approach shot 18 feet from the pin. Price's third shot,
a sand wedge, rolled off the green and down into the rough, 20
yards from the cup. After Allenby two-putted for par, Price needed
to make a chip shot to keep the match going. But it slid past the
hole, giving Allenby the victory and Price a headache.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed, giving it to Robert on a platter
there,'' Price said. ``The last 13 holes, I hit three good tee
shots. I think I could have won quite comfortably if I had driven
the ball well. Let's put it this way, I don't think that driver's
going to see the light of day again.''
</P>
<P>
   With birdies on eight of his first 15 holes, Allenby reached the
16th tee holding a three-stroke lead over Price, who was on the
15th hole. But Allenby bogeyed both No. 16 and No. 18, while Price
birdied No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   For Woods, it was the first time he did not finish in the top 20
since the Sprint International last August, ending a streak of 23
top-20 finishes. Woods did not sound concerned about his putting,
however, as he looked ahead to his next tournament, the British
Open, where he will try to complete the career Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I putted absolutely terrible going to the United States Open,
and I did all right there,'' said Woods, who was headed to Ireland
for a week of golf and fishing before the British Open. ``I just
couldn't get it going this week. I tried my best. I drove it great.
I just didn't make any of those 10- to 15-footers to get momentum
going.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was Allenby who left with another victory, and $450,000.
Once again, he was forced to work overtime. Once again, it was
worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in six playoffs and I've won all six,'' said
Allenby, counting victories on other tours around the world. ``To
win when Tiger's in the field is awesome. He doesn't lose too many
these days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
