<SLUG> BC-RAC-HOLLYWOOD-GOLF-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH LONGEST ODDS, EARLY PIONEER WINS HOLLYWOOD GOLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEN GURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Early Pioneer, a former claiming horse
trying Grade I company for the first time and the longest shot in
the field of nine, ran down the 7-5 favorite, General Challenge, in
the stretch and captured the $1 million Hollywood Gold Cup Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Early Pioneer ran the mile and a quarter in 2:01 2/5 for the
one-length victory over General Challenge, with the New York
invader David another length and a half back.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which paid $51 for a $2 bet to win, was the first
in a Grade I race for all of Early Pioneer's connections: his
owners, David and Holly Wilson; his trainer, Vladimir Cerin; and
his jockey, Victor Espinoza, Hollywood Park's leading rider, who
replaced the regular rider, Matt Garcia, for this race.
</P>
<P>
   David Wilson, who owns several Southern California auto
dealerships and has a 25-horse stable, picked Early Pioneer out of
an Oct. 25, 1998, sprint at Santa Anita based on Daily Racing Form
past performances. He suggested Cerin claim the horse for $62,500
from the trainer Jerry Hollendorfer and the Golden Eagle Farm,
owners of General Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it would not be a good claim when we claimed him,''
Cerin said, adding that he called David Wilson ``after we took off
the bandages and asked if he had claiming insurance. I didn't know
if he'd survive the race. When I first looked at his ankles, I
thought his career might be in jeopardy. But he's 100 percent
sound.''
</P>
<P>
   The $600,000 first-place purse more than doubled Early Pioneer's
career earnings. Most of the $506,815 had come from sprinting, and
he had never run a mile and a quarter until Sunday. His biggest
victory had been the Grade II San Bernardino Handicap on April 9,
when General Challenge finished third behind David. General
Challenge came out of the race with an entrapped epiglottis, which
closes the windpipe during eating, and underwent surgery. This was
his first race in three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to get beat, but he laid his body down,'' the trainer
Bob Baffert said of General Challenge. ``At least the horse is
back. He just got tired.''
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge, who won the Santa Anita Handicap in March
with a sweeping late move, was closer to the leaders in this race,
tracking David and Big Ten on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked him to do something different because fresh horses
tend to be a little keener in a race,'' said Corey Nakatani,
General Challenge's jockey. ``If we'd have had a race under our
belt, I think we would have won it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the backstretch, Espinoza followed 2 lengths behind General
Challenge. At the three-eighths pole, with General Challenge about
to edge past David, Espinoza got after Early Pioneer, who caught
General Challenge on the outside in the stretch and pulled away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect General Challenge in front of me, but when I
saw him there, I knew it was over,'' said Espinoza, who dyed his
hair gold to mark his first ride in the race. ``I was glad to see
the best horses in front of me because I knew I would catch them.''
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Espinoza, who also won the $300,000 Triple Bend
Breeders' Cup aboard Elaborate Sunday, got the mount only two weeks
ago. Cerin conceded he had jumped on the jockey's bandwagon,
noticing the dramatic improvement that had put Espinoza ahead of
the world-class jockeys Nakatani, Kent Desormeaux and Chris
McCarron in the Hollywood Park standing. ``I just thought he was an
OK transplant from Northern California who should have stayed
there,'' Cerin said. ``But the kid is phenomenal seeing holes. He's
really developing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerin, 45, came to California from Yugoslavia through Canada and
graduated from UCLA with a degree in kinesiology, the study of
muscular movement. He became a trainer after he purchased a horse
in partnership with several professional athletes. He said that
Early Pioneer, who is eligible for the Breeders' Cup, would most
likely be pointed toward the $1 million Pacific Classic at Del Mar
on Aug. 26. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
