<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WIMBLEDON'S CHAMPIONS
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, July 10:
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every Wimbledon tennis tournament produces one unexpected
outcome or another, but this year's was exceptional for the number
of dramatic firsts and emotional milestones. Pete Sampras defeated
the weather, the clock and a noble and agile opponent in Patrick
Rafter to win his 13th Grand Slam title, breaking Roy Emerson's
longstanding record of 12. Seven of these victories have been
achieved on Wimbledon's grass courts, the rest on the hard courts
of the United States and Australian Opens, none on the soft clay
courts of the French Open _ the only shortcoming in Sampras'
otherwise extraordinary career.
</P>
<P>
   A Rafter victory would not have been surprising, given his
riveting semifinal triumph over Andre Agassi. But even if Sampras
had not won, this Wimbledon had already been made memorable by the
Williams sisters, especially Venus. She defeated her younger sister
Serena in the semifinals, then dominated the defending champion,
Lindsay Davenport, to become the first African-American woman since
Althea Gibson in 1958 to win Wimbledon. On Friday, Venus and Serena
became the first African-American team to reach a Wimbledon doubles
final, and they may yet win the doubles title in a match delayed
until today by the same rainfall that nearly forced a postponement
of the men's final.
</P>
<P>
   In that event, Sampras was not to be denied. Despite occasional
shakiness in his normally lethal serve, he began to return Rafter's
serve with increasing precision and power. By the fourth set,
Sampras was clearly the more confident of the two, and Rafter had
little to offer in return. This should not be the end of it for
Sampras. Though he seems to have been dominating the game forever,
he is still only 28 years old.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-00 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
