u a BC-OBIT-SACK-ART-NYT     07-09 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SACK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAROLD SACK, 89, CONNOISSEUR OF AMERICAN FURNITURE, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By RITA REIF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harold Sack, the nation's pre-eminent dealer in American period
furniture, who paid a staggering $12.1 million for an 18th-century
Newport desk-bookcase in 1989, died on Saturday night after a brief
hospitalization at South Nassau Communities Hospital in Oceanside,
N.Y. He was 89 and lived in Oceanside.
</P>
<P>
   Sack, who was president of Israel Sack Inc., bought the boldly
carved bonnet-topped mahogany secretary by John Goddard at
Christie's in New York, stunning the art world by paying what was
then the highest price ever at auction for an object other than a
painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all masterpieces hang on the wall,'' Sack said that day
after the gavel came down on his purchase. The desk, which he
bought for Robert M. Bass, a Texas financier, was at 9 feet high
the tallest surviving example of a status symbol for the merchants
of Colonial America. Its pedigree was enviable: It was had
descended in the family of the original owner, Nicholas Brown of
Providence, R.I., from which Brown University took its name.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was nearly blind and had to use a wheelchair after
suffering for a decade from Parkinson's disease, Sack was until a
month ago usually at his desk at the Israel Sack gallery, 730 Fifth
Avenue, at 57th Street, three times a week. He worked there with
his younger brothers, Albert, the vice president, and Robert, the
treasurer. As recently as January, he had sold another rarity with
a million-dollar price tag: an 18th-century Philadelphia Pembroke
table that had been discovered recently and was the only known such
piece with cabriole legs.
</P>
<P>
   Sack came into the family business as president in 1933, fresh
out of Dartmouth College, where he was Phi Beta Kappa and had
graduated magna cum laude a year earlier, majoring in English
literature. The Depression was deepening, the antiques business was
in turmoil, and his father, Israel, who had galleries in Boston and
New York, was forced to liquidate to pay his debts.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoning plans to do graduate work at Oxford, Sack and a
colleague formed Israel Sack Inc., a new corporation with two
stockholders, few assets and no cash but with Israel Sack's good
name and his talent for buying and selling. The elder Sack, who
came to the United States in 1903, had been a cabinetmaker in a
small shtetl in Kovno, now Kaunas, in Lithuania, where he was born.
After landing in Boston, he worked for two years at making
reproductions, repairing antiques and peddling furniture before he
founded his own business on Charles Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was very young and went on buying trips with my father
in his open Buick touring car through the Massachusetts
countryside, I learned how to recognize masterpieces and to pay
more for them,'' Harold Sack said in a 1987 interview. ``My father
moved fast, paid high prices and then sold what he bought for even
higher prices.''
</P>
<P>
   These traits made envious dealers at the time call him Crazy
Sack. But Israel Sack's knowledge, enthusiasm and savvy about
American furniture won over the early collectors of American
furniture, including industrialists like Henry Ford and Henry
Francis duPont, as well as Francis and Mabel Garvan (utilities and
transportation) and Ima Hogg (Texas oil) and Maxim Karolik, a
failed opera singer who married Boston money and spent it wisely.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Sack, too, was always daring in his buying, paying record
prices for antiques, especially after his father's death in 1959,
when he began to dominate the field. When he blinked or raised his
pencil or paddle at auctions, the prices for American antiques
rose.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1960s into the 1990s, bidding with a gambler's gleam in
his eye, he rewrote scores of auction records for American
furniture. In 1977, he raised the record for American furniture to
$135,000, buying a Boston bombe chest. In 1980 he pushed the record
to $396,000, for a block-front Newport chest. And in 1983 he did it
again, paying $687,500 for a Newport kneehole desk, all at
Sotheby's. The $12.1 million he paid at Christie's for the mahogany
secretary in 1989 remains the record for American furniture,
although an 18th-century Italian cabinet brought $15.2 million in
1990 at Christie's in London.
</P>
<P>
   Sack sold these and other choice pieces to postwar
industrialists and businessmen, and he also bought for and sold to
the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Art Institute of Chicago, the
Museum of Fine Arts Boston, Colonial Williamsburg and the Henry
Francis duPont Winterthur Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harold Sack's association with the Metropolitan Museum goes
back more than 40 years,'' said Morrison H. Heckscher, curator of
decorative arts. ``He was a founding member of the Friends of the
American Wing and remained one. In 1980, Harold, representing the
three Sack brothers, made a generous contribution to the wing to
honor their father. His name appears above three federal period
galleries.''
</P>
<P>
   As a dealer, Heckscher said, Harold Sack's ``alchemy'' combined
``his charm, his excellent eye, his business acumen and his
powerful analytical intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sack was born in Lynn, Mass., the eldest child of Israel and Ann
Sack, and went to Boston Latin School before Dartmouth. He later
served as an adviser to Clement E. Conger, curator of the
Diplomatic Reception Rooms at the State Department, in forming that
collection. He served as a national trustee throughout the 1980s at
the Baltimore Museum of Art and lectured extensively at Colonial
Williamsburg, Winterthur and elsewhere. He wrote articles on the
history of American furniture and on collecting, and he was author
with Max Wilk of ``America Treasure Hunt,'' the story of Israel
Sack, the man and the business, published in 1987 by Little, Brown
&AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his brothers, he is survived by his wife, the
former Loretta Dorn; four sons, Dr. Kenneth Sack of Tiberon,
Calif., David, of Pearland, Texas, Michael, of Philadelphia, and
Daniel, of New York; and eight grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Martin Wunsch, a New York consulting engineer and a 40-year
veteran of collecting American furniture, said in assessing Sack's
career: ``Harold Sack helped to elevate the field of American
antiques radically. When Harold came into the business, if you had
money, you bought English or French furniture. But he saw American
furniture of the 18th and 19th centuries as a reflection of
America's growth, strength and originality. And he helped make
collectors see that, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
