<SLUG> BC-OBIT-AKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAROLD AKS, 78, WHO LED CHORAL GROUPS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Harold Aks, a conductor and music teacher at Sarah
Lawrence College and the Dalton School for nearly half a century
whose amateur vocal group became a respected part of New York's
musical life in the 1950s and 60s, died on June 30 while on
vacation in the Canadian Rockies. He was 78 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was congestive heart failure, said his son, David.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s Aks was hired to conduct the Interracial
Fellowship Chorus, a group of 150 amateur singers that reflected
the diversity of New York. He led the group until the late 1960's.
He also founded the Dorian Chorale, a 22-member professional group
specializing in contemporary vocal music.
</P>
<P>
   Aks was born in Yonkers and grew up in Brooklyn. He studied
music at Brooklyn College. During World War II he served as a
weatherman for the Army Air Corps, stationed in India.
</P>
<P>
   After the war Aks studied at the Juilliard School of Music,
graduating in 1948 with a bachelor's degree in choral conducting.
His teachers included Robert Shaw and Pierre Monteux. Aks taught
music and conducted the chorus at the Dalton School from 1949 to
1997 and at Sarah Lawrence from 1954 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Aks' third wife, Patricia, died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son, of Northridge, Calif., he is survived by
his companion, Lorie Hartman of Manhattan; a daughter, Catherine
Aks of Brooklyn; a stepson, Michael Untermeyer of Philadelphia; a
stepdaughter, Kathryn Untermeyer Atwood of Concord, Mass.; a
sister, Esther Ray of Freehold, N.J.; and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
