<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE COMING BACKLASH AGAINST `THE BIG TEST' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   By BRENT STAPLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The national obsession with getting into a brand-name college
has bled down into grade school, where children who have yet to
reach puberty are biting their nails over the SAT. More than 2
million high school students will sit for the tests this year,
after concerned parents have shelled out tens of millions of
dollars for special preparation classes. In the frenzy of practice
and preparation, students will ignore the carefully worded booklet
from the College Board, which sponsors the test. The booklet notes
that the test has nothing to do with innate intelligence _
suggesting that no such thing exists. Nor does it measure either
what was learned in high school or motivation, creativity and
special talents, factors that affect success in college. The SAT is
rather a test of mental dexterity, one element among many in
predicting college performance.
</P>
<P>
   These caveats have always been true. Even so, the SAT was
promoted as a sacred index that tells all about the individual.
Real estate agents sell houses based on scores at nearby public
schools. Educational rating services evaluate colleges based partly
on average SAT scores. Bond-rating companies are said to take the
scores into account when judging a college's creditworthiness.
</P>
<P>
   When the scores are mailed out this year, high school guidance
offices will fill with anguished, tearful teen-agers for whom
disappointing scores will seem a stain on their lives, if not the
end of the world. These teen-agers and their parents were the
target audience when Mount Holyoke College in Massachusetts
announced that prospective students would no longer be required to
submit SAT scores with their applications. Over all, about 390 of
the country's 1,800 four-year colleges and universities do not
require the tests. But in discarding the SAT requirement, Mount
Holyoke followed several other quality liberal-arts institutions,
including Bates, Bowdoin, Bard and Connecticut College.
</P>
<P>
   These highly ranked colleges have long since counted the test as
no more than about 10 percent of the admission process, relying
instead on high school transcripts, graded papers, letters of
recommendation and an evaluation scheme that rates high schools in
terms of academic rigor. A faculty committee at Holyoke concluded
after several years of research and internal debate that the test
should be optional. Holyoke's president, Joanne Creighton, was
personally convinced by reading Nicholas Lemann's 1999 book, ``The
Big Test: The Secret History of the American Meritocracy,'' which
documents how the SAT became a tool for class segregation.
Creighton describes Holyoke's decision as a way of saying that
``our process is individualized, rigorous and includes qualitative
material'' _ and does not favor the rich, who can lay out vast sums
for test preparation.
</P>
<P>
   But this was also a marketing decision. In general, schools that
drop the test requirement enjoy a surge of applications that allows
the school to remain highly selective, while attracting a stronger,
more diverse student body. Holyoke is hoping to replicate what
happened at Bates College in Maine, which has seen its application
pool double since 1984, when SAT scores were no longer required.
More than a quarter of Bates students come with no SAT scores. A
study of the Bates students found that they had the same grade
point averages and the same graduation rates as Bates students who
took the SATs, which raises profound doubts about why the SATs are
given such weight in the first place. ``These students say, `I am
not being accurately measured by these standardized tests,' '' said
William Hiss, a vice president at Bates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We misunderstand intelligence when we think of it as a
unidimensional quality _ or in terms of the math and verbal scores
on the SAT,'' Hiss said recently, adding that Bates seeks out
students who have shown ``disciplined success'' in a variety of
areas, including those who write exceptional application essays or
who have made a definitive difference in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   The positive response from guidance and college communities
suggests that Holyoke's decision could herald a backlash against
the tyranny of the big test. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
