<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PERU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REBUILDING DEMOCRACY IN PERU  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, July 10:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This spring Alberto Fujimori mugged democracy in Peru, retaining
his presidency by winning an illegitimate election and runoff vote.
Although Peru erupted in protest and foreign governments rebuked
him, Fujimori gambled that his adversaries would not have the
stomach to make him hold a truly democratic election.
Unfortunately, this cynical strategy is proving to be correct. It
is still possible, however, to rebuild the democratic institutions
that Fujimori has destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Although election observers from the Organization of American
States documented widespread unfairness, Brazil, Venezuela and
Mexico led the OAS to acceptance of Fujimori's victory. The OAS
sent its chief, Cesar Gaviria, and the Canadian foreign minister,
Lloyd Axworthy, to Peru in late June to start working out a
democratization program with Fujimori and his opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS has been there before. After Fujimori's assumption of
dictatorial powers in 1992, the OAS sent a similar mission, which
Fujimori manipulated. He is trying to do so again. He has endorsed
the group's goals for reforms _ which are worthy, but extremely
vague _ and set up an unimpressive democracy commission.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition has asked for the government to take several
steps to show its good faith before the opposition is willing to
negotiate a specific democratization plan. They include restoring
the constitutional court judges Fujimori fired when they blocked
his re-election plans and sacking Vladimiro Montesinos, the
sinister intelligence chief. The OAS must not settle for cosmetic
change again. It should demand a strict democratization program,
with measurable benchmarks, beginning with the removal of
Montesinos from all political influence.
</P>
<P>
   If Fujimori lags, the OAS ought to be willing to act, perhaps by
instructing members to withdraw their ambassadors, deny visas to
Fujimori and Montesinos, and vote against certain loans to Peru in
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund. If the OAS is not
willing to sanction Fujimori for noncompliance, Washington should
act on its own. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-00 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
