<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: THE STATE PIE AND HOW TO CUT IT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City, upstate and the suburbs. It's the
classic three-way cut, how candidates, political analysts and
pollsters always divide up New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Elections are more than statistics, but numbers are inescapable,
and crucial, which raises a provocative question: Are we defining
each of the three slices of the state pie correctly? That's always
easier to answer after the fact, but so far, it looks as if the
answer is no. The suggestion here is that candidates, pollsters,
strategists and journalists belatedly faced facts and overcame
their New York City-centrism, but haven't begun to pay enough
attention to the suburbs. That could be a problem, especially this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidate for Senate, Rick A. Lazio, represents
Suffolk County, on the state's eastern stretch of suburban life,
Long Island. The Democrat, Hillary Rodham Clinton, moved from the
White House to Chappaqua, in suburban Westchester. And the
Republican presidential candidate, George W. Bush, is running as a
social moderate and fiscal conservative _ in other words, he's
positioned himself as the candidate of suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   The suburbs could well emerge as the battleground in New York,
yet the pros still think of them as basically three or four places
_ Nassau, Suffolk, Westchester and maybe Rockland _ as if suburban
sprawl hadn't come to New York. It has. And in more than three or
four places.
</P>
<P>
   There is Staten Island, which votes more consistently with the
suburbs than with the other four boroughs. Why not lump it with the
suburbs? There are also what might be called the extended suburbs,
the counties north and west of the city: Orange, Putnam, Sullivan,
Ulster, Dutchess, Columbia and (again) Rockland. Those 11 counties
have accounted for 32 percent of the statewide vote in recent
elections, compared with 29 percent for the city without Staten
Island (or 31 percent with), and 39 percent for upstate (the 47
counties north and west of Columbia County). It makes a lot of
sense to view the counties as a voting bloc, says Philip Friedman,
a political strategist and proponent of this theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, they vote cohesively, share the same concerns and
have proven a willingness to split tickets, and so deserve maximum
attention from both candidates,'' said Friedman, who supports
Clinton and provides his observations to some of her advisers, but
is not working for any candidate in New York this year.
</P>
<P>
   Elections are won or lost on a lot more than numbers, of course.
Disaffection with Mario M. Cuomo, for instance, energized voters
upstate, severely injuring him in the 1994 gubernatorial race. Four
years later, Senator Alfonse M. D'Amato lost to Charles E. Schumer
in part because he had worn out the welcome he once enjoyed among
Democratic city voters.
</P>
<P>
   This year, such ambiguous factors as Clinton fatigue and Lazio's
callow image seem to be influencing voters. But demographics and
voting patterns will still play a role, and there's a good argument
that the conventional wisdom hasn't caught up with reality.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the city vote remains solidly Democratic, but now
that it accounts for as little as 29 percent of the statewide vote
(down from 41 percent in 1960), Clinton and Al Gore will need to do
well upstate and in the suburbs even if they get overwhelming
support in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is spending a great deal of time upstate, but recent
election results show that while the suburbs lean to the
Republicans, they are less ideological, more flexible, and voters
there are more willing to switch parties: The 11 suburbs strongly
supported Gov. George E. Pataki in 1998, and 10 of the 11 voted for
Clinton in 1996 (only Putnam supported Bob Dole).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the suburbs _ more than the four core city boroughs
_ are growing, while upstate has lost population, estimates show.
The suburban counties also consistently vote alike; all 11 voted
the same way (mostly Republican) in seven of the last 10
presidential elections, for example.
</P>
<P>
   While the suburban counties are traditionally Republican, Nassau
and Westchester increasingly vote Democratic, and all 11 counties
are ideologically flexible. The voters care about the same issues
that interest suburbanites everywhere. Polls show they are socially
moderate and fiscally conservative, in favor of gun control and
abortion rights. ``They care about quality of life,'' said
Friedman, the political strategist. ``These are people worried
about schools, safety, the environment, property taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is reasonable to expect a campaign dominated by talk about
those very issues. Assuming the candidates have figured out the
not-so-complicated State of New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
