<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHUMER-ENERGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER CALLS FOR ACTION TO PREVENT AN ENERGY CRISIS
</HEADLINE>
 By SHERRI DAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If present trends continue, the United States, and
New York state in particular, could face the most serious domestic
energy crisis since the 1970s, Sen. Charles Schumer said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, in a news conference at his Manhattan office, said a
report by his office showed that the nation's inventories of crude
oil, natural gas and home heating oil are at or near a 24-year low,
while the demand for them and for electricity is rising. That, he
said, could indicate that an energy emergency lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have a mild summer and a mild winter, which would
take much of the pressure off our inventories,'' Schumer said, but
added, ``All it would take is a somewhat unseasonably hot summer or
cold winter to push us over that line.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has called on President Clinton to create a national
energy commission to study energy use and production nationwide.
The presidential commission is necessary, he said, because Congress
is divided on how to handle energy issues.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, P.J. Crowley, said that the Clinton
administration had put before Congress a number of proposals to
deal with the energy situation, but that Schumer's ideas were
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Stu Nagurka, a spokesman for the federal Department of Energy,
said the department had not yet reviewed the senator's report.
</P>
<P>
   In New York state, gasoline prices have surged to an average of
$1.64 per gallon, according to a survey by AAA.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said New York was in a precarious position because of
the state's reliance on home heating oil and the generally high
price of gasoline throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   According to state Public Service Commission reports, over the
last three years, New York City's peak electricity demand has
increased by 700 megawatts, which equals the output of an entire
electricity plant. Power failures are likely during the summer
because of the limited capacity of transmission wires to import
energy from other regions and the inability to put new generating
plants in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer also proposed miles-per-gallon standards for sport
utility vehicles, which represent 40 percent of all new car sales
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   If the president accepts his proposal for an energy commission,
Schumer said, he would like to see members represent
energy-producing states like Alaska and Texas as well as consumer
and environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   The senator also said he supports using alternative energy
sources like solar energy, giving tax breaks to new electricity
plants that use clean natural gas and promoting energy conservation
efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
