<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-MAIN0710-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong plans to ascend in peaks
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAX, France _ When Alberto Elli stepped to the podium Sunday
afternoon to accept his bouquet of zinnias and daffodils and show
off his yellow jersey, most thought it would be the Italian's final
time to be in the sweet limelight at the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 112-mile stage from Agen to Dax in southwest France was
the final stage in which the sprinters, such as the 36-year-old
Elli, could shine. Mapei's Paolo Bettini won stage nine in a time
of 4 hours, 29 minutes and 6 seconds. However, unlike the past few
races, when sprinters bolted and stayed far from the main group of
cyclists, the peloton rode conservatively, with 157 of them
receiving the same winning time as Bettini.
</P>
<P>
   The overall standings didn't change. Lance Armstrong, the
defending Tour champion, remained in 16th place, 5:54 behind Elli.
He received the same time as Bettini.
</P>
<P>
   Expect that to change today when the riders enter the intense
mountain phase of the Tour. Today's 127-mile stage from Dax to the
mile-high summit of Hautacam in the Pyrenees Mountains should
scramble the leader board, with the real competitors stepping
forward to compete for the yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   To complicate an already difficult stage, snow is forecast for
parts of the day. There likely will be a heavy mist as the cyclists
try to get up three major climbs, including the summit finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fifteen guys ahead of Lance won't be in front of him after
Monday,'' predicted Frankie Andreu, Armstrong's teammate with the
U.S. Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong clinched his Tour championship last year, when he won
consecutive stages, winning a time trial at Metz and the first
mountain stage at Sestrier in the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Time margins in the flatter stages tend to be measured in
seconds, if it all, which is what happened Sunday. In the
mountains, where Armstrong and former Tour winners Marco Pantani
and Jan Ullrich are expected to fare well, riders cross the finish
line many minutes apart.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he ``prioritized'' his main threats before the
start of the Tour. None of riders he foresaw as his competition
have gone past him in the first nine stages. ``I was trying to
visualize all the different scenarios,'' he said. ``You have to
prioritize. I don't think we have yet to see who is strong. The
race starts Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, like he did last year, paid close attention to the
Tour's mountain courses when he trained for the event in May. He
rode today's course several times to learn every nuance, every
mountain pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a long training ride,'' he said. ``I went up it, then
rode back down and did it again a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyclists have ridden the flatter stages more aggressively than
they did last year. The speeds have been faster and there have been
more riders willing to attack. Earlier last week, members of the
Postal Service were content to let the sprinters go. But over the
weekend, the American team became more aggressive, with riders such
as Andreu and Kevin Livingston chasing down the riders trying to
escape the peloton.
</P>
<P>
   Elli tried a breakaway early in Sunday's stage in order to pad
his lead. But Livingston stayed with him. ``We were just trying to
have representation in the top group,'' Andreu said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
