<HEADLINE>
LACK OF PREP MAYBE HURT GENERAL CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It seemed as though all the fretting and
questions about General Challenge's fitness following a three-month
layoff would be forgotten as the gelding charged into the lead at
the top of the stretch Sunday afternoon at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   In the final eighth of a mile of the Hollywood Gold Cup,
however, General Challenge lost the lead and a chance to make
history. He finished a strong second under jockey Corey Nakatani, a
length behind long-shot winner Early Pioneer, and his connections
seemed pleased with the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can work them all you want, but there's nothing like a
race,''trainer Bob Baffert said. ``You hate to get beat like that,
but he laid his body down and gave it a good effort, so at least we
know he's back strong.''
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge had a chance to become the first horse since
Affirmed in 1979 to win the Santa Anita Handicap and the Gold Cup
in the same year, and bettors made him the 3-2 favorite Sunday. But
all week long, Baffert couldn't escape questions about the horse's
condition.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge, a winner in three of his previous six Grade I
starts, had last raced April 9 in the San Bernardino Handicap at
Santa Anita and finished a disappointing third. He also had surgery
to correct a breathing problem, but Baffert proclaimed his horse
ready to run.
</P>
<P>
   The horse trained well leading up to the Gold Cup, but after the
race, Baffert conceded that General Challenge could have benefited
from a prep race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lacking a recent race, that might have been a factor,''
Baffert said. ``I thought when he turned for home, he looked like a
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, David and Big Ten set the pace early, but General
Challenge remained close, somewhat surprisingly, just two lengths
off the lead after a half-mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked him to do something a little different because he was
fresh, and fresh horses tend to be a little keener in a race,''
Nakatani said. ``He came out and positioned himself perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into the final turn, General Challenge made his move and
pulled ahead of David by a length, but Early Pioneer came from the
outside and passed General Challenge in the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being off for three months and being an athlete, you've got to
think he lost some kind of fitness,'' Nakatani said. ``The other
horse just outran us today. If we'd have had a race under our belt,
I think we would have won it easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Nakatani rejected the suggestion that General Challenge might
have been better served by staying behind the leaders early and
stalking the pace from farther behind, the way the horse typically
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track was fast, it was fast all day,'' Nakatani said. ``I
don't care about the fractions, I just care about how the horse is
running, and he was right there. He ran a strong race.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said he intends to next run General Challenge in the
Aug. 26 Pacific Classic at Del Mar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
