<SLUG> BC-NY-CHRYSLER-BUILDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER EYEING OFFICE SPACE IN NEW YORK'S LANDMARK CHRYSLER
BUILDING 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Chrysler Building in midtown Manhattan was an
icon of the automobile age when it opened in 1930, with stylized
hubcaps and racing cars on setbacks, hood-ornament gargoyles and a
stainless steel spire thrusting skyward.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy years later, Walter Chrysler's glorious 77-story Art
Deco tower may again become a powerful symbol for an automaker
whose fortunes are as dependent upon popular images and Wall Street
perceptions as it is on engines and the open road.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler AG, one of the world's largest companies with
revenues of more than $150 billion and principal offices in
Stuttgart, Germany, and Auburn Hills, Mich., said Sunday that it
planned to rent space in the Chrysler Building as a ``virtual
headquarters'' _ a meeting place for its board and a center for its
investor relations and public relations staffs.
</P>
<P>
   For DaimlerChrysler _ whose stock has plummeted since
Daimler-Benz swallowed the Chrysler Corp. in November 1998 _ the
upper reaches of the landmark tower at 42nd Street and Lexington
Avenue would provide luxury space for only about 100 of the
company's hundreds of thousands of employees.
</P>
<P>
   But it would reaffirm the American roots of a company that has
been viewed increasingly by investors as a European behemoth with
the global aspirations its chairman, Juergens Schrempp, and put the
company's key image makers squarely in the media and financial
capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good opportunity if we can move to the Chrysler
Building,'' Michael Pfister, a DaimlerChrysler spokesman, said by
telephone from Stuttgart.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming a report in The Detroit News &AMP; Free Press Sunday,
Pfister said that DaimlerChrysler's investor and public relations
departments would be moved from Auburn Hills to New York, and that
the company hoped to lease space in the Chrysler Building for those
staffs, as well as meeting space for it's 13-member board of
managers. The boar currently meets twice a month in New York in the
Seagram Building on Park Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Pfister said the deal was not yet set and declined to discuss
details of reported negotiations with Tishman Speyer Properties, a
principal owner of the Chrysler Building. Tishman Speyer could not
be reached Sunday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The News &AMP; Free Press reported that DaimlerChrysler had offered
$100 per square foot for the top five floors, and would provide $5
million for renovations, including a restoration of the Cloud Club,
where Chrysler executives once wined and dined in marble-and-bronze
splendor with sweeping views over the city.
</P>
<P>
   When it opened on May 28, 1930, the Chrysler Building _ William
Van Alen's architectural masterpiece _ was briefly the world's
tallest structure at 1,046-foot, but was topped by the Empire State
Building in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   The building's lobby featured red Moroccan marble with a ceiling
mural 110 feet long and 76 feet wide by Edward Trumbull, the theme
of which was industrial and transportation progress. The mural was
restored last year.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler's founder, who insisted upon the automotive iconography
in the architecture of the building, occupied a lavish suite of
offices at the top.
</P>
<P>
   However, Chrysler did not establish a corporate headquarters in
his building, choosing instead to rent out its offices and keep
Chrysler offices in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler Building's facade was designated a New York City
landmark in 1978. In 1997, Tishman Speyer and the Travelers Group
bought the building for $225 million.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempp, DaimlerChrysler's chairman, is said to be acutely
aware of the advantages of a company presence in New York City,
near Wall Street and the headquarters of the major American media.
</P>
<P>
   Since the merger creating DaimlerChrysler, the company's stock
has lost about half its value _ it closed at 54 1/8 on Friday _
blamed largely, financial experts contend, on investor perception
of the company . American investors made up half of the
shareholders of the merged company in 1998, but now make up only
about a quarter of the shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempp is said to believe that a move to the Chrysler
Building, even by a few key operatives, could represent a powerful
signal that a company with global ambitions was ready to play in
New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
