<SLUG> BC-R-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-ART-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ATTACKS PASSER-BY WITH PIECE OF CONCRETE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make one-time purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A young woman walking from church to an East Side
subway station suffered a fractured skull Sunday afternoon when she
was struck from behind by a man wielding a melon-sized chunk of
concrete, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the woman, Tiffany F. Goldberg, 25, occurred
minutes after noon. It was the latest frightening and seemingly
random assault in a public place in Manhattan, and bore uncanny
similarities to the attack last November on Nicole Barrett, a young
woman from Texas who was attacked in Midtown by a man who smashed
her skull with a 6{-pound paving stone.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Brown, who lives directly across the street from the
scene of Sunday's crime, came out of her building moments after
Goldberg was struck. She said an off-duty firefighter, who had
leapt from his car as the attack occurred, began helping Goldberg
as she toppled to the sidewalk in front of an electrical
substation.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg was bleeding heavily, she said, and the firefighter was
cradling her head and trying to stanch the flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just floored,'' Brown said. ``But she was conscious,
because she was squeezing the hand of this guy who was helping
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, who moved to New York four years ago and is a waitress
at the Bryant Park Grill in Manhattan, was taken to Bellevue
Hospital Center; the authorities there said she had survived the
attack with surprisingly few injuries. Wes Anglin, the hospital
administrator on duty, said she was in stable condition Sunday
night and described her as ``alert and oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Andrew McInnis, a police spokesman, said that the stone
struck her directly in the back of the head, fracturing her skull,
and that she also suffered two chipped teeth and lacerations when
she fell face-first to the ground. But there was no apparent sign
of neurological damage, the authorities said, and Goldberg was held
for observation and to wait for a specialist to interpret the
results of a CT-scan.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis also said that although Goldberg had no recollection of
the attack, she had remained conscious throughout the afternoon and
was strong enough to be interviewed by detectives. She had also
been able to talk by telephone with her father in Madison, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has talked with many people, but she is unaware of exactly
what happened, because she was hit from behind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Barrett, Goldberg, 25, was not robbed. Brown said her
handbag was undisturbed on the ground near where she fell. And like
Barrett, Goldberg had no known connection to the man who assaulted
her, the authorities said. As in the earlier assault, the man who
fractured Goldberg's skull ran away and was not immediately
apprehended.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities declined to discuss their investigation in
detail but said that they were seeking a man, believed to be in his
20s to 40s, who was about 5 feet 6 inches tall and 150 pounds, and
was wearing a bright gold shirt at the time of the attack. They
also said the chunk of concrete, apparently from a shattered
sidewalk, was recovered on the street. It weighed 3 to 5 pounds,
the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police supervisors said the investigation's initial focus was on
the homeless, because two witnesses said the man who struck
Goldberg appeared disheveled. Detectives were seen late Sunday at
the nearby Bellevue Men's Shelter. Bernard Samson, a shelter
supervisor, said the police took a man into custody for questioning
Sunday about 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The police would not confirm that they had a man in custody, and
said the investigation was following other leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just attacking the homeless, we're looking at many
possibilities,'' McInnis said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the buildings on the block where Goldberg was attacked
have security cameras pointed toward the sidewalks. But the two
cameras at the electrical substation are still being installed and
were not working Sunday, said Sandy Miller, a spokeswoman for the
utility company Con Edison.
</P>
<P>
   However, Miller said, the police had obtained videotape from
another building. ``There's an adjacent building with a camera
working, and I am told that the police have a videotape of the
entire attack,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The police declined to comment about any videotape.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Goldberg, who lives in Manhattan, had moved to New York four
years ago, the police said. She had lived in Brooklyn until
recently and planned to enroll at Columbia University this fall.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday she had attended the 10:30 a.m. service at the Marble
Collegiate Church and lingered afterward for coffee and pastry.
McInnis said she planned to pick up a newspaper and return home by
subway, and was attacked just after leaving the church.
</P>
<P>
   About 12:10 p.m. she was walking on the sidewalk when the man
slammed the concrete into her head. Brown, who arrived seconds
later, described a disturbing scene: a young woman, stylishly
dressed in a blue sleeveless top and black pants, sprawled on the
ground, struggling through the disorientation and blood, trying to
sit up. The firefighter was holding her head. He was calmly urging
her to stay down.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis said that given the severity of the attack, the outcome
was surprising. ``She's conscious,'' he said. ``It appears she's
going to be fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
