<HEADER>
A7343 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     07-09 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW, DODGERS ENVY ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a friend had told you back in April that the Los Angeles
Dodgers would envy the Anaheim Angels at the all-star break, you
would have helped your buddy find counseling.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have never, ever had a single reason to envy their
little baseball brothers, the team Walter O'Malley allowed to play
at Dodger Stadium for four years (1962-65). The Dodgers have won
six World Series. The Angels have watched 39.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the snide little war between megalomaniac owners
(Fox, Disney), the Dodgers generally are indifferent to the Angels,
while the Angels are just indifferent, period.
</P>
<P>
   But at the traditional all-star break, here are four reasons why
the Dodgers should feel something about the Angels:
</P>
<P>
   1. The Angels, despite losing their best pitcher during the
offseason to free agency (Chuck Finley) and two veteran pitchers
during the season to injury (Ken Hill, Tim Belcher), have a better
record. The Angels are 47-41 and just swept Colorado. The Dodgers
are 44-42 and were shutout in their last two games before the
break.
</P>
<P>
   2. While the Dodgers are the ones who lean on their tradition,
it is the Angels that are managed by a blueblood, Mike Scioscia.
Eighty-eight games into his managing career, he seems to have
bought a touch of the old Dodger (set ital) familia (end) to the
Anaheim clubhouse, replacing the ennui of past generations.
</P>
<P>
   3. While the Dodger pitching theme is ``Park and Brown and
reason to frown,'' a tattered staff of journeymen or worse, the
Angels suddenly have all these promising twentysomething pitchers
jockeying for innings.
</P>
<P>
   4. Where the Dodgers have been putting out one fire after
another, all hot spots descended from the Mike Piazza fireball, the
Angels appear to have a plan.
</P>
<P>
   One makes this last point cautiously, because it would be wrong
for anyone to believe that the good folk at Disney have put a lot
of thought into how their baseball team performs on the field. In
the Disney corporate world, the Angels are merely a division of
their amusement holdings, and not exactly an E ticket. They're more
``Mr. Toad's Wild Ride'' than ``Matterhorn.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, former General Manager Bill Bavasi had a plan, too -- sign
homegrown players to longterm contracts, avoid arbitration -- and
it failed to produce a division title or keep him employed.
</P>
<P>
   But there does seem to be some de facto policy at work in
Anaheim. Disney has gone through all of the typical machinations of
modern baseball management -- build a new (or renovated) park,
invest in a free agent (Mo Vaughn), dispatch upper management
(Bavasi, Terry Collins), shake up the clubhouse (Finley, Jim
Edmonds) -- and settled into letting baseball nature take its
course.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not necessarily a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Angels are healthier than they were a year ago, and you
knew they would be simply because just about everyone was hurt at
some point in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil of the clubhouse a year ago has dissipated. One can
argue long into the night whether Edmonds and Collins got a raw
deal, but it doesn't matter anymore. They're gone and the clubhouse
dynamic is different.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia has everyone's focus directed on the field, the kind of
thing one expected from the former Dodger catcher, Iron Mike, who
had a quiet work ethic and who guarded the plate with his life. No
one in the clubhouse has to wonder what Scioscia expects of them,
and if they meet that standard, they're not going to spend a lot of
time in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are all the distractions and debris of '99. The Angels
strength in 2000 is that no one is wondering who will get traded or
fired (no one will) or if management will add a free agent down the
stretch (not a chance).
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Angels can hang in a pennant race with the
surprisingly successful Seattle Mariners and Oakland A's is the
question of the summer. But they look a lot like those two teams
ahead of them, reason enough to think they might compete next
summer if not this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have survived quite nicely without Ken Griffey, not
to mention Randy Johnson. They rebuilt their pitching staff around
what they got from Houston (John Halama, Freddy Garcia) when they
traded The Unit under free agent duress, and it is now deep and
young. While the Reds have sunk under the weight of
Griffey-inspired expectations, the Mariners are playing loose and
good.
</P>
<P>
   The A's, meanwhile, endorsed the same policy Bavasi and several
other teams have taken in the wake of the Yankees, Dodgers and
Orioles spreading money around like manure. They built around
products of the farm system, put together a budget with a bit of
flexibility, and were patient.
</P>
<P>
   It's a notable statement that the teams considered to have the
brightest futures are those that invested in their farm system and
have embraced young pitching as the key component.
</P>
<P>
   Take away Hill and Belcher (who happen to have two of the
highest ERAs on the team) and the Angel pitching staff looks like a
day care center.
</P>
<P>
   There are ex-Trojans Brian Cooper (25) and Seth Etherton (23),
Dominican Ramon Ortiz (24), and lefthanders Scott Schoeneweis (26)
and Jarrod Washburn (25). Derrick Turnbow, a neat Rule V claim by
new G.M. Bill Stoneman, is just 22. He pitched last year in A ball.
Combined, they are 19-13 on the season.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn has an ERA under 4.00, an astonishing achievement in
the current beer league softball atmosphere in the A.L.
</P>
<P>
   Behind them in the farm system are former Fullerton star Matt
Wise, St. John Bosco product Mark Harriger, and Matt Beaumont and
Steve Green. Plus, Jason Dickson, should he ever regain his health,
and Mike Holtz are just 27.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to Bavasi's foresight, Stoneman has a workable
budget, with a nucleus of players under contract, and no apparent
holes outside of the one currently vacated by injured shortstop
Gary DiSarcina.
</P>
<P>
   It may not produce a playoff spot in 2000, but at least the
Angels can look down the road with some hope. Give it a year, and
maybe the Dodgers look down the freeway with envy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
