<SLUG> BC-RAC-GOLDCUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY PIONEER WINS HOLLYWOOD GOLD CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. -- David and Holly Wilson had just finished
watching a replay of their 5-year-old gelding, Early Pioneer,
winning Sunday's $1 million Hollywood Gold Cup when victorious
trainer Vladimir Cerin arrived at the postrace press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won again, Vladimir,'' David Wilson joked.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's winning team of jockey Victor Espinoza, Cerin and the
Wilsons is laughing all the way to the bank after the 24-1 long
shot collared favored General Challenge midway through the stretch
and posted a one- length victory in front of an on-track crowd of
29,151 at Hollywood Park, giving both Espinoza and Cerin their
first Grade I wins.
</P>
<P>
   The winner's share of $600,000 increased the Wilsons' earnings
to more than $1 million since they claimed Early Pioneer for
$62,500 at Santa Anita in October 1998. The son of Rahy has won 6
of 19 races since the claim, including the Grade II San Bernardino
Handicap in April at 26-1.
</P>
<P>
   The winning time for the 1 miles on dirt was an unspectacular
2:01 2/5, but there is nothing ordinary about Early Pioneer's
success since being switched from sprint to route races during the
past Santa Anita meet.
</P>
<P>
   Early Pioneer has three victories and three seconds in six races
since the change. Matt Garcia was aboard for the first five, but
the meet's leading rider, Espinoza, got the call Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make the change myself and I explained it to
Matt,'' Cerin said. ``It was a difficult thing to do because I like
Matt, I respect him, and I was taking a good mount from him. But I
felt Victor would fit the horse a little bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   Espinoza fit him like a glove, settling Early Pioneer back into
sixth place as pacesetter David went the first half-mile in :46
2/5. The winner was third, behind David and General Challenge,
after a 1:34 4/5 mile and then finished strongly for his ninth
lifetime victory in 31 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I turned for home, General Challenge was done. I knew I
had it,'' Espinoza said. ``I only worried about (Eddie)
Delahoussaye's horse (Out of Mind). I know that sometimes he is
coming like a rocket. But I never saw him.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 45-year-old Cerin, the victory was the pinnacle of a
steady, yet unspectacular career. His biggest victory before Sunday
came in a couple of $300,000 races.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's joined the trainers' millionaire club, along with the
likes of Bob Baffert, D. Wayne Lukas, Ronald McAnally and Richard
Mandella.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it means yet,'' Cerin said. ``I've never won
one before, so I'll have to assess it. It's nice to be surrounded
by friends and people I like.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert and jockey Corey Nakatani thought General Challenge's
three- month layoff was a major factor in the 4-year-old gelding's
second consecutive defeat. Nakatani said he placed his mount closer
to the pace than in his most recent races because ``fresh horses
tend to be a little keener in a race.''
</P>
<P>
   After General Challenge, it was another 1 lengths back to
third-place finisher David. Out of Mind was fourth, followed by Cat
Thief, Blueprint, Chester House, Big Ten and Pleasant Breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Early Pioneer and General Challenge will likely square off again
in the $1 million Pacific Classic on Aug. 26 at Del Mar, according
to both horses' connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna go home and get a good night's rest, then I'll
call Mr. and Mrs. Wilson in the morning and tell them he came out
of the race in great shape, I hope,'' Cerin said. ``We'll wait four
or five days before we make any decision and we'll do it together.
That (Pacific Classic) would be in our plans, I guess that would be
on top of my list, but we'll take a vote and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Espinoza won twice Sunday, raising his meet-leading victory
total to 49. Five of the victories have come in stakes races.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
