<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOST-AND-FOUND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEA-TAC LOST-AND-FOUND GETS TOP MARKS IN STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALIYA SAPERSTEIN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alma Rose Tejeda opened the black backpack to find out what was
inside. She was looking for a name, address or phone number that
might help her locate the owner.
</P>
<P>
   Tejeda found the information, as well as a camera, some money
and a plastic bag filled with what looked like dirt. She considered
tasting it to find out what it was, but inexplicably pulled her
hand back.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, Tejeda, a customer service representative
with Washington state's Seattle-Tacoma airport's Lost and Found,
discovered the bag contained what was left of someone's Uncle
Charlie.
</P>
<P>
   The man's ashes were supposed to have been scattered at sea, but
had been left at the airport by a woman from the East Coast who had
lost her backpack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a dead person in my life. It still gives me
the chills,'' Tejeda said. ``But it always gives me a good feeling
to return something special.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Sea-Tac Lost and Found, which returns
approximately one-third of more than 12,000 found items each year,
will be on the receiving end of good news.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey, conducted by Michael Franz, of Washington State
University's small business development center, found Sea-Tac's
Lost and Found to be one of the best in the country at reuniting
frantic travelers with their glasses, purses, luggage _ and even
``Uncle Charlie.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington Works, which runs the Lost and Found, was pleasantly
surprised to find its two-year-old job-training site out-performing
its conventional counterparts at other airports surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Works, under a contract with the Port of Seattle,
uses the Lost and Found as a ``managed work site'' for people in
its Welfare-to-Wages program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping we were doing well, but we had no idea how we
stacked up, industry-wide,'' said Thomas Donlea, executive director
of the non-profit agency.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Works originally approached Franz for advice on how
to improve business practices at the Lost and Found. As part of
that process, Franz conducted a survey to see how Sea-Tac measured
up.
</P>
<P>
   The competition: Airports in Los Angeles, Portland, Minneapolis,
Miami, Dallas-Ft. Worth, Ft. Lauderdale and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Sea-Tac was found to provide the highest level of customer
service, to handle the highest volume of lost items, to put the
most energy into locating owners and returning items and to have
zero thefts or complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Works said the findings debunk myths about the work
ethic of employees who are on welfare, or who lack job experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't see the potential because of the stigma,'' said
Dennis Hatch, Sea-Tac Lost and Found's operations manager. ``Some
of the folks here who are offering our high level of service have
only been here for two months.''
</P>
<P>
   Tejeda, 35, has worked at the Lost and Found for nearly a year.
The part-time job helps the California native support her four
children and disabled husband.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to finding Washington Works, Tejeda had not held a job for
11 years. Now she has customer service skills, knowledge of
Windows, e-mail and the Internet _ and a lot more confidence.
</P>
<P>
   When Tejeda's stint at the Lost and Found ends next month, she
plans to finish school and get her GED.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very extra patient here about showing me
everything,'' Tejeda said. ``I love (this job). I enjoy every
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Encinas feels the same way.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, Encinas waited for someone to approach
her window at the Lost and Found _ tucked away up the stairs behind
the Continental Airlines counter, down the hall past cases
displaying the work of local glass artists and around the corner
from the Meditation Room.
</P>
<P>
   A red canvas case sat on Encinas' lap. It contained a fishing
pole, but no name or address. Encinas zipped the case up and
started entering the item into a computer database.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men always come back for their fishing poles,'' the
28-year-old said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the owners do come looking, but sometimes those in the
department have to do some detective work to find them.
</P>
<P>
   By tracing a credit card receipt number, Tejeda once located a
man who had lost a suitcase full of new clothes _ and $300 cash.
</P>
<P>
   The staffers don't accept any rewards, however. Not even for the
$8,747 recently returned to one traveler, or the 50-year-old
heirloom wedding band returned to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we do get lots of thank yous,'' Hatch said. ``Lots of
e-mails, phone calls ... it just feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   The office's back room is packed with items still to be
returned. A pile in one corner is the sad remains of things turned
in during May, about to be donated to non-profits to make space for
the 1,500 lost items expected in July.
</P>
<P>
   A framed John Elway poster crowns the donation pile. Around the
corner, a single, baby-sized white sandal sits alone in a cubby. A
dinosaur puppet lays next to a red squirt gun.
</P>
<P>
   Coats ha)5Y :} rW+1%m6mUr &QR; \6KX
</P>
</TEXT>
