news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TECH21 (COLUMN) _  &LR; Enough, for now, about security and privacy
issues _ this week let's relax and take a look at some recent
developments involving a device we use every time we sit down at
our computers: the monitor. One of my biggest disappointments about
the 21st century, at least in the technology arena, is that most of
us still have to look at CRTs. Years ago, I confidently predicted
that these hulking, flickering, energy-devouring dinosaurs would be
extinct by now, replaced by sleek LCD flat-panel displays if not
some newer and even better technology.
 &UR; COLUMN BY HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BIOSCOPE (COLUMN) _ &LR;  Robert Kay has a new twist to the old riddle
about the chicken and the egg. As chief executive of Origen
Therapeutics in Burlingame, Calif., Kay knows that birds begin life
as embryos, and he hopes to parlay that knowledge into a technique
that could change the future of chicken-kind.  &UR; COLUMN BY &LR; 
 &UR; TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CERUS _  &LR; Blood, the fluid of life, can also become the agent of
infection, as occurred in the early 1980s when thousands of people
were infected before blood banks knew how to screen transfusions
for HIV. Now a Concord, Calif., biotech firm is in the late stages
of testing a process that promises to nip future epidemics by
inactivating any virus or bacteria found in the blood _ even a new,
unknown pathogen.  &UR; BY TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; INVESTING (COLUMN) _  &LR; There isn't any magic behind successful
investing. You get there by building a list of suitable investment
candidates and picking the best prospects from it. What's suitable?
That depends on your style. Investors tend to fall into three
categories.  &UR; COLUMN BAY HARRY DOMASH &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
