<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDLIGHT </SLUG>
  
BC-REDLIGHT-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DRIVERS SEE RED AT LONG STOPLIGHTS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By Laura Trujillo(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the crowded intersection of Grand Avenue, Thomas Road and
27th Avenue, Lee Chase sees what a lingering red stoplight leads
to.
</P>
<P>
   There's a woman putting on mascara, a man eating a hamburger, a
teenager talking on a cell phone and a couple who appear to be
arguing. A guy in a Toyota has his windows unrolled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must not have air,'' Chase observes from the office of the
Ugly Duckling used car lot where he works.
</P>
<P>
   And when the light grows too long, and impatience too short, he
sees some drivers cut through his parking lot rather than wait.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the light {ndash} at one minute and 50 seconds during
rush hour - is one of the longest reds in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also true that red lights everywhere are getting
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic engineers say wider streets require longer light cycles.
So as the city grows, so do the red lights.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, many Chandler intersections had 50-second
waits; now they are 80. Where the wait was 30 seconds in the
mid-1960s in Phoenix, it's now 60 seconds. Lights along Grand
Avenue in Peoria now run up to a whopping three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The increase is not unique to this Valley of wide streets, lots
of left-hand turn lanes and even more cars. Across the nation,
engineers are lengthening traffic signals. In the past 30 years,
the length of red lights has doubled at many intersections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going on everywhere. Las Vegas is crazy with almost
three-minute reds at some spots,'' said Nazir Lalani, former
president of the International Traffic Engineers. ``As we widen
streets and go to the double left, unfortunately it drives up the
cycle and the red light.''
</P>
<P>
   Longer lights, engineers explain, can help move traffic more
efficiently. That's because with a longer cycle, you have a smaller
percentage of time devoted to the yellow (four seconds at some
intersections) or the overlapping reds (add another four seconds in
some places). Lalani points out that wider streets also require
more time for pedestrians to cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic engineers aren't sitting here trying to figure out
ways to make the red lights longer,'' said Lalani, a traffic
engineer in Ventura, Calif. ``But doing the mathematics requires
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many cities increase traffic light times during rush hour. So
while you might wait 60 seconds at an intersection around noon, you
could wait 80 seconds during the evening commute.
</P>
<P>
   Although some say the longer red lights encourage people to run
the yellow or the red, and Phoenix leads the nation in red-light
accidents, Alberto Gutier of the Governor's Office of Highway
Safety says the longer reds really do make streets safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives people more time to cross these wide streets,'' he
said, ``and if it helps move traffic, it's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Try explaining that to Bryan Lubash as he waits in his Chevrolet
Cavalier delivery car, air-conditioner blasting, at a Mesa
intersection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it feels like you can wait forever,'' said Lubash,
29, a driver for Home Office Express. He can check his maps, his
delivery schedule and make a phone call before many of the lights
change during his morning route.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the longest waits occur at the intersections of small
streets with bigger ones. The small streets get the red light 90
percent of the time, said Jerry Whelpley, Glendale's traffic signal
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no matter what you do, they all say it's way too long,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the guy who sees the cup as half-full.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to remember, if your red is longer, that means
someone's green is longer,'' pointed out Steve Ramsey, signal
systems analyst for Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Romero, who drives Grand Avenue almost daily taking her
mother to doctor's appointments or on errands, says she tries to
remind herself of that when she's stopped at a long red light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to be ready for it,'' the 41-year-old from Surprise
said. ``I can check out all the radio stations. I don't have a
phone so that's it. You just wait. Unless the train comes, then
forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix and state traffic engineers agree that the triple
intersections along Grand Avenue are bad. The Arizona Department of
Transportation is designing bridges to get rid of the triple
intersections starting in 2003, which would cut red lights by
almost one minute in some spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just no way around it,'' said Matt Burdick, an ADOT
spokesman, ``when you have traffic from six ways, you're going to
wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Ugly Ducking, Chase watches the traffic and knows
he'll soon be in it.
</P>
<P>
   But the car salesman maintains a sort of Zenlike attitude about
it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just turn on the talk radio,'' he said. ``And I figure it's
another moment I can sit back and enjoy my time.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Laura.Trujillo(a)Arizona
</P>
<P>
   Republic.com or (602)444-8891.
</P>
</TEXT>
