<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-09 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7477 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-09 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS SITTING PRETTY AT BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This is not where the Mariners figured to be, sitting
in first place at the All-Star break, owning a three-game lead in
the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland was supposed to be the team to beat. Texas was the
two-time defending West champion.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle? Just another team with dreams.
</P>
<P>
   But with the first half of the 2000 season in the books, Seattle
has had one dreamy ride. The Mariners' 2-0 victory over the Los
Angeles Dodgers Sunday at Safeco Field left them with a 51-35
record, 16 games over .500. Only Atlanta and the Chicago White Sox
have more wins.
</P>
<P>
   It should, perhaps, be a team like the Dodgers, who have spent
$30 million more on payroll than have the Mariners, who should own
this lofty perch. Not a chance. For all their big market moxie, the
Dodgers don't have what the Mariners have _ all cylinders firing.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any other team I've ever had,'' manager Lou Piniella
said, ``this team is playing up to its potential. We're playing as
well as we can play.''
</P>
<P>
   High praise, coming from a manager who took another
under-appreciated team, the 1990 Reds, and guided them to a World
Series title. Until now, Piniella wasn't sure he'd have another
team able to play the kind of cohesive baseball that makes a
contender into a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about the type of players I have and the type of
coaches I have,'' Piniella said. ``They make my job relatively
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case Sunday. Starter Jamie Moyer threw seven
shutout innings. Catcher Joe Oliver hammered an 0-2 fastball from
Chan Ho Park out to left field for a 2-0 lead in the second inning,
and that was all the Mariners would need.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptional defense from second baseman Mark McLemore and
shortstop Carlos Guillen smoothed whatever bumps were in the road
for Moyer and the M's bullpen. Jose Paniagua threw a 1-2-3 eighth
inning without letting the Dodgers get the ball out of the infield,
and closer Kazuhiro Sasaki ran his streak of consecutive saves to
nine with a perfect ninth.
</P>
<P>
   That final inning started with one of the best defensive plays
of the season _ Guillen, who hasn't played shortstop regularly in
three years _ going to the deepest part of short to snare a ball
from Eric Karros. Guillen's long throw, a certified jaw-dropper,
nailed Karros at first as the crowd of 45,251 erupted.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many English words Sasaki has mastered in his time
in Seattle, but he saved one for Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great!'' Sasaki said, nodding his head up and down in obvious
delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge play,'' Sasaki said through interpreter Allen
Turner. ``There's no way to know he's going to make that play. He
got me fired up. He got the team fired up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Guillen doesn't get that out, who knows what happens next?
That turned everything around for us.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, did Oliver, who has been rock-steady since being forced
into the role of everyday starting catcher with injuries to Dan
Wilson and Tom Lampkin. He had three hits, the only hits allowed by
Park in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver doubled in the fifth and singled in the seventh, both on
curves. But it was what he did to an 0-2 fastball in the second
inning that riled Park.
</P>
<P>
   Batting after David Bell's sinking liner had been dropped in
right field, Oliver hit his third homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed with one pitch and that one pitch made me a loser,''
Park said. ``That guy (Oliver) was the best hitter in the world
today. I threw an 0-2 fastball for a home run and it cost me the
game. That's a very hard-luck loss for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer is now 8-3 after dominating the Dodgers. He allowed seven
hits in seven innings, but always got the key pitch when he needed
it. With two on and one out in the fifth, Moyer got Jim Leyritz to
ground into a double play. With one on and one out in the fifth,
Moyer induced another double-play grounder.
</P>
<P>
   The best bit of pitching for Moyer came in the sixth after a
bunt single by rookie Mike Metcalf _ his first big-league hit _ and
a single to center by Adrian Beltre put men at first and second
with no one out and the 3-4-5 spots in the order due up.
</P>
<P>
   But Shawn Green flew out to left, Gary Sheffield took a called
third strike and Eric Karros popped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That backdoor cutter Jamie threw Sheffield to strike him out
was something else,'' Oliver said. ``There aren't too many in
baseball who can put a good swing on that pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer said the shutout was of relatively little importance to
him. The crucial accomplishment was winning and getting to the
break with a three-game lead in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a pretty good first half,'' Moyer said. ``It's not
because of any one guy. Last year, everybody contributed, but not
all at once. This year, we're all contributing now. It's been
everybody working hard and getting the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being chased, and since I've been here, we've always
been in the position of being the chaser. Now we've got to work
harder to get where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a manager.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
