<HEADLINE>
NEW LEAGUE SHOULD HELP PROPEL WOMEN'S SOCCER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- After the Summer Olympics in Sydney ends in
October, U.S. stars Mia Hamm, Brandi Chastain, Michelle Akers and
Julie Foudy will move forward in new uniforms with new logos and
try to clear the final hurdle for women's soccer in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Olympic gold medal victory in Atlanta, the 1999 Women's
World Cup title at the Rose Bowl, all the victory tours, television
appearances, commercial endorsements and public appearances were
geared toward the future. More specifically, the team's success has
led to the proposed launch of the finest and most competitive
women's professional soccer league in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In April, John S. Hendricks announced preliminary funding of $40
million to launch the Women's United Soccer Association (WUSA) next
April with eight franchises and commitments from each of the 20
U.S. women who captured the World Cup title a year ago today at the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Cable companies Time-Warner, Cox and Comcast are the big
backers. In May, Major League Soccer agreed to a comprehensive
cooperation agreement that provides a sharing of marketing and
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   MLS first planned to launch its own women's league to compete
against the WUSA. But after talks with the U.S. Soccer Federation,
the two sides felt it served the sport's best interest to work
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have seen from other sports, having two leagues probably
is not what is best for the game and its growth,'' said veteran
national team member Carla Overbeck. ``We, as players, are ecstatic
about the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in both MLS and the WUSA agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's equal value to both sides in this agreement,''
Hendricks said.
</P>
<P>
   MLS commissioner Don Garber said: ``We're up against a fractured
market already. We both face challenges ahead, and together we can
achieve a whole lot more than if we were to work independently.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchises in Washington, D.C.; Atlanta; New York; Boston;
Orlando; Philadelphia; San Diego, and San Francisco will open the
inaugural season. The headliners include Hamm (Washington, D.C.),
Chastain (San Francisco), Kristine Lilly (Boston), Tiffeny Milbrett
(New York), Lorrie Fair (Philadelphia), Akers (Orlando), Briana
Scurry (Atlanta) and Foudy (San Diego).
</P>
<P>
   Acting WUSA commissioner Tony DiCicco, coach of the '96 gold
medalists and last year's world champions, is hoping to sign 16
big-name foreigners before the Olympics. Then it will be just six
months until the league makes its debut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
