</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SHUT OUT YANKEES, 2-0 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Hampton thinks Mike Piazza is the toughest
player on the Mets, and he was shocked when Piazza was beaned by
Roger Clemens on Saturday night. The Mets are still furious over
the incident, but Hampton promised not to initiate any disturbances
when he started on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets did not say it, but they had plenty to lose if Hampton
touched anything off. The Mets needed a victory, not a beanball
war, and Hampton gave them their best chance for that. He stayed
out of trouble and worked seven shutout innings as the Mets beat
the Yankees, 2-0, for their only victory in this four-game subway
series.
</P>
<P>
   If Piazza is the toughest Met, Hampton might be the
second-toughest. The thought of giving in to hitters disgusts him,
and he throws his body around the field with abandon. But like
Piazza on Saturday, Hampton was forced to leave this game with an
injury. He sustained a muscle cramp in his left forearm and was
replaced by Armando Benitez before throwing his first pitch of the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez walked the first hitter he faced, Jose Vizcaino, then
struck out Chuck Knoblauch as Todd Pratt, Piazza's replacement,
threw out Vizcaino trying to steal. It was Knoblauch's first
strikeout since June 24, and Pratt's second throwout of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez struck out Derek Jeter to end the eighth. He got Felix
Jose to bounce to first with two men on to end the game for his
19th save, and first of two innings.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who improved to 9-5, was hardly a consideration for the
All-Star team; a 2-4 start in which he posted a 6.52 earned-run
average took care of that. But in his last 12 starts, he has been
one of the majors' best pitchers, going 7-1 with a 1.87 era.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Zeile has been among the most reliable Mets hitters this
year, and he has been hot lately, hitting .353 since the start of
the Mets-Braves series on June 29. That is also what Zeile was
hitting in his career off Andy Pettitte before Sunday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile was the first batter in the fourth inning, and he sliced a
ball to right field. On Friday night, Paul O'Neill had made a
game-saving catch in nearly the same spot when he planted himself
under a high fly by Derek Bell, leaped straight up and robbed Bell
of a homer in the Yankees' 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile's hit was more of a line drive, and O'Neill first turned
to his left in pursuit. He reversed himself at the warning track
and jumped to his right, but the ball made it into the bullpen
safely for a home run, Zeile's 14th. O'Neill slapped the plexiglass
with his glove in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored their next run in the seventh, without getting a
hit. Pratt _ who is 0 for 28 since June 2 _ led off with a walk.
Hampton sacrificed him to second, and when Jeff Nelson came in to
relieve Pettitte, a wild pitch brought Pratt to third. Melvin Mora
scored him with a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte (9-5) worked six and a third innings, allowing two runs
on five hits and four walks. Like Hampton, he played it straight.
The crowd stirred in the fourth inning when Pettitte buzzed a pitch
near Robin Ventura's knees, but there were no other hints of
tension.
</P>
<P>
   That was surprising, given the tenor of the comments before the
game. The Mets (48-38) made no secret of their disgust at what they
perceived to be Clemens' deliberate attempt to drill Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Piazza's very important to our organization,'' General
Manager Steve Phillips said. ``To jeopardize his career also
jeopardizes the well-being of the Mets.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza did not seem certain another incident could be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is the end of this,'' he said. ``I don't
know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   As Piazza watched from the dugout, this is what happened:
Hampton kept the game, and the Yankees, under control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
